<HEADLINE>Focal point around the fireside</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LUCY LOCKHART</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>978321544</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
With the opening of a new fireside design showroom in Glasgow, Lucy
Lockhart looks at the latest range of styles available.
SATURDAY sees the official opening of Hestia Fireside Design at 96
Great Western Road, Glasgow. Customers visiting the superb display of 27
custom-made mantelpieces will be offered -- on Saturday and Sunday -- a
celebratory glass of wine to sip as they browse among the broad range of
inspirational ideas on view, which will disappoint no-one.
From the era of the sixties and seventies when ''domestic vandalism''
was rife and period features were systematically ripped out of so many
houses, things have turned full circle, with people now anxious to
reinstate fine craftsmanship back into their homes.
While the upsurge in the installation of central heating encouraged
the removal or closing up of fireplaces at this time, happily, it was a
trend which didn't last. Over the past decade or so, more people in
Britain have decided that a fire and surrounding mantelpiece makes an
unsurpassable focal point in a room. Advancing technology has played an
important part, with gas coal effect fires now highly efficient in many
cases, as well as looking convincingly like the real thing.
Eight years ago, Colin Greig opened his first branch of Hestia
Fireside Design at 4 South Trinity Road, Edinburgh, followed two years
on by a second branch at 90 Comiston Road in the capital. Now, a third
showroom has seen him expand into Glasgow, traditionally a city which
appreciates style, good design and quality.
''All our mantelpieces are custom-made,'' explained Mr Greig. ''We
have our own craftsmen in Edinburgh. If someone wants a mantel two
inches smaller, it takes us exactly the same amount of time to make as a
larger one, it costs no extra. In many places, they either can't do it
because everything is mass produced, or customers pay an extra 15%-20%
just to change it by a couple of inches. To us it makes no difference,
we offer a flexible, custom-made service.''
Similar flexibility is available in many different ways. If you see a
mantel in limed oak, for example, and would prefer it in mahogany,
perhaps without one or two of the design features, it can be done. The
woods used by Hestia are pine, mahogany and oak, and apparently the
last, which is also the most expensive, is tops in popularity.
''We have copied designs from photographs people have brought to us,''
explains Colin Greig, pointing to a superb example in carved wood, ''and
we can make sure that details like the top of the mantelpiece being
broad enough to take a lamp, are looked after. We use real wood,'' he
adds, ''many people use MDF and so on, but you can see the difference in
our models, in the graining of the wood and how it feels to the touch.
They do look beautiful when they're installed, they really enhance a
room.''
Hestia also imports its marble direct from Portugal, and holds large
stocks for its own use, often in unusual colours rarely seen elsewhere.
''We have marble masons working for us, and again we can make it to just
the dimensions required,'' says Mr Greig, ''there's no limit to what we
can offer. We do try hard to be completely different.''
He points to a marble fireplace with beautifully sculpted angles,
explaining: ''Most people can't do that. Quality is what we are about,
that is our sector of the market; with our quality of materials and
workmanship we can't compete at the bottom end of the market, but in
comparison with the top end we are competitive with others in the field,
but we do think our quality is exceptional.''
Certainly the range of styles and designs on display is excellent, it
would be unusual for almost anyone not to find their dream come true
here: ''There must be about 1500 to 2000 combinations feasible from what
we have on show,'' comments Colin Greig. ''Verine are our main gas fire
suppliers, and we use Stovax for the tiles, but everything else, all the
mantels, we make ourselves.''
In terms of design and period, the company finds its customers' tastes
are broad, with both mature and younger buyers united in their desire to
restore properties to their original glory.
''We've found over the years that customers come in with their own
ideas of what they want, but once they've had a look around, they
frequently end up changing their minds and buying something that they
see,'' smiles Mr Greig.
Convector boxes are very efficient fires. ''Most people have central
heating now and don't want a fire as a complete central heater point,''
says Colin Greig. ''Usually people want a fire as a focal point with
some heat, but we always ask customers what it is they want the fire to
do, then advise them accordingly.''
Easy to install
ONCE upon a time, a house without a chimney meant that installing a
coal-effect gas fire was impossible unless there was an outside wall to
take a balanced flue.
Now, however, Colin Greig explains: ''We can put a fireplace into any
house, using a Power Flue -- all our working fireplaces in the Glasgow
showroom use this method -- fumes are ducted through the back of the
fire, and drawn out by fan to the outdoors.''
Another innovative idea is Switch Craft, a system which allows a gas
fire to be lit electronically, by a remote switch.
From start to finish, ordering to fitting takes between one and three
weeks, according to Mr Greig, and six months' interest-free credit is
available, with a 20% deposit. The new showroom is open Monday to Friday
between 9am and 5.30pm; Saturday 9am to 5pm and Sunday 12 noon to 5pm.
</TEXT>
