<HEADLINE>A question of first or foremost</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEREK DOUGLAS, CHIEF RUGBY WRITER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>48</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>978321546</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Pretoria
SCOTLAND'S rugby management face a strategic decision in the next few
days as the clock ticks down to their Rugby World Cup opener against
Ivory Coast next Friday.
Should they pick the best side for all of the pool games -- against
Ivory Coast, Tonga, and France -- or should they rest as many of the
front-line players as they think circumstances allow.
In all likelihood, the management have already made up their minds,
but yesterday, team manager Duncan Paterson was still weighing up the
situation.
''There are arguments both ways, especially when one takes into
account the possibility of injuries.''
The easiest game in Scotland's section will be against the Ivory
Coast, who recently lost 97-7 to Northern Transvaal and who,
incidentally, staged a reception for the Scots on Wednesday night.
It will be of the utmost importance that the Scots get their campaign
underway with a convincing display against the Ivorians. The top players
therefore will be on parade at the Rustenburg opener. Within the space
of nine days, Scotland must play Tonga and France.
Ideally, Scotland would wish to field the first-choice XV on each
occasion, but three international matches within the space of just more
than a week is a tough schedule for any side, let alone one like
Scotland where player resources do not run that deep.
At the inaugural World Cup in 1987, the Scottish strategy was to go
with the first-choice players. The result then was a quarter-final exit
at the hands of the All Blacks.
In 1991, the Scots mixed and matched, choosing a blend of first and
second string players where appropriate. The outcome then was a
semi-final defeat by England and a third/fourth place play-off, again
against New Zealand.
One player who has a particular interest in the strategy which the
management adopt out here in Pretoria is the Edinburgh Academical lock,
Jeremy Richardson. Now 32, he was a member of the 1987 World Cup squad
but returned from New Zealand without having played a game.
Richardson, who had to wait until November last year for his first
full cap, against South Africa, said yesterday: ''The thing about 1987
was that there were five individuals in the party who did not play. One
of those included Roger Baird. The last time he had been out in New
Zealand was with the British Lions. I was one of the youngest in the
group, and although I was disappointed it was much worse for the likes
of Roger.
''It was the late Bob Munro, the team manager, who said that, with
hindsight, it had been a mistake not to give all the players a game.
''From my perspective, I am hoping that this time they will give
everybody a run.''
Richardson adds that, having been involved in 1987 and not making the
1991 squad, the odds must have been stacked against him re-appearing for
this World Cup.
''But what it comes down to is the old David Sole adage about miles on
the clock and not age that truly matters. I have not been involved in
international rugby and so I have not been taking the physical
hammerings like a lot of the guys who have been involved all the time.''
* THE World Cup referees are ready to revolt if the organisers don't
change their minds on a new lineout ruling. As the 26 officials left
yesterday to fly to the Republic, they were ready for a showdown with
the law makers tomorrow.
The referees have been instructed to ban the step out of the lineout,
and support of the jumper even though the two practices have become
commonplace around the world. But the referees, led by the 1991 World
Cup final official Derek Bevan, want the tournament organisers to allow
players to support the jumpers.
</TEXT>
