<HEADLINE>Praise for Miller as Aitken takes over</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GRAEME SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>48</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>978321548</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ROY Aitken was last night appointed manager of Aberdeen -- and
immediately thanked the man he replaced, Willie Miller, for giving him
the opportunity to further his career at Pittodrie.
The announcement was made as Aberdeen face two of the most important
games in their 92-year history, games which will determine if they are
demoted from top-flight football for the first time.
The appointment of Aitken will be a major boost to the players, who
have shown considerable commitment to him during his 12 weeks as
caretaker manager, and to the fans who have been eager to see his
position made permanent.
Aitken took over the reins as Aberdeen propped up the premier
division, but he successfully guided them off the bottom with the reward
of an opportunity to avoid relegation in a two-leg play-off against
Dunfermline, at home on Sunday and away on Thursday.
After his appointment Aitken said he was looking no further than these
two games and any changes which might be necessary in the playing or
backroom staff would not be considered until after the relegation issue
had been settled.
''The situation we are in is far too important to have any outside
influences or outside distractions. The main hurdle is getting through
these two games,'' he said.
Aitken said he believed that after easing his way out of the playing
side into the coaching side he was now ready to manage a top club. ''I
have taken a gradual route into it and I have to thank Willie Miller for
having the faith to bring me to a club of the calibre of Aberdeen. At
that time I was looking to get into the coaching side on a more regular
basis, and when he left he encouraged me to give it my best shot and
that is what I have done.''
Announcing the appointment, Aberdeen chairman Ian Donald said: ''Over
the past few critical weeks Roy has demonstrated that he has the
confidence and commitment of the playing staff to make the Dons a major
force in Scottish football.
''The directors believe his appointment will be welcomed throughout
the club and will be warmly received by our fans with whom he has
quickly established his own personal rapport.''
Aitken praised the fans for their reponse during the difficult period
for the club. ''I have said for the past six or eight weeks there has
been a great response from everyone concerned with the club and it shows
the commitment there is among the fans, the players, everyone.
''I am just delighted to get the job. I am very proud to have been
given my first management role with a club of the stature and potential
of the Dons.
''I'm confident we can realise this potential in the seasons ahead,
especially given the commitment and desire shown by the players in
recent games.
''The fans, who displayed their loyalty and backing at a time when we
needed it most, have been inspirational and have provided a positive
environment for future success.
''I said when I arrived my ambition was to spend a long time here and
I think the fans know what I will put into the job. I think they realise
I am someone who will give it his best shot.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
