<HEADLINE>Let's put Hampden in with a final shout</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JIM REYNOLDS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>48</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321549</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND'S football fans will be given the opportunity to contribute
to the history of the game by helping to build the final phase of
Hampden Park -- the new South Stand which will hold 17,500 and bring the
capacity of the ground to around 53,000.
The cost of building the stand will be #18m and more than half of that
money is now in place. The dream is a Hampden which will be among the
great stadiums in Europe, and that means re-creating the spirit of those
pioneers of almost 100 years ago, who built the biggest and most
technically advanced stadium in the world.
Launching a debenture scheme yesterday, National Stadium director
Austin Reilly said: ''The concept of debenture initiatives is not new,
with successful projects already completed in football and rugby, but
here is a truly unique project where the fans can play a vital and very
public role in the further development of Scotland's national football
stadium.
''Queen's Park, the SFA, the Scottish League, the Football Trust, and
local and national government are all actively behind the redevelopment
plans and a positive reaction to the debenture scheme will give us the
opportunity to provide the country with a football stadium to match the
best in Europe.
''We are asking the fans to register in large numbers to demonstrate
their support. At the moment, we do not know what the cost will be, but
after a period, we will approach a number of the fans to seek their
views on various aspects. They will be consulted on cost, where the
debenture seats will be, and what they will expect in terms of
facilities.''
I understand, however, that when it comes down to settling on the
cost, fans will be asked to pay between #600 and #1000.
While many will want to take advantage of the scheme, it is worth
considering that Scottish football fans have already forked out plenty
of cash on their clubs.
The biggest supports follow Rangers, Celtic, Hearts and Aberdeen.
Rangers fans have already been asked for up to #399 each for next season
as part of their ''Ready For The Future'' campaign, Celtic have recently
had a share issue, Aberdeen are considering the same, while Hearts have
also asked their fans to put their hands in their pockets.
A major advertising campaign will be launched today which will promote
the pre-registration period. Fans can also call the Hampden Hotline
freephone number 0800 585498.
Reilly said: ''There will be only a limited number of debenture seats
available through the scheme and, with that in mind, we are asking
people to pre-register an interest so that we can provide them with a
free registration pack containing all the relevant details.''
The Hampden debenture will guarantee the right to tickets for all
ventures at the ground -- international matches, Scottish and League Cup
matches, concerts, and exhibitions.
Jim Farry, chief executive of the SFA, said: ''We are aiming to raise
#5m from fans and businesses and we are absolutely certain demand will
exceed supply. We are very confident and optimistic about this.''
''There are comparisons between this scheme and the one at
Murrayfield, but they are not the same. At Murrayfield the fans were
asked to come in right at the start of re-building, but we have already
completed two-thirds of the work at Hampden.''
The Murrayfield debenture scheme has already raised #32m, but those
who support club rugby do not have anything like the outlay of their
football counterparts. It does not cost much to follow rugby on a weekly
basis, so the fans of the oval ball game had money to spend on something
special, like a guarantee of a seat at the super new Murrayfield.
Also for major rugby internationals, Murrayfield is always a 67,500
sell out. Unfortunately, the same cannot be said for football at
Hampden.
However, the football authorities have to be applauded for their
thinking and everyone should hope that the Hampden plan is a success.
After all it is the national stadium and football is the national sport.
Said Farry: ''The SFA's ambition is that Hampden, when completed, will
be on the very exclusive UEFA list of five-star stadiums. If you are on
that then you can host all of their major finals.''
To gain a UEFA five-star listing, the stadium must have a helipad, an
in-house hospital, and secure underground parking for when heads of
state and other dignitaries attend events.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
