<HEADLINE>Rangers forced to be patient</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES TRAYNOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>48</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321550</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RANGERS would like nothing better than to announce that both Paul
Gascoigne and Florin Raducioiu will sign on before this weekend is over,
but the Ibrox club continue to be frustrated in their bold and ambitious
attempts to piece together a side capable of being Champions' League
contenders.
Walter Smith was back in Rome on Wednesday trying to bring the #4.5m
transfer of Gascoigne from Lazio to Rangers closer to reality, but the
player's arrival in Glasgow is not imminent. The same applies to the
Romanian, Raducioiu.
Rangers are still favourites to sign Gascoigne although contrary to
reports he has not resolved his differences with Lazio. It is believed
the player is seeking a #1m settlement for the two years left on his
contract with the Italian club. His agents, Mel Stein and Len Lazarus,
have been working towards that. I understand Lazio have offered
#300,000.
It is my information that Lazio are still in the mood to haggle over
the amount for a player who has given them little productivity because
of long-term injury. Lazio have the power to banish Gascoigne to the
reserves for the rest of his contract.
Last night the player failed to turn up for a training match against
Tuscan side Grosseto ahead of Sunday's Serie A action. Lazio coach
Zdenek Zeman said: ''The club may take disciplinary action, but I want
to talk with him first.''
Smith and his right-hand man, Archie Knox, have been checking
Raducioiu since they watched him play for Romania in the World Cup
finals. Espanol want #2.5m for 25-year-old Raducioiu.
Rangers might run into difficulty in trying to sign another another
player from outwith the European Community. Currently all 10 work
permits allocated to Scottish football are in use -- no club can have
more than two -- and Scottish League secretary Peter Donald said
yesterday: ''It would seem Rangers would have to rely on other clubs, or
even themselves, to release a current holder of a work permit. Even then
they would not necessarily be guaranteed first place if another club
have ambitions of bringing in a non-European Community player.''
The 10 players holding permits are Rudi Vata (Celtic), Jerren Nixon
and Gordan Petric (both Dundee United), Dragoje Lekovic (Kilmarnock),
Tony Rougier (Raith Rovers), Dusan Vrto (Dundee), Arnold Dwarika (East
Fife), Henry Stoute and Dave Alleyne (both Meadowbank Thistle), and of
course Rangers' own Alexei Mikhailichenko.
It is in Rangers' favour that Nixon has been put up for sale and
Petric is not certain to relish life in the first division, but it would
be most frustrating for the Ibrox side if they were to have their
attempt to bring talent into Scottish football blocked because of East
Fife or Meadowbank.
It can be assumed that neither Smith nor Rangers' chairman David
Murray would have gone as far as to say they are willing to meet
Espanol's price for Raducioiu unless they were confident of gaining a
permit. It could be they are waiting until July when Mikhailichenko will
have worked here four years and thus be exempt.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
