<HEADLINE>First battle is against jet-lag</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAMON QUIGLEY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>47</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>978321554</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Hiroshima
SCOTLAND may never quite have managed to conquer the world in a
footballing sense, but the national team will deserve no little praise
if they can recuperate quickly enough from the rigours of a 21-hour
journey to Japan to win the Kirin Cup.
Craig Brown's squad landed in Hiroshima last night, briefly parted
from the hampers containing the team kit, but in the end the pool
settled well in what for most is an uncharted territory.
There has been vociferous criticism of the whole event from those at
home who fail to see what benefit can possibly be derived from taking,
in effect, a skeleton group to the Far East. Certainly, the original
notion that this trip would provide useful match practice ahead of the
European Championship qualifying match against the Faroe Islands on June
7, has long since been discredited due to the withdrawal of most of our
leading players.
Yet the manager insists that it remains a worthwhile exercise.
''Everything is OK. We had a good flight over and now that we have had a
nice meal the players are just relaxing and going for an early night,''
said Brown.
''I never had any qualms about the travelling involved, even though
some people had their doubts. Other countries do it because it's part
and parcel of the modern game. I also spoke to Gary Lineker before we
came here and he assured me that going to Japan would be no problem. The
lads will take a day to adjust and then they'll be ready for action.''
While the only man absolutely guaranteed to start Sunday's opener
against Japan is Jim Leighton, who has been made captain, his Hibs
colleague Darren Jackson must also be regarded as a banker selection for
Brown. He played with distinction against both Russia and San Marino in
Scotland's last two matches despite being asked to perform relatively
thankless tasks.
It seems unlikely that he will be left out, so the real question is
whether he will be joined in attack by Chelsea's John Spencer or John
Robertson, so often a rival of Jackson's when he has played for Hearts
in Edinburgh derbies.
Robertson gives every impression that he is more than ready to try to
resurrect an international career which had seemed in terminal decline.
''I have got the chance to represent my country again by coming here
and if I do get to play then it will be what I have been craving for the
last two years,'' said Robertson, whose previous appearance was against
Estonia in 1993 when he received his eleventh cap.
''Now the manager has given me that chance, if I am selected for
either Sunday's game or the game against Equador on Wednesday, then it
is up to me to try to do well.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
