<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000014</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000014</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>United front is under pressure</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>47</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321558</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MANCHESTER United's FA Cup final preparations were rocked for the
second time in two days yesterday when winger Andrei Kanchelskis
announced that he could no longer play for Alex Ferguson.
After speculation that Manchester City had put Ferguson's assistant,
Brian Kidd, at the top of their wanted list to replace sacked boss Brian
Horton, Kanchelskis declared that he must leave United.
The Ukrainian has not featured in the United team since returning from
international duty last month suffering from a mystery stomach problem.
''Andrei loves the club, the players and the fans, but he cannot work
with the manager,'' said his agent, Grigory Esaylenko. ''It's a personal
thing, man to man, and his heart is not in it. He asks every day if he
can leave, but the manager says no. It is not a good situation.''
Ferguson was upset that the story had broken so close to the cup
final, after feeling that he had made his peace with Kanchelskis -- ''I
must say he's picked the right time, hasn't he?
''We spoke to him and his agent last week, and I thought we'd thrashed
it out.''
Ferguson clearly does not want Kanchelskis to leave, but he is in no
mood to cause an early confrontation with the player, who will join up
with the rest of the United party before tomorrow's game.
''I'm off on holiday next week and we'll wait and see what happens
over the summer,'' Ferguson added. ''Andrei is very much in my plans for
the future of Manchester United.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000015</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000015</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Airdrie will be all dressed up for the cup final</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES TRAYNOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>47</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>978321559</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CELTIC flew off to Milan to begin their Tennents Scottish Cup final
build-up, but it was business as usual for their opponents, Airdrie, who
were pounding a familiar beat in Strathclyde Park yesterday, taking time
out to show off their new strip which will be worn for the first time in
the final a week tomorrow.
The club can dress them up as much as they like, but underneath the
new rig-outs nothing will have changed. The same players who took
Airdrie to success in the B&amp;Q Cup and who almost managed a play-off
place in the first division championship race will be on duty at Hampden
next week, determined to go one better than the last time they played a
cup final at the national stadium.
They lost 2-1 to Rangers in the '92 final, which remains as the
biggest match in which any of the Airdrie players had been involved. In
fact, it was too much for some of them and yesterday Jimmy Boyle, a
veteran of Hampden, having played there for Queen's Park in 142
consecutive games, admitted the team did not go into the final equipped
with enough self-belief.
''We went into the game against Rangers maybe thinking that we
wouldn't really win,'' he said. ''But it won't be like that this time.
''I remember I was very nervous, but I am now one of six Airdrie
players who have played in a Scottish Cup final, while Celtic could have
four at the most. I think the experience of those who have been there
before could be vital.''
Boyle is a product of the Celtic Boys' Club system, and while it would
not have been difficult to convince his famly to support Airdrie against
Rangers, he has had to work harder this time. However, his brother
Stephen -- ''he's a Celtic fan'' -- has agreed to sit in the Airdrie
section of the stadium next week.
Apart from Boyle, Jimmy Sandison, John Martin, Alan Lawrence, Andy
Smith, and Sandy Stewart are survivors from the last final. Celtic's Pat
Bonner, Tommy Boyd -- while with Motherwell -- Andy Walker and Paul
McStay all played in finals. Peter Grant has also appeared in a cup
final, but it is not known yet whether or not he will recover from
injury in time to play against Airdrie.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000016</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000016</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Gloucester showdown</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>47</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321560</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GLOUCESTERSHIRE, the surprise package of the season so far, face a
Benson and Hedges Cup showdown with arch rivals Somerset. Jack Russell's
team were 50-1 outsiders for the competition a month ago, but they won
all five group games to guarantee a home draw in the quarter-finals --
and their reward could hardly be more appealing.
Gloucestershire have already beaten their West Country neighbours in a
Sunday League fixture at Taunton. And the atmosphere in Bristol on
quarter-final day -- Tuesday, May 30 -- should be electrifying.
Last year's cup runners-up Worcestershire face a tough trip to
Headingley where they have already lost in the competition once this
season. Yorkshire beat them by six wickets there last month, despite a
century from Graeme Hick, on their way to topping Group B.
''They are the one team to have beaten us in one-day cricket so far
this season,'' said Worcestershire coach David Houghton. ''I would have
preferred us to play someone from a different group but if we perform to
our potential we should be more than a match for them.''
Kent, who have won nothing since lifting both the Benson and Hedges
Cup and county championship in 1978, have been drawn at home to
Middlesex. The other quarter-final sees Lancashire take on
Nottinghamshire at Old Trafford.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000017</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000017</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Olympic dream is over</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ELSPETH BURNSIDE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>46</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321561</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EUAN Stewart has joined the list of dissatisfied Scottish swimmers and
has abandoned plans to try to fulfil an Olympic dream in Atlanta next
summer.
The 25-year-old from Dundee, who joined the City of Glasgow team as a
full-timer at the start of this season, said: ''Nothing has gone right
for me recently and I've had enough. It's unlikely that I'll be back.''
Stewart, the Scottish butterfly champion, blames lack of support from
within Scottish swimming as the reason behind his decision to quit.
''It's diabolical,'' he claimed. ''I was turned down for a Sports Aid
grant and was so hard up that I had to survive on ham sandwiches at a
recent meet in Leeds.''
He had hoped that the switch to Glasgow would enhance his prospects,
but he swam poorly at last month's Multi-Nations Tournament in
Edinburgh. Disheartened, he pulled out of the following week's European
championship trials.
Still living in Glasgow, he has now started applying for jobs, and
admitted: ''It's unlikely that I'll return to swimming.''
</TEXT>
