<HEADLINE>Hobson's choice is favourite</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DOUG GILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>46</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321563</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE annual season of masochism and machismo, otherwise known as the
Isle of Jura Scottish Peaks Race, has opened.
A total of 51 yachts was mustered at Oban last night for the world's
largest race of its kind. At noon today they launch a Hebridean odyssey
which will carry them some 160 miles, via Mull, Jura, and Arran, to the
finish at Troon Marina.
Last year's Class 2 (for monohulls) winning skipper, Ross Hobson, is
tipped to win overall, having stepped up to an F40 catamaran, Fingers
Crossed. His biggest rival may be Curly Mills, whose Antigua Cat, Dilly
Dream, has Dr Findlay, aka David Rintoul, as a crewman, raising funds
for Amnesty International.
Class 2 favourite is Eos, a 51-foot Beneteau, whose crew includes
Round the World race skipper Paul Jeffes, one of the consultants on
Scotland's Largs-based Admiral's Cup bid.
Landfall in Ayrshire is at the mercy of wind, weather, and tide -- and
the ability of each crew's two athletes to negotiate nearly 60 miles of
mountain running and some 11,000 feet of ascent and descent -- often
while recovering from sea sickness.
The athletes face ascents of Ben More (22 miles/966 metres), the Paps
of Jura (18/784), and Goat Fell (18/874) -- their sole reward being a
plaque and a few drams of sustenance from the sponsors, Whyte and
Mackay.
</TEXT>
