<HEADLINE>Leader Mitchell to the Tour's defence</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>46</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321566</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LONDONER Peter Mitchell shot a six-under-par 66 to lead the field at
the Spanish Open in Madrid yesterday -- and then spoke out in defence of
the European Tour.
Seve Ballesteros (70), Jose Maria Olazabal (73) and Colin Montgomerie
(70), with backing from Nick Faldo in the United States, have condemned
the European Tour as having too many players and lacking quality. But
Mitchell, eighteenth in the order of merit last year, disagrees.
''Everybody has their own point of view,'' he said. ''It's okay for
the superstars to say what they like. They have no worries, but there
are guys out there who have no money, no sponsorship. It can cost them a
grand (#1000) a week just to play and it's a different ball game at that
level.
''Those players who have got millions and get exemptions all over the
world can do what they want to do. They are not going to struggle.''
Told that the superstars are worried about sponsors dropping out,
Mitchell replied: ''If the top players do not play in all the European
tournaments and go off to America we shall not have such good
sponsorship.''
Mitchell, reluctant to mention names, was clearly critical of Faldo,
now playing regularly in the United States, and of Ballesteros,
Olazabal, and Woosnam, who have hinted they may follow suit. ''We would
have a great tour if all the top players played over here,'' said the
37-year-old.
Ken Schofield, executive director of the European Tour, also hit back
at the criticism.
Falso had said: ''We need new blood. After all, we are all 37 or 38
and in a few more years when we are gone, there will be a massive void
on the Tour.''
But Schofield responded: ''That doesn't apply to Colin Montgomerie and
Jose Maria Olazabal. Monty has been No.1 in Europe for the past two
years while Jose Maria has won the US Masters -- and they are not 37 or
38.
''Not everyone can be a superstar. But every player is trying his
hardest to win and I don't believe there is a comfort zone. And it
wasn't so long ago that Nick Faldo was singing the praises of Peter
Baker and Robert Karlsson as players of the future, the type we need on
the Tour.''
As for Faldo's worry about the loss of three major sponsors, Schofield
said: ''We have lost sponsors, it is true, but overall we have a net
gain in sponsors.''
Ever cheerful, Mitchell was happier to talk about his round. His three
eagles came at the 507-yard fourth where he holed from a greenside
bunker, 538-yard seventh where he hit his second shot to five feet with
a No.7 iron and 477-yard twelfth where he was on the green in two and
holed out from eight feet. He also chipped in from 25 feet for a birdie
at the eighth.
Paisley's Stephen McAllister was the best-placed Scot on 69. Leading
