<HEADLINE>The pick of Mayfest</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID BELCHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>MAYFEST</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>978321567</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
* TONIGHT is definitely the night for rock'n'rollers who have
gallantly served their full term before the mast. Fats Domino would have
headed the list if only he hadn't been felled by illness. But there is
still a bundle of stoic musical veterans to choose from.
John Mayall brings his latest group of Bluesbreakers to town at the
Garage at 7pm, 30-odd years after he first began to assemble his
blues-powered bands from the flower of young British musical talent. But
while Eric Clapton, Peter Green and Jack Bruce are long gone, the
venerable Mayall's mastery of the zappier end of the genre continues
unabated.
Castlemilk's noble and tireless musical toilers at C Sharp Music
Factory, located in Castlemilk Community Centre, Castlemilk Drive,
continue their three-day event with an 8pm show by boogie-merchants
Climax Blues Band. Support tonight is from local hero Billy Rivers.
Naturally, however, there are new contenders on tonight's Mayfest
musical menu. Supergrass is a hotly-tipped teenaged power trio which
will be bringing its meaty, guitar-driven riffs and its mutton-chop
side-whiskers to the Plaza at 7pm. .
Finally, a reminder of another postponement: NVA won't be creating
Stormy Waters tonight and tomorrow. It should go ahead on July 21 and
22.
</TEXT>
