<TEXT>
Ross Finlay finds a manufacturer who speaks his language
ANYONE put off considering the Hyundai Accent 1.3-litre Coupe, because
the front-end styling makes it look like a late arrival at Burl Ives's
''Ugly Bug Ball'', should think again. The entry-level car of the whole
Hyundai range will never win a concours d'elegance award, but it is
lively and responsive, very roomy despite its compact appearance, and it
combines good economy returns with rip-snorting performance for an
unassuming 1300.
Hyundai, the largest of the Korean car companies, is part of an
immense business conglomerate which started in 1940 as a modest repair
workshop, and now has world-wide annual sales of more than #45 billion.
While vehicle building is only part of its activities -- shipbuilding,
electronics, aerospace and petrochemicals have their own divisions --
its single-site factory at Ulsan is the largest production unit in the
whole world motor industry.
Like all Korean manufacturers, Hyundai originally tapped foreign
sources for most of its cars' mechanical elements. The Accent is the
first one which counts as a genuine home-grown product. In the
showrooms, it may take the place of the rather dull X2 model, but the
two cars have no hardware in common.
The 1.3i three-door Coupe is the sparsely equipped base model of the
Accent range. Selling at #6899, the test car had such features as a
digital clock, remote fuel filler release, cigarette lighter and
instrument light dimmer, and that was pretty much that as far as its
non-essential equipment went. No radio, although a wing-mounted
retractable aerial was provided, no airbag, no steering column height
adjustment, no alarm system, no central locking, simple cabin trim and
absolutely no frills at all, unless you count the ''glitter'' effect on
the rear-end badging. And yet, this dumpy-looking little car has a great
deal going for it.
To begin with, the packaging is first class. After I set the driver's
seat to suit my own well-reclined position at the wheel, I could ''sit
behind myself'' with plenty of rear headroom, kneeroom and footroom --
to an extent that made me wonder what other designers of this size of
car think they are playing at. And the Accent does not gain passenger
space at the cost of restricted luggage room, because the boot is both
large and reasonably unobstructed.
Hyundai fits its own Alpha-series engines to the Accent range. The
1.3i has a 12-valve 1341cc unit which peaks at 83bhp and produces its
maximum torque at 3100rpm. Together with a low kerb weight for a
solid-feeling car, and well chosen gear ratios, these figures let the
Coupe romp to 60mph in about 12.5 seconds, storm through the gears, and
reach a test track maximum around 108mph. You can expect fuel
consumption figures like 62mpg at 56mph, 46 at 75 and 39mpg around town.
A good driving position, accurate rack and pinion steering, and
enthusiastic turn-in make the Coupe an unexpectedly spritely performer.
I drove the test car part of the time in Ireland, on climbs and winding
moorland plateau roads often used for rally stages. While the front
wheels would sometimes scrabble a little for grip -- this is not, after
all, set up as a sports car -- the Coupe was great fun to drive, with
secure handling and a dependable stability over the bumps, of which
these roads have an abundance.
Just as impressive, the suspension kept up a good ride quality under
pressure. The Accent was not upset by the dips and humps encountered on
straights and corners alike. And the Hankook tyres kept road noise low.
We tend to regard Korean cars as derivative, but here is one whose
handling, ride, passenger space, performance and economy -- taken as a
combined package -- are right up with the class leaders. If this is what
the Koreans can do when they start with proper in-house designs, then
their ambition to make a massive sales breakthrough by the start of the
new century will be no mere pipe dream.
</TEXT>
