<HEADLINE>United Auctions gives assurance on future of small markets</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT ROSS, FARMING EDITOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321570</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE long-term trend towards a reduction in the number of auction
markets in Scotland will continue with some of the smaller markets
disappearing, John Izat, chairman of United Auctions (Scotland) said
yesterday.
Speaking after the company's annual meeting, held at Kildean Market in
Stirling, Mr Izat said that the company was well aware of the importance
of local markets to their farmer shareholders. The company's aim was to
co-operate in improving the auction system in Scotland.
In his annual report the chairman referred to the closure of the
United Auctions mart at Inverness. A financial assessment of the likely
costs of creating a new market there had led to the current agreement to
establish a 50/50 partnership with the board of Dingwall Auction Mart to
operate the market at Dingwall.
The market at Cupar had also been closed but, he said, it was very
close to Perth. Negotiations are continuing for the sale of the Cupar
site and a number of other property sales are expected to be concluded
this year. A substantial bid, subject to planning consent, has been
received for land at Polmaise.
Mr Izat said that the company was conscious of the importance of the
role of their markets in outlying areas. ''We have hung on to our
islands business despite the competition of the new market in Oban,'' he
said. ''Dalmally, as far as we are concerned, is totally secure.''
The new layerage at Oban, established to cater for stock coming in
from the islands, was being fully utilised. That stock was being sold
through Dalmally.
Chief executive Alan McGregor, in his report, said that he hoped that
the latest development at Perth Agricultural Centre would be in
operation by mid-summer. That will include a provision for a small
theatre which will stage an animal show based on the story of Highland
livestock.
Fergus Wood, who runs a similar venture on the story of sheep at
Aberfoyle, has been engaged to operate the Perth show.
Adjacent to the theatre will be an animal farm where visitors will be
able to see the livestock after the show. Scottish Enterprise Tayside is
backing the project which is seen as an important tourist development
for the area.
On the animal welfare front United Auctions has run the first of two
planned courses on stock-handling for staff at Stirling and Perth. It
also plans to produce a policy document on animal welfare which will
include material from animal health inspectors and the RSPCA.
The company results, declared earlier this month, show net trading
profits of #837,339 after interest, compared with #782,551 last year.
The meeting approved payment of a dividend of 20p a share.
In the terms of a special resolution passed yesterday the company is
to seek re-registration as a public limited company, which will allow
its shares to be traded on the alternative investment market (AIM) which
is being created specifically for dealing in the shares of smaller
companies.
There will also be a bonus issue of two new Ordinary shares for every
Ordinary share currently held.
</TEXT>
