<DOCNO>GH950519-000029</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000029</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Methane study</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321573</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Macaulay Land Use Research Institute in Aberdeen has teamed up
with its Japanese counterpart to study similarities in the emission of
methane from paddy fields and Scottish peatlands.
''Japan is the world-leader in paddy-field methane research,'' said
the Macaulay's Dr Steve Chapman. ''They are anxious to reduce the
release of methane without also having to reduce the production of
essential food.
''We have been looking at methane emissions from natural wetlands in
the UK, including the relationship between emission levels and the
existence of trees and the evidence to date is that methane release is
lower in wetlands where there are trees.''
</TEXT>
