<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ayrshire advisory group names first full-time member</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS CORRECTION: This article should point out that Sandy Findlay continues as chief executive as well as becoming chairman            and that Alastair Deakin remains as finance director.</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>978321574</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FARMER'S daughter Liz Garner (right) is the first full-time Farm
Conservation Adviser appointed by Ayrshire and Arran Farming and
Wildlife Advisory Group. With her appointment the group now has a
network of 19 advisers covering all of Scotland.
''Farmers in Ayrshire now have an opportunity for renewal -- a chance
to put something back into the land for future generations and leave
things better than they find them,'' said John Scott, chairman of the
Ayrshire and Arran FWAG, at a meeting at Culzean Castle.
Harvey Leckie of SmithKline Beecham, one of the corporate donors
supporting the Ayrshire branch, said that the largest proportion of land
in Ayrshire was associated with farming in one way or another.
''It is clear that the provision of advice and assistance from the new
adviser will make a significant contribution for the benefit fo future
generations and for the wildlife of this area.''
Ms Garner studied rural environmental sciences before completing an
MSc in ecology at Bangor. She has been a member of three expeditions to
St Kilda undertaking research work on the feral Soay Sheep population.
</TEXT>
