<DOCNO>GH950519-000032</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000032</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Support for pound</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321576</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A STRONGER dollar, particularly against the mark, where it broke
through a key resistance point, fed through to sterling which rose by
0.6 on a trade-weighted basis to 85.1.
The dollar is thought to be in a long-term uptrend which should
provide some ongoing support for the pound.
Against the mark the pound jumped over two pfennigs to DM2.2773. It
appears to be well supported as it continues to consolidate in a
DM2.2400-DM2.2850 trading range. However, against the richer dollar, it
lost over half-a-cent to $1.5630. It shrugged off the surprise dip in
April retail sales.
Elsewhere, the French franc was steady after its recent sell-off as
the market digested President Chirac's new cabinet appointments.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000033</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000033</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Enterprise on prowl</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321577</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ENTERPRISE Oil is actively looking for other potential acquisitions
following last year's failed attempt to take over Lasmo, shareholders
were told yesterday.
Chairman and chief executive Graham Hearne said the company's failure
to buy Lasmo was a disappointment but there were limits to the price it
was prepared to go.
''So we did not succeed. But rest assured, it has by no means
diminished our appetite for growth,'' he told investors at the annual
meeting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000034</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000034</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Personal Assets</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321578</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A REMARKABLE set of results have been produced by the #14m Personal
Assets Trust which has been independently managed by Ian Rushbrook for
the last 4[1/2] years for well-to-do individuals who wish to commit a
significant proportion of their capital.
Net asset value increased by 7.3% to #91.59 in the year to April 30,
significantly better than the benchmark All-Share index, which lost
0.1%.
Since becoming independent after years in the Ivory &amp; Sime stable,
Personal Assets has increased its asset value by 97.4%. The All-Share
index gained 59% over the same period.
A second interim dividend of #1 is being paid raising the total to #2
from #1.95. Earnings per share rose strongly to #2.33, an increase of
9.9%.
</TEXT>
