<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000035</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000035</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Burton Group on road to recovery</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NICOLA REEVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>978321579</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BURTON Group is steadily trying to move its business upmarket with
less focus on discounted prices. By building its brand integrity it
hopes to generate better margins and thus increase its profits. In line
with other successful retailers such as arch rival Marks &amp; Spencer, it
is working more closely with a smaller number of key suppliers which
leads to a more efficient, customer-focused business.
There are some signs that this strategy is beginning to pay off
although the company itself would admit that it has a long way to go
fully to satisfy both its customers and its shareholders. ''Building the
way back is very hard,'' said chairman Sir John Hoskyns.
Profits in the six months were up strongly to #61.5m before tax and
exceptional items to #61.5m against #35.1m previously. This was achieved
despite a 0.7% decline in overall turnover to #1035.7m. Gross margins
were 3.6% better in the first half.
Earnings per share were 3.3p before the exceptional item, up from
1.9p. Despite the strong performance the management is not complacent.
It is cautious about trading in the second half given the strong
comparative performance for last year and the continued fragility of
consumer confidence. So the interim dividend has been held at 1p.
The financial position of the group continues to strengthen. Despite a
busy store refurbishment programme there was a net cash inflow in the
first half of #61.4m compared with an outflow of #12m previously. At the
half-year net debt was just #19.2m, equivalent to gearing of just 2%.
Group capital expenditure for the full year is expected to be slightly
ahead of depreciation at around #115m.
Debenhams continues to be the jewel in the crown. Its sales were 4.5%
higher in the period. The Debenhams brand is being developed in its own
right across the Classic home furnishings range and Casual Club clothing
merchandise. A new store is to open in Leeds and further opportunities
are being explored in both out-of-town and town centre locations.
Ideally the company would like to add another 12 stores by the year
2000 taking the total to 100. Increasingly Debenhans is seen as an
attractive anchor store for new retail developments.
Within the multiple chains, which include Dorothy Perkins, Etam, Top
Shop, Principles and Burtons, the store refit and changes in merchandise
ranges toward more classic lines and away from high fashion is begining
to feed through to the bottom line.
It is taking time for customers changes in Dorothy Perkins smaller
catchment areas and the repositioning of Burtons menswear is taking
longer to achieve. This was behind the 4.5% drop in sales in the ongoing
Multiples business. Experiments are continuing with customer loyalty
schemes and the development of stand alone shops for its successful own
brands.
The encouraging trading statement prompted City analysts to upgrade
their annual profit forecasts and pushed up Burton Group shares by
5[1/2]p to 85p.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000036</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000036</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>London Life closed to new business</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER SIMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321580</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LONDON Life, one of the oldest life insurance companies, has decided
not to take on any more new business and to axe its marketing operation,
as a result of increasing competition in the industry.
It will become a caretaker operation, looking after the 90,000
policyholders on its books and their #2000m investments. The company
stressed that policyholders' investments were ''absolutely safe'' and
all existing contractual rights would continue to be met in full.
However, the move will send a frisson of fear through the life
insurance industry, which is suffering from over-capacity. Closures
among the smaller companies are widely expected. ManuLife recently
pulled out of the UK market.
''There is absolutely no cause for policyholders to be concerned,''
said London Life chief executive Jim Divers.
The company is owned by a much larger and financially very strong
group, Australian Mutual Provident Society (AMP). Mr Divers said it
stood full square behind London Life.
Closing the company to further funds should not have any significant
impact on future bonus rates or surrender values on with-profits
policies.
However, Mr Divers agreed that the lack of inflow of new money into
the life fund could have some impact on investment performance. Having
an inflow makes it easier for the investment manager. Without this he
would normally have to pursue a more conservative investment strategy to
avoid increased volatility but this will be less necessary with AMP
behind the compnay. Bonuses will also benfit from the company having
much lower expenses.
The fund will continue to be managed by AMP's investment managers.
Now 460 jobs at London Life will go, with all its 14 sales offices
closing. The only Scottish branch, in Glasgow, employs eight full-time
staff. However the company expects most redundancies will be voluntary.
Full disclosure of commissions from the beginning of the year was the
final straw for London Life by exacerbating an already difficult market.
Its sales, which were concentrated in single premium business, suffered
a sharp fall last year and the trend has continued into 1995.
The company has a chequered history, having to be rescued by AMP in
1989 after it had tried to expand too fast. AMP injected #50m into the
life fund in 1992. Since then London Life has tried to revive itself
through new products and reducing expenses but its size and background
were against it.
A review, assisted by actuaries Bacon &amp; Woodrow, concluded that sales
were unlikely to recover to the level needed to support the marketing
infrastructure.
The Department of Trade and Industry, which regulates the insurance
industry, was kept informed throughout but Mr Divers said the move to
close was not prompted by DTI action.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000037</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000037</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>BritishGas hitby mildwinter</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NICOLA REEVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321581</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CEDRIC Brown, chief executive of British Gas has no feelings of guilt
over the 71% increase in his remuneration package last year to #492,602.
Speaking as the company announced a drop in first-quarter profits he
expressed confidence in shareholders support for his remuneration
package.
A resolution to be put to the company's shareholders at the AGM in
London's Docklands at the end of the month calls for a change in the
company's controversial pay structure for senior executives.
The Labour Party has lobbied major institutional shareholders such as
the Prudential and Standard Life to vote for the resolution. Mr Brown
believes that when they hear the company's explanations of the package
and what the job entails then ''I think they will see I am being paid
properly and correctly,'' he said.
Profits in the first three months of the year were depressed by a mild
winter. Growing competition led to a loss of market share, to below 40%,
in the large industrial and commercial customer segment. The company
faces a loss of market share in the important domestic market when its
monopoly supply position is ended at the beginning of next year as a
result of the Gas Bill currently going through Parliament.
Historic cost net profits slipped to #605m from #651m, broadly in line
with City expectations. The mild weather which reduces domestic demand
for heating clipped #28m off trading profits. Year-on-year comparisons
were distorted by the sale of the Consumers Gas company in Canada last
year.
On a divisional basis, results from Transco in the first quarter
showed operating profit of #450m compared with #480m previously. The
results of the Trading division showed a drop in operating profits to
#175m from #220m.
However, this was offset by a strong performance from Exploration and
Production which reported 67% higher profits of #212m. Business in this
division was boosted by the start of production from its North Morecambe
field and increased output at its South Morecambe operations.
''This division is also beginning to enjoy the benefit of a rigorous
cost reduction programme aimed at improving its efficiency,'' the
company said.
British Gas continues to develop its overseas business to provide an
unregulated income stream. The merger between NGC and Trident was
completed in March which gives British Gas a 34% shareholding in NGC,
one of the leading energy companies in the USA.
The company has expanded its interests in northern Russia. The first
gas arrived on shore this month from a Tunisian field.
''These are a fair set of figures but nothing to get excited about,''
said one analyst. Profits for the full year should benefit from
continuing cost-cutting. The company plans to make a further 10,000 job
cuts this year which should help to cut costs by #150m. There have
already been 2400 voluntary redundancies this year, ahead of the
company's expectations. British Gas embarked on major changes about two
years ago which included cutting 25,000 jobs by December 1998, most of
them by the end of 1996.
It has shed a total of 12,000 jobs. The company expects to eventually
recoup more than #600m in annual savings from the programme, a figure
that should be achievable by next year. A sharp drop in the number of
employees has been a key feature of all the privatised utilities as they
strive to maximise profits.
British Gas shares were a penny lighter at 303[1/2]p but are expected
to recover once they reach the lower end of trading ranges and interest
revives not least because they are supported by a 6% yield.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000038</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000038</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Devro warns of slow start</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT POWELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321582</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DEVRO International, the Scottish sausage skin-maker, said yesterday
that British and US authorities would probably approve a proposed
takeover of its much larger US competitor Teepak International during
the summer.
But Devro warned that a slow start to the year in Continental Europe
would keep its interim results flat, little changed from last year's
level.
The Moodiesburn-based firm, which manufactures casings for meat and
dairy products, announced in March that it had reached an agreement in
principle to buy Teepak for $135m, taking on net debts up to a limit of
$155m.
The main obstacle to completion of the deal is approval by the US
Federal Trade Commission, but Devro chief executive Graeme Alexander
said this was expected within three or four months.
''I would be surprised if it came before June, but I would be
disappointed if it came after September,'' he told The Herald on the
sidelines of Devro's annual general meeting in Glasgow.
Mr Alexander said the UK Office of Fair Trading must also give its
green light for the takeover, but no hitches were expected on that front
either.
The chief executive said slow sales in Continental Europe were
expected to keep Devro's results for the six months to June in line with
their 1994 level. The company made a pre-tax profit of #14.1m on
turnover of #47.5m during the first half of last year.
''There is definitely a downturn in Germany and Central Europe,'' Mr
Alexander said.
But business in the UK, the United States and Australia was doing
better and a decline in Japanese sales had been reversed, he added.
''We are expecting the interim result to be broadly in line with last
year. It could be a little more or a little less,'' he said.
Devro chairman Leon Allen told the AGM that Devro's planned purchase
of Teepak would give the Scottish firm a wider product range and
additional production capacity and would give both firms better access
to world markets.
Devro could take advantage of Teepak's stronger position in the United
States, while Teepak could benefit from Devro's bigger presence in
Europe and the Far East, he said.
Teepak is twice the size of Devro, which was created by a management
buyout from Johnson and Johnson in 1991 and was floated on the stock
exchange in 1993.
But the US firm, which also has factories in Belgium, the Netherlands
and the Czech Republic, suffers from declining profits.
Devro, with sales of #98m last year, regards the US firm with 1994
sales of #205m, as an overweight giant, that must be restored to full
fitness.
For the last three years Teepak has suffered from flat sales,
declining profits and rising debt, although heavy investment has greatly
increased its production capacity.
Mr Alexander said Devro planned to integrate Teepak fully into a
single management structure.
The Scottish firm plans to finance the purchase of Teepak with about
#20m of its own cash, a #28m share sale to institutional investors and
about #80m of bank credit, he said.
The bank loans would be raised by First Chicago Bank with strong
support from the Royal Bank of Scotland and Clydesdale, he added.
The chief executive said Devro might well make further acquisitions in
the future, but it would take about two or three years to digest Teepak.
''We have maybe bitten off as much as we can swallow right at this
moment,'' he said.
Devro shares dipped 9p to 234p.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
