<HEADLINE>Apache set for #9000m take-off</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>978321583</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Westland Apache attack helicopter is likely to be worth about
#9000m at its peak to UK industry, GKN chairman Sir David Lees told
shareholders yesterday.
At the moment Westland, bought last year by GKN, is engaged in a
bitter fight to win an order for the Apache from the Ministry of
Defence.
''This order, which initially could be worth around #2000m, would
bring with it very substantial opportunities for additional work, much
of which is in leading edge technologies, for over 150 UK companies.
''Over time, we believe the total UK industrial participation in the
Westland Apache programme could amount to some #9000m.''
Addressing the annual meeting, Sir David said the group was delighted
with the Westland acquisition. Its trading results for the first four
months of 1995 were well ahead of the comparative figures for last year
and its longer-term prospects were encouraging.
In other core areas, GKN has enjoyed strong trading in its car and
agritechnical parts businesses in the early months of the year. ''The
level of activity in almost all our plants around the world is high and
in a number of cases very high. Looking forward we do not expect this to
change much in the short term.''
GKN, based at Redditch in Worcestershire, is confident of boosting
sales in its key North American market this year despite independent
forecasts that demand for cars and light trucks will fall off slightly.
''In Europe as a whole, we are still expecting car production in 1995
to exceed last year's figures by a small percentage and the commercial
vehicle and agritechnical markets continue to strengthen.''
</TEXT>
