<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Trafalgar House sinks into the red</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321584</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TRAFALGAR House, the civil engineering, property and shipping group,
has sunk into losses of #48.2m for the six months ended March.
It is again not paying an interim dividend after a loss per share of
6.67p against earnings of 0.46p.
Today's news comes in the wake of the disastrous Christmas cruise by
the QE2, flagship of Trafalgar's Cunard shipping line, which was spoilt
by refitting work.
In all the Cunard liner business suffered an operating loss, before
exceptional items, of #6.9 million as a result of lower than expected
occupancy levels on its ships.
Trafalgar House, which had made #13.8m profits at the same stage in
1994, has appointed a new chief executive at Cunard and made further
management changes to strengthen the sales and marketing side of the
business.
Cunard's chairman is leaving ''by mutual agreement'' just five months
after the disastrous Christmas voyage.
Trafalgar House said John Olsen was leaving its board and that of
Cunard ''to pursue other interests''.
He will be replaced on the Trafalgar House board and as chairman and
chief executive of Cunard by Peter Ward, chairman of Rolls-Royce Motor
Cars.
The group said the action launched against Cunard by a group of QE2
passengers ''is in progress and is being vigorously contested. We
continue to believe that the action has no merit.''
The group also suffered #7.5m exceptional costs to cover refit
problems on the QE2.
Its power engineering business made a half-year operating loss of
#18.8m. In response, redundancies were announced in March.
In addition, Trafalgar suffered costs of #12m as a result of a foiled
bid for Northern Electric.
A group of American shareholders in Northern yesterday increased the
pressure on the company to reopen takeover talks with Trafalgar House.
Newcastle-based Northern rejected the revised Trafalgar bid after the
original, recommended #11-a-share offer was withdrawn following the
fresh investigation into electricity prices launched by the industry
regulator Professor Stephen Littlechild.
Trafalgar subsequently proposed an alternative 950p bid, but that
offer lapsed because Northern's board refused to allow shareholders to
vote on it.
</TEXT>
