<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000042</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000042</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Profits dip means lower bonus for chairman.BT feels pressure</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER SIMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<FLAG>COMMENT</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>978321586</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
COMPETITION and regulatory pressure are catching up with BT, whose
latest results show a fall in profits, though dividends still go up by
well above inflation.
Over the year to March, profits dipped 3% to #2662m and the fall
accelerated in the final quarter, when they were down nearly 9% at
#509m.
The result means a lower bonus for chairman Sir Iain Vallance. This
will fall from #185,000 to #115,000. But BT's remuneration committee,
composed, the group hastens to add, entirely of non-executive directors,
has reviewed salaries of executive directors and has given Sir Iain a
3.2% rise to #480,000. It last increased in July 1992.
Sir Iain's total remuneration goes down nearly 10% to #599,000. At a
briefing yesterday he would not elaborate on what the committee had
decided for other directors but said the annual report would include a
detailed break-down.
So for last year shareholders do better than the chairman as the final
dividend is raised by 6% to 10.65p for a total of 17.7p.
Two factors were mainly responsible for the profits downturn.
Redundancy costs were #303m higher at #820m because more higher earning
managers took redundancy under the group's voluntary scheme and more
employees took the terms in total than expected. Secondly price cuts
cost #800m in lost revenue.
The massive technology-driven job reduction programme has largely run
its course, and the group-wide redundancy programme will finish in a few
weeks time. There will continue to be further losses in specific areas
of operation, still on a voluntary basis.
Redundancy costs will be down to #400m-#500m this year, while the
benefits of the reduction in costs will come through. The impact of
price cuts will also be less pronounced, resulting in a revenue
sacrifice of about #400m. These lower negatives are just as well given
the pressures BT is under.
Market share is continuing to slip, with the greatest challenge coming
from cable television, which can offer phone services up to 20% cheaper.
Around 50,000 BT customers a month are signing up and the cable network
is growing.
However, BT professes not to be worried, claiming that the rate of
decline in its share was less than forecast. It is wooing some people
back and it did succeed in seeing off the competitive challenge from
Mercury. It claims also to be more interested in expanding the total
market rather than concerned about its total market share.
But the haemorrhage of customers highlights the importance of the
large-scale trials of interactive services planned for this year. How
far the regulator, Don Cruickshank, will allow BT to go in this
direction remains to be seen.
In company with other privatised industries BT is not pleased with the
regulatory regime. Sir Iain said that although BT's trading prospects
were ''sound'' they were susceptible to a ''hostile and unpredictable
regulatory environment'' in the UK.
The group is keen to escape the UK regulator by expanding overseas but
here too it is not going to have a free hand and Sir Iain also mentions
the ''uncertain shape'' of regulation outside the UK.
The effect of UK price reductions, mainly reflecting lower rates for
weekday morning calls, national calls made at the weekend and many
long-distance national calls, was partly offset by a 7% rise in inland
call volume. International call costs have come down by 7% on average,
while volume was up 5%.
Competition from cable caused a 1% fall in domestic connections in the
final quarter and was also reflected in an 15% increase in interconnect
sales, where rivals pay BT for the use of its lines to deliver calls.
Revenue from mobile phones, mainly BT's controlling interest in Cellnet,
jumped 43%.
BT's overseas strategy is coming along, centred on its joint venture
with MCI of the US, called Concerto. This is aimed at giving
multinationals private worldwide networks.
During the past year the group has forged links in Norway, Germany,
Italy, and Sweden and only France remains to complete its European
coverage. This places the group in a strong position to take advantage
of liberalisation of telecommunications in the European Union, subject
of course to the regulatory regime.
Partly as a result of the development of Concert, and also of the
Cellnet mobile network, capital spending last year rose 23% to #2671m
and is set to be even higher this year. Another area of spending is the
computers to provide bills by the second rather than the unit. Despite
this BT's gearing remains modest at 18%.
BT shares were initially ahead on the figures but came back to end at
exactly 400p, down 2[1/2]p on balance. Given the uncertainties they are
no more than a hold but there is a good chance of dividend increases
ahead of inflation for years to come, which should keep its army of
small shareholders happy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
