<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scratch card game blamed for a drop in April retail sales</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>R E DUNDAS, CHIEF FINANCIAL EDITOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>978321587</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE National Lottery's Instants scratch card game, which began on
March 21, is thought to have hit retail sales, which fell by 0.2% in
April confounding City expectations of an increase of 0.5%.
The continued weakness of sales could strengthen the hand of Kenneth
Clarke, the Chancellor of the Exchequer, in any disagreement with the
Bank of England over whether interest rates should rise on June 7.
Though lower than in March after seasonal adjustment the volume of
sales was 0.8% higher than in April. The March figures were revised down
from a drop of 0.1% to 0.3%, but the year-on-year gain was 1.6%.
The three-monthly comparisons are healthier. In the latest three
months sales were 0.3% higher than in the previous three and 1.6% better
than in the same three months of 1994.
The British Retail Consortium said that consumer confidence continued
to be at a low ebb and the housing market refused to budge.
''Consumers are reluctant to take on debt, and, faced with these
factors, the retail market continues to be highly competitive and
particularly difficult for small traders,'' said James May, the
consortium's director-general.
''The BRC was relieved that the Chancellor resisted recent pressure to
increase interest rates and the BRC hopes that he will avoid such action
as long as possible.''
Average weekly ticket sales from the Instants lottery game are running
at #44m, which is equal to 1.5% of retail sales.
From this needs to be deducted the prize money of 50%. James Capel's
Adam Cole said it was unlikely that all the Instants sales represented
substitution from low ticket retail sales.
''It is quite conceivable that the introduction of these cards reduced
the volumes of retail sales in April by around 0.5%.
Other non-food retailers, a residual category comprising mainly small
shops, were the weakest sector with sales falling by 0.8%
month-on-month. The only area of notable strength was clothing and
footweart where volumes grew by 0.5%.
The three-monthly figures, which provide a better guide to the
underlying trend, showed steady growth in sales at food retailers and
mixed retail businesses with volumes in both categories up 0.7% on the
previous three months. Food retailers posted a gain of 2.9% on the same
three months of 1994 and mixed retailers' sales were 2.3% higher.
Clothing and footwear sales rose by 1.5% from the previous three
months and were up by 3.6% from the same three months a year earlier.
Good weather boosted sales of spring fashions.
Household goods sales fell sharply -- down 1.1% between the latest two
three monthly periods. Sales were only 1.5% higher than in the same
three months of last year. Fresh weakness in the housing market has
coincided with a steady acceleration in prices, now 3.2% higher than a
year ago.
Sales by other non-food retailers fell by 0.4% in the latest three
months and were 3.1% below the level of the same three months a year
ago.
Adam Cole said: ''It seems likely that much of the recent weakness of
retail sales is down to consumers substituting into purchases of leisure
services generally and the National Lottery in particular.''
He thought that the ''sogginess'' of the data made a base rate rise in
early June slightly less likely.
''While the Bank's argument for a rate rise (the strength of
manufacturing and the fall in sterling) are undented by these figures,
the chances that the Chancellor will choose to ignore the Bank's advice
have clearly increased.''
</TEXT>
