<HEADLINE>Gordon takes back-seat role at Scottish Radio</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT POWELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>978321588</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JAMES GORDON, a pioneer of independent radio in Scotland, will step
down as chief executive of Scottish Radio Holdings and managing director
of its flagship station Radio Clyde next year after reaching the age of
60, writes ROBERT POWELL.
But Mr Gordon, who has built up Radio Clyde since its foundation in
1972, will retain a back-seat role as non-executive chairman of the
group.
He will succeed Ian Chapman, the former head of Collins the publisher,
who will retire early next year after turning 70.
Mr Gordon's present job will be split in the reorganisation.
Richard Findlay, the managing director of Radio Forth in Edinburgh,
will take over as group chief executive, while Alex Dickson, the
programme director at Radio Clyde, will replace Mr Gordon as managing
director of the Glasgow-based station.
Scottish Radio Holdings said in a statement accompanying its interim
results yesterday that these changes would take effect in May 1996.
The company announced a 25% rise in pre-tax profits to #2.5m for the
six months to March 31, on turnover up 15% to #8.5m.
It achieved these results because of a 50% increase in national
broadcast revenue booked through its group sales house in London. This
compensated for a 1% fall in revenue generated locally in Scotland.
Scottish Radio said running costs had been kept below inflation in all
areas except marketing.
It raised the interim dividend to 2.1p from 1.8p at the half-way point
last year, but this failed to enthuse investors on a generally depressed
day in the stock market. Scottish Radio shares fell 2p 256p.
The management shake-up at Scottish Radio follows the renewal of its
licences to run four radio stations in east and central Scotland for a
further eight years.
Besides Radio Forth and Radio Clyde, the group owns Radio Tay in
Dundee and Northsound in Aberdeen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
