<DOCNO>GH950519-000045</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000045</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Guinness produces mixed cocktail for shareholders</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321589</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GUINNESS produced a mixed cocktail of news for shareholders yesterday,
saying its stout beer side was strong but the spirits business was
depressed.
''Trading for the first four months of the year has shown no
significant change to the pattern experienced in the second half of
1994,'' chairman Tony Greener told shareholders.
''Guinness stout continues to perform strongly. In spirits,
Continental Europe and Japan remain depressed and there are specific
difficulties in Mexico and Venezuela,'' he said at the annual meeting.
''In the UK, the 'feel good' factor remains elusive'', he warned,
though trading reamains ''very staisfactory'' in Latin America and
South-east Asia.
''Looking further ahead, I can but reaffirm my confidence in the
opportunities that present themselves for the group around the world.
''There are exciting long term opportunites, particularly in emerging
and developing markets for spirits,'' he said.
''The prospects for our unique Guinness stout product are improving
all the time as we continue to make rapid progress in North America and
Continential Europe, with other opportunities also available in other
parts of the world, particularly in Asia-Pacific'', Mr Greener added.
</TEXT>
