<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>S&amp;N callsfor #354m to fund purchase</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321590</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Scottish &amp; Newcastle purchase of Courage finally saw the light of
day yesterday with the Edinburgh company paying an initial #425m for the
assets of the Foster's Brewing Group subsidiary.
Subject to regulatory approval with the Office of Fair Trading --
probably the biggest hurdle -- S&amp;N will have achieved what should have
happened over two decades ago.
The geographic fit between the two companies is remarkable with no
serious overlap apart from Yorkshire while they both share the
philosophy of being free traders with the tie representing under 15% of
volume.
Only 15%-20% of S&amp;N profits are generated in Scotland and just 1.5
million of the nine-million-barrel annual beer capacity is brewed in
Edinburgh.
In addition to the cash sum, it is committed to topping up the Courage
pension fund by #48m but that is spread over 12 years so the annual
amounts involved are of little consequence.
Intriguingly, Foster's has added an equity kicker to the sum by being
paid the increase in value on 10 million S&amp;N shares over 537p in either
1999 or 2000 obviously judging that the S&amp;N share price will rise over
the next few years by a useful amount.
Last night they closed down 7p at 539p with the City generally happy
about the complex details of the deal which transforms S&amp;N into being
Britain's largest brewer and with a brand portfolio that will provide a
platform to take it into Europe under the Foster's banner.
The rights issue designed to raise a net #354m is in two parts on the
basis of one new share at 475p for every seven held.
The first instalment of 190p is payable by June 9 and is not dependent
upon the deal proceeding to completion. The second payment is 285p and
will be made only on completion which is expected before the end of
July.
Chief executive Brian Stewart said that there will be a minimal effect
on earnings per share in the first year, ignoring exceptional items such
as goodwill write-downs and be earnings positive thereafter.
Annual savings of at least #40m annually are expected from 1997
onwards,
For the year just over to April, 1995 pre-tax profits are estimated to
have risen 18% to not less than #262m and earnings of 36.2p. The
dividend total will rise at least 7% to 18.23p with a final of 12.05p --
the new shares will not be entitled to this payment.
Courage in the year to last June had operating profits before
exceptional items of #34m on turnover of #1334m based on assets of
#411m. So the cost economies promised from the acquisition are extremely
significant.
The crucial question is the extent to which S&amp;N can capitalise upon
the selling power of its brands.
The impact upon the balance sheet is to increase overall gearing only
marginally from 42% to 45% although interest cover in the short term
will fall from six times to about four times.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000047</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000047</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Open and shut case for a key</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN FOWLER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>978321591</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT would be nice to have sardines for my tea -- sardines on toast.
It's a long time since I've had that. So I bought a tin of sardines at
the Co-op down the road. It came packaged in a box with a pretty wavy
blue design and pink fishy things on it.
When I took the tin out it looked white and naked. Something was
missing. There was no key. All my life, sardines have come with a key.
It's part of the natural order of things. The technology is simple. You
snap off the key from the side of the tin, attach it to the little
tongue of metal conveniently supplied, and turn. The key glides round
gathering a scroll as it peels off a narrow strip of metal all round the
tin. Then you lift the lid off.
Sometimes there's a tricky bit at the joint of the tin, and
occasionally the strip of metal breaks off half way, but mostly it's no
problem. Sardines are easy.
I studied the bare tin in my hand, but there was no obvious solution.
It was aesthetically pleasing to look at, shiny with gently rounded
corners, but it was clearly designed to keep the sardines in and me out.
I picked up the box it came in. ''Guidelines: Co-op Sardines in
Vegetable Oil are now packed in a new easy-to-open can, simply use your
usual can opener''.
Strictly, that should be two sentences. There should be a period after
the first can, and simply should start with a capital S, but I could
live with the punctuation. The puncturing was more to the point. Now I
knew what to do.
I took my usual tin opener (that's what I call it), in fact my only
tin opener, and applied it in the usual way. It slid nicely round the
first corner and stuck at the next. A coil of oil oozed out and coated
my fingers.
I applied it to the tin a little further on. Again it cut a smooth
path round the first bend until it came to the next, where it skited
off. I now had a tin open at two opposite corners with the section of
lid in between still firmly attached.
I prised up one of the corners so that I could see the neatly packed
slivers of fish glinting with a silvery lustre. In doing so, being
slightly agitated at this turn of events, and having my fingers slippery
with oil, I managed to nick my thumb on the cut edge. A small smear of
blood appeared. I swore.
At this impasse I took a radical measure. I levered up the two open
ends of the tin as far as they would go and worked a teaspoon underneath
to dislodge the fish and scoop it out.
I didn't bother with the toast. I didn't bother grilling the emergent
sardines. To tell the truth, I felt quite trembly after this small
trauma. But a salad with minced sardines is really quite tasty. Try it
sometime.
Next time I was shopping I mentioned this to the woman at the counter.
She said: ''Maybe you need a new tin opener''.
But that's not so. It opens other tins well enough. Beans, OK.
Tomatoes. Spaghetti hoops. Well, I don't know. What's the world coming
to?
Tonight I might have fish fingers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000048</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000048</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Waste not, want not</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JENNIFER CUNNINGHAM</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>978321592</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Public attitudes to recycling are very positive, but the provision of
local authority schemes in Scotland, and the success they enjoy, varies
greatly from one area to another, discovers Jennifer Cunningham
THERE is no waste strategy in Scotland, partly because the Scottish
Office has decided it wants to wait until the Scottish Environmental
Protection Association is established in 1996. In the meantime, England
has evolved a system which is already five years ahead of us, with
#16.4m from the Department of Environment to set up schemes. ''In
Scotland, everybody is dashing off in their own direction with no
overall planning,'' said John Ferguson, chairman of the Recycling
Advisory Group Scotland.
The most frequent request to cleansing departments is to start regular
collections of household paper. We all want to save the earth, but most
of us do little more than the ritual chink of bottle in bank, unless you
live in Leith, Dundee, Kyle and Carrick or some other district which has
taken the practical approach to environmental targets.
Bottle banks are a handy measure of public attitudes to recycling:
people do take the trouble to put the correct colour in each bank and
there is a demand for more bottle banks.
The idea of setting all local authorities a target of a 20% recycling
rate was met with predictions of doom that, as more and more waste
materials were collected, prices would fall below economic levels. In
fact, the opposite has happened.
Three years ago, as many charities discovered, waste paper became
worthless to the point where you could not give it away. That was
specifically due to an edict in Germany that paper could no longer be
disposed of in landfill sites. There was an immediate overspill into the
European market, prices plummeted and some mills were even being paid to
take waste paper. Now newsprint can fetch #80 a tonne.
Households in Dundee -- recycling city -- have had a separate paper
collection since before the war, but as a result of the district
council's environmental policy, 31,000 households have a green bin on
wheels for all paper and card, except waxed or plasticised cartons. With
a participation rate of vetween 81% and 95%, they collect about 120
tonnes a week, which is sold to Davidson's of Aberdeen, who reprocess it
to produce packaging and plasterboard.
Despite the market being flooded with paper from Germany just after
they had invested in a new baler and expanded their plant, Dundee
District Council stuck to its guns and found that in less than six
months the price rose from #9 to #55 a tonne.
Last year, the council made #350,000 from waste paper -- enough to
cover the cost of collecting it without adding in the savings in the
cost of transporting it to new landfill sites, since its own is almost
full.
The council has instituted an environmental policy which has led the
way in recycling in Scotland. In addition to green bins for paper,
12,000 households in the city have brown wheeled bins for what the
council calls botanical waste -- all vegetable matter from both kitchen
and garden. From 8000 tonnes of garden refuse a year, they produce 3500
tonnes of compost under the supervision of a microbiologist from Abertay
University.
Garden centres cannot get enough of their Discovery Compost, and the
bottom line is looking extremely cheerful according to the city's
environmental services department. They are now planning to take
productive waste mangement a step further with a waste to energy
incineration plant in conjunction with Scottish Power, which would
produce energy along with a heat recovery scheme which could possibly be
used to heat greenhouses.
Edinburgh has several innovative pilot schemes. The latest runs during
the Festival of the Environment -- from now until May 28 -- when there
will be collection points for old telephone directories in libraries and
sports centres.
Last year, 1000 tenement households in Leith took part in a pilot
scheme to recycle paper, cans, glass and plastic. Gary Turner,
Edinburgh's recycling officer, wanted to test commitment in an area with
a low level of car ownership and of storage space in the house.
On the basis that the easier you make it for people the more they
participate, they gave households a green bag into which they put all
paper, cans, glass and plastics, and they were sorted by the district
council. The contamination rate was very low, and the participation rate
was 42% -- better than predicted for an inner-city area, but the costs
remain prohibitive because it more or less means collecting refuse twice
on two different days.
Glasgow has 50 ''bring sites'' mainly in car parks, but there are
plans to increase the number accesssible to Glasgow's non car owning
population. They all have bottles banks, 10 also have depositories for
paper and steel cans, and some also take aluminium cans, textiles, waxed
beverage cartons and household plastic containers. ''We want to be in
the position where everyone in Glasgow will have access to a recycling
centre,'' said recycling officer, Rolf Matthews.
John Ferguson, chairman of Recycling Advisory Group Scotland, voices
the belief of his members in calling for positive intervention from
government.
''The EC packaging directive gives responsibility to nation states to
guarantee an end user for waste products. In the UK it has not gone far
enough.'' As an example, he cites the Government's voluntary agreement
with the newspaper industry to increase the amount of recycled material
in their newsprint to 40% by the year 2000.
''It should have been mandatory, and should have been a minimum of
50%, preferably 60%, and that would have sent the right signal for
additional mill capacity, which should logically be in Scotland, at
Gartcosh, serving the needs of Scotland and the north of England.''
THE EUROPEAN EXPERIENCE
* Is packaging greener in the rest of Europe?
In Germany every kind of mineral water is sold in the same glass
bottle, with only the labels differentiating between brands, so the
empties can be returned to the nearest filler.
A major catering company based in Munich has abandoned disposable cups
for a strong polypropylene beaker which can be washed and re-used. The
Dutch chainstore Albert Heijn has been innovative in reducing
unnecessary packaging in their own label goods. Examples include
replacing the plastic trays inside boxes of chocolates with a simple
separator between the two levels, and dispensing with the paper bag
inside boxes of dry goods such as rice. Other continental examples
include refillable plastic bottles for milk, drinks and household
detergents, a returnable, refillable  paint pot system for professional
decorators, and refillable spray cans for both commercial and household
use.
</TEXT>
