<TEXT>
* AS well as a number on the front door, flats and houses are about to
acquire another, that could add up to a key selling point. From July 1,
all new homes and conversions will be energy-rated on a scale from 0 to
100 -- the higher the better -- as part of the Government's commitment
to tackling global warming through energy saving.
Experts with specialised equipment will provide accurate measurements
of a home's energy efficiency.
For information about the scheme, contact the Energy Efficiency Office
on 0181-691 900. The June issue of Individual Homes magazine also
carries a guide.
* MORE than a million people in Britain have diabetes. It's not their
only handicap -- virtually all have problems with insurance.
If an application is not refused outright stringent medical tests are
imposed, with high premiums.
The British Diabetic Association, which blames lack of understanding,
is teaming up with the Co-operative Bank to provide a full range of
insurance services for diabetics, who don't have to be bank customers to
benefit.
For details call 01903-262 900 (Motor), 0161-829 5600 (Life) and
0171-512 0890 (Travel).
* FOR more colourful conversations, BT are extending their range of
coloured phones and answering machines. As a measure of how far we've
progressed since the ''Henry Ford'' days of the take-it-or-leave-it
black telephone, the new line includes racing green, midnight blue, pale
yellow and peach, antique rose and Wedgwood blue. There is also postbox
red to match reminder bills!
According to BT, home owners should be thinking of changing phones to
harmonise with colour schemes. Dial 0800-33 44 22 for information.
* A CAMPAIGN to save Scotland's trees from careless cable operators is
launched today by the Consumers' Association. Claiming that as many as
nine in 10 street trees may be damaged by trenching squads, the CA says
recent industry guidelines are voluntary and only legal sanctions will
prevent damage.
Meantime, vigilantes are urged to call the Tree Line on 0171-830 6083
if they think trees are being damaged.
* MAKE A DATE: The Wondrous Machine is the title of a series of organ
concerts on the newly-restored Father Willis organ at St Mary's
Cathedral, Palmerston Place, Edinburgh on May 30, June 6, 13, and 20
(8pm). Telephone 0131-225 6293 for tickets.
Story from Glasgow is an exhibition of prints by leading contemporary
artist Ken Currie at Kirkcaldy Museum and Art Gallery until June 4.
Edinburgh Festival of the Environment (until May 28) takes wildlife as
its main theme, with more than 100 events covering environmental issues.
Programmes from city libraries and sports centres or phone 0131-529
3030.
</TEXT>
