<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000050</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000050</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Wise words and deaf ears</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALF YOUNG</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>978321594</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ON the surface, this week's shake-up at the Scottish Office is all
about saving money and improving service delivery. That insistent
duopoly of aims virtually sums up the rubric of our times, does it not?
But, on a more subliminal level, the proposed new departmental
structure is saying something deeply significant about how the
collective Scottish Office mind currently views the impact of its
wide-ranging policies on real life.
Industry and education are to merge into a single department. Those,
like the Scottish CBI, who fret about the skills deficit among the
young, and the gulf between academia and industry in commercialising the
fruits of research, will warmly welcome that.
But the Industry Department is to shed its recently acquired
responsibility for Scotland's roads programme, together with
responsibility for urban regeneration, European structural funds, and
new towns. All these go into a super Local Government Department, which
is also to embrace the new single-tier councils, planning and housing.
One could nitpick. Why does tourism go into Education and Industry,
while responsibility for the Historic Scotland agency sits in the new
Local Government pantechnicon? Does that make sense at a time when Rob
Roy is set to maraude across the world's cinema screens, with Liam
Neeson with a ''Come to Scotland'' message pinned to his plaid?
Enough of nitpicking. I want to address a bigger issue, prompted, in
large part, by work done by David Webster, a senior official with
Glasgow City Housing. This week's Scottish Office decision to separate
urban regeneration from industrial policy into separate departments
flies in the face of Webster's central concern.
It is that Glasgow has been bleeding jobs in frighteningly large
numbers for the past 15 years -- 37,756 manufacturing jobs lost between
1981 and 1991 and only 2843 service jobs gained -- and that an urban
regeneration strategy which concentrates primarily on upgrading the
physical infrastructure and does not seek to influence the location of
jobs within the city, will fail to staunch that haemorrhage.
For the past year, in a series of personal papers, Webster has argued
trenchantly that the task of finding new work for the urban unemployed
cannot be divorced from efforts to improve the environments in which
they live.
Webster's approach is deeply at odds with official Scottish Office
thinking. Ministers have occasionally paid lip service to his plea for a
comprehensive approach to urban regeneration. For example, when New Life
for Urban Scotland was published in 1988, ushering in the four
partnership initiatives in disadvantaged estates in Glasgow, Paisley,
Dundee, and Edinburgh, the Scottish Secretary's foreword acknowledged
that ''these peripheral estates grew up lacking the local economic base
. . . needed to sustain them as viable communities.''
But that acknowledgement of one historical mistake has not prevented
officials from repeating it this time round. When the 1993 follow-up
document, Progress in Partnership, was published, it stated: ''The main
route to increased employment is to improve links to economic
development outwith the areas, and the creation of employment within the
areas is a secondary objective.''
Unsurprisingly, the initiatives in Castlemilk, Ferguslie Park,
Whitfield, and Wester Hailes have focused on improving the housing stock
and the rest of the built environment. As far as jobs are concerned, the
emphasis has been confined to the kind of training and counselling
designed to help people get on their bikes, Tebbit-style, and compete
for jobs, wherever these jobs happen to be located in the wider
travel-to-work area.
Such thinking is spawning more apocalyptic official visions. When the
Scottish Office Environment Department responded to the Strathclyde
stucture plan last year, officials pointed out that, while Glasgow's
population had declined by 11% between 1981 and 1990, Eastwood's had
grown by 13%. ''This'', they pointed out, ''seems to us to raise
important questions about the likely future level of population of the
city.''
Webster argues that public policy has contributed directly to the
city's relative decline. The creation of a string of new towns and
enterprise zones around Glasgow; the bypassing of the city as a favoured
location for inward investment; disproportionately favourable shares of
Government industrial assistance going elsewhere; failure to redevelop
inner-city brownfield industrial sites -- all these aspects of public
policy have contributed to inexorable urban decline.
His own statistical analysis of census returns challenges the central
assumption in that policy stance. Webster shows that, even in relatively
advantaged areas, by far the largest percentage of people seek to live
and work in their home area. That is as true of Eastwood and Bearsden as
it is of Castlemilk and Springburn. When people travel elsewhere to
work, Webster demonstrates, the share of jobs they take in other areas
falls away far more dramatically with distance than common sense would
suggest. Even after a few kilometres, the percentage shares of jobs
captured are typically in the 0%-2% range. For those taking Norman
Tebbit's advice, the job pickings are relatively thin.
Webster is convinced that the current Scottish Office orthodoxy on
urban renewal dates from the mid-1980s when an analysis of Gear, the
Glasgow Eastern Area Renewal programme, by Pieda and the University of
Glasgow, explicitly rejected the idea that such programmes could have
any significant impact on economic regeneration, although that had been
one of Gear's core aims. ''The high unemployment experienced by (Gear)
residents'', the Pieda report concluded, ''reflects their social and
economic characteristics (eg, low education and skill levels) rather
than a lack of local employment opportunities.''
That approach, Webster believes, has since become enshrined in
Scottish Office policy, although the claims which underpin it are -- on
his analysis -- at best unproven and, at worst, erroneous. This week's
Scottish Office restructuring suggests that, so far, all his warnings
are falling on deaf official ears. Worse, that orthodoxy is becoming
even more entrenched.
</TEXT>
