<DOCNO>GH950519-000051</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000051</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JACK MCLEAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>978321595</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHEN wee Denis Mooney of Scottish telly was a backroom boy in the
business he was ever persuasive. Since he became a frontman for the
Scottish Action programme he has developed an approach which would do
for that of one of Bertie Wooster's aunts: in short, one finds oneself
doing the most remarkable things. Like appearing in front of camera for
one of his programmes when one knows that Scottish would pay two Lees
Macaroon bars for an hour-long interview with Clara Bow in the nude.
Thus I found myself being filmed in Heraghty's Bar on the Soo-Side of
Glasgow.
Let me put you straight about this Heraghty's Bar. I have used this
establishment as my club, office, and psychiatrist's couch for many
years. I have filmed in it often. Indeed, if there is a pub in the whole
of the British islands which has been filmed more often in I shall be
surprised. Astonished even. The lights, camera, action is never far away
from this institution.
So just last Tuesday the Urban V was back before the cameras and so
was Heraghty's. It is for a very short little piece indeed for a show by
Denis. Titled The A to Z of Glasgow. He and his team had shot a similar
piece about Edinburgh the week before. Hardly a new idea really, I
should have thought. Godfrey Smith, the English columnist, once wrote a
splendid tome called The Englishman's Companion which had much the same
notion. You look to an item which sums up things and do it by the
alphabet. Therefore under ''B'' in Mooney's short film, it is Bevvy.
This item was shot in Heraghty's Bar. ''H'' was for Heraghty's. They
shot that in Heraghty's Bar. A little later came an item for ''J''. This
stood for Jack McLean, ie, me. What else? They shot that in Heraghty's
too. Cheap really. Incidentally they had ''V'' represented by Vinegar,
the stuff you spray on fish and chips. Denis filmed that round the
corner from Heraghty's.
You will just have to wait to see the short little film to get the
rest of the subjects contained in this alpabetti spaghetti of the mind
of Scottish Television. Monday night at 10pm will do. Some of it makes
you think that you are not right in the head but that is the way of
telly. I have a dream of getting Chris Evans, Jonathan Ross, and Noel
Edmonds altogether in the Cairngorms next winter but only wearing
plimsolls and cycle shorts.
Why stop there? That Anthea lassie on brekky TV could join them with
gusto. Nobody on Scot FM would even be permitted the cycle shorts.
Needless to say the mountain rescue squads will have been disbanded. A
worthy and fitting end to them all. Let us get back to the filming.
Nothing makes any sense in TV filming. I once did a film for Scottish,
the plot of which revolved around the idea that I had been warned off
the sauce and was going to rattle the last wee goldie before I clung on
to the wagon in the most difficult pub to reach in Britain, which is in
Knoydart. We spent four days shooting the film. Last wee goldie? The
entire shoot was so packed full of last wee goldies that STV took to
calling the entire boozy cruise: Moydart in Knoydart. I remember we had
to film across the road from the pub we had allegedly kicked off from:
yes, my little South Side club.
The camera boys couldn't get it even after God knows how many takes.
Every time we got the cue a bus or a lorry passed by, obscuring my bit
of business. Once three fire engines raced across in front of the
lenses. And lastly came the children of the nearby primary school,
whooping away like the Iroquoi nation, prancing in front of camera and
waving to their grannies. Eventually I myself, the mere performer, came
up with the solution. ''Hal, luvvie'', I said to the producer, ''Go
round the corner to the Classic Cafe and buy 10 quid's worth of Mars
Bars for them.''
We withheld the box of confectionery from the pests until we contrived
to finish the filming of that sequence which took all of 30 seconds, and
then distributed the goodies so the midget bleeders could go off to
work, rest, and play to their content. Incidentally I recollect that the
wee short film won a European award. Sod all to do with me, apart from
my ruse concerning Mars Bars.
But all that is as nothing to the curious idea that soundmen and
camera people have that ''just one more take'' is going to provide
perfection. What another take provides in fact is a living for the boys
and girls in the production team and a pain in the arse for performers
like me. But then wee Denis can be awful persuasive. I got a dram for my
trouble. Ach, and a bit of fun.
</TEXT>
