<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000052</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000052</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Figures on the landscape</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JULIE DAVIDSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>978321596</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HMMM. The mountaineer, it says here, finds the last 3000ft of
Everest's north ridge slow going. ''At that altitude, and with no
artificial oxygen, climbing 10ft feels like the equivalent of 100ft on a
Scottish mountain. He or she will manage 10 steps, then have to stop and
rest.''
Isn't that the way everyone climbs mountains? For one who finds each
10ft of the Scottish mountains the equivalent of 100ft in the Himalayas,
it's my favoured technique. But I shouldn't be so modest; while the
heroic Alison Hargreaves was hauling herself to the top of the world I
was sitting in the bar of the Loch Torridon Hotel looking, with
stupendous self-satisfaction, at the summit of Beinn Alligin.
Been there, done that. Is it possible? Across the loch the mountain's
daylight elegance is masked by dusk. Beinn Jekyll is turning into Mount
Hyde; shadows fill the great quaigh of Coir' nan Laoigh and wipe out the
definition of ridges, shoulders, and Horns -- all the inviting stepping
stones to the top. Alligin retreats into its primeval rock. Its
monstrous silhouette, like some beast of pre-history, looks inviolable.
The rocks remain; or as Hugh MacDiarmid had it, there are many ruined
buildings in the world but no ruined stones. We know what he meant,
though the literal mind might point to the climatic erosion which, only
30 million years ago, carved the Torridon mountains out of sandstone
over 600 million years old.
It's not quite so many years since I last visited this ancient wedge
of Wester Ross but it's a long time, and I'm cheered by its defiance.
Despite all the interfering efforts of the Scottish Tourist Board,
Highland region, and the National Trust it has changed little. It
remains the quintessential corner of the West Highland seaboard, with
all the emotional contradictions of its glorious wilderness:
heartbreakingly, heartsoothingly empty, heartmeltingly beautiful in
sunshine, heartsinkingly grim in glaur.
To burst into tears or burst into applause -- these are the only
possible responses to a May twilight on Upper Loch Torridon. As already
mentioned I'm also bursting with pride, because despite the late
snowfields and fresh frosting on the famed triptych of Alligin,
Liathach, and Eighe I have outmanoeuvred the conditions and followed my
own yellow streak to breach Beinn Alligin at a weak spot; even if the
route devised is treated with contempt by all the guide books. In fact,
it isn't even treated as a route.
The pages of this newspaper are often filled with boisterous accounts
of ''airy scrambling'' on famous ridges but years ago, on the final
approach to Sgurr Alasdair in the Cuillins, I had one serious exposure
to ''exposure'' -- that innocent euphemism for the experience of walking
along the tops of precipices -- and lost my head for heights. These
days, it's the tourist route or nothing.
Beinn Alligin is my husband's idea. ''An exquisitely scuptured
mountain of great beauty,'' he says, reading from Irvine Butterfield's
The High Mountains Companion. ''. . . the least complex of the three
mountains,'' he says, reading from Hamish Brown's entry in the SMC's The
Munros. ''The name means the Jewel Mountain,'' he says, reading from W H
Murray's The West Highlands of Scotland.
I say, reading from my centre of gravity, ''Is there a tourist
route?'' But there is no designated tourist route up Beinn Alligin.
Either you traverse the Horns, with ''some exposed, but perfectly easy
scrambling'' (which was what they told me on Sgurr Alasdair) or you go
up the steep Coir' nan Laoigh; and I can see that the corrie is patched
with snowfields, possibly glaciated.
The imagination ferments: ''Mountain Madness -- Couple Helicoptered
off Alligan'' at best, ''Tragedy in Torridon'' at worst. The humiliation
of being called ''unfit'' or ''underequipped'' for the conditions. No
crampons, no ice axe, no survival bag.
The mountain, like Liathach, stays with us through dinner in the Loch
Torridon Hotel, which is the best possible base camp for armchair
climbers. I watch the corrie from the bar, the dining room, the drawing
room, the library, our bedroom, and even our loo. Washing my hands,
brushing my teeth, I scrutinise the gradient, the scree, the snowfields;
even if we pick our way between them, might there not be black ice?
''There must be another way up,'' I mutter. ''Let me have a look at that
little book.'' My husband has been raving about the good sense and
careful detail of a walker's guide to Torridon by a man called Peter
Barton, who lives in Shieldaig.
Mr Barton sounds like our kind of hillwalker; to him goes the credit
for nudging us in the direction of our very own tourist route.
I discover it not under ''Mountain Ascents'' but under ''Long and High
Level Walks.'' Like everyone else Peter Barton mentions Coir' Nan Laoigh
and the Horns as the conventional routes to the top but in his account
of a walk round Beinn Alligin he slips in this reference: ''As you
continue round the impressive cliffs of Sgurr Mhor you may be surprised
to find these giving way to grass slopes leading to the summit. These
offer an easy and almost direct route to the summit . . . 1400ft and
half a mile away . . . its ascent is not part of this walk; but if you
feel tempted . . .''
We feel tempted. The next day, after three hours of rough but
exhilarating circumvention, we decorously mount the ridge between
Alligin's two tops of Tom na Gruagaich and Sgurr Mhor from the
north-west. We have crossed waterfalls, lunched beside lochans, gazed
hypnotically across great glacial scoops at the intimidating crags of
Liathach, Beinn Dearg, and Baosbheinn. And we have been the only figures
on this landscape of blasted beauty.
There's another good reason for improvising our tourist route. We hit
the ridge at a grassy saddle, and the whole vertiginous bowl of the
Jewel Mountain falls away below us, opening up views across the Horns to
Letterewe and Fisherfield, and across the awesome precipices of Tom na
Gruagaich to Ben Damph Forest and Applecross. My breath shortens and my
knees weaken.
Suddenly the mountain is busy. As we climb the last stepladder stretch
to Sgurr Mhor men, women, and even a child converge from the recommended
routes. One gung-ho young chap stomps past irritably, anxious to reach
the top before us. We have met him at the start of our walk; he knows
nothing of our sneaky sidestepping round the mountain but seems to be
wondering how two such obvious softies have managed to overtake him.
The race, my friend, isn't always to the strong.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000053</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000053</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The kind of job you never see advertised</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>TOM SHIELDS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>DIARY</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>978321597</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE is nothing quite like a spot of lasciviousness in the name of
art.
The Blue Moon cafe in Edinburgh is offering an exhibition of
photographs by one Della Grace.
It is imaginatively entitled Hermaphrodykey and is a collection which
''goes beyond the boundaries of butch/femme, male/female and aims to
stir the desires, regardless of gender and sexual positioning''. Della
describes her work as representing ''a subculture of sexual deviants,
lascivious lesbians and gender-bending perverts''.
Della learnt to take snaps at the San Francisco Art Institute
simultaneously ''discovering leather sex and the joys of driving a motor
cycle cross country on mescaline. From here she found a way to make her
life and art synonymous.''
A few obvious questions spring to mind:
* Why do you never see these kind of jobs advertised?
* What exactly does she mean by sexual positioning?
* What kind of motorbike runs on mescaline and is it not awfy
expensive by the gallon?
* This Blue Moon place. Is it anything to do with relative sexual
positioning on a frequency scale?
Making waves
WE do not often turn our attention to a periodical called Utility
Week, the weekly magazine for utilities management. But we make an
exception to quote one of their reports which qualifies for the Diary's
Nation Once Again Department.
Under the heading ''English firms chase Scottish water deals'', we
read: ''The new Scottish water structure opens up exciting contract
prospects for cross-utility consortia which are not possible in
Britain.'' So, it's official. We can burn those Union flags.
Sad day
TO our Haud Me Back events section we feel we must add the fun day at
Kildare Park in Lanark which is being hosted by local funeral directors
Dorricott and Bent in aid of funds for Lanimer Day.
Shotgun wedding
WE try, honest, to avoid in this column material which is not just so.
But we do get tempted as in the case of an announcement which appeared
in the engagement column of the Oban Times, that bulwark of the West
Highland establishment. It reads: ''Small-Ritchie. Both families are
devastated to announce the engagement between M'Titza Small and M'Bosa
Ritchie, both of 6 Woodlea, Barbreck, by Lochgilphead.'' We could, of
course be totally wrong in the conclusions to which we have jumped and
there may be a couple of Afro-Scottish origin who have settled happily
in deepest Argyll.
Night school
WE are sorry but the innuendo continues. We are in receipt of a
leaflet detailing a ''marriage preparation'' course at Carberry Tower, a
college over Musselburgh way. It is entitled An Overnight Course for
Engaged Couples.
The name game
THE bad taste continues with a lawyer who had the task of defending a
chap accused of indecent exposure in Hove. A Mr Arscott.
For the record
LET us go upmarket and talk about Yes, the nice new restaurant which
Ferrier Richardson has opened in West Nile Street, Glasgow.
Ferrier, being a cultured type, has formalised that delightful
southern European business of soaking some nice bread in olive oil and
eating it while you wait for the starters to arrive.
The Diary, being far-travelled and un poco pretencioso, has always
done this but it usually involves spilling the olive oil all over the
table.
At Ferrier's new place, all the kit is in place. A bottle of the extra
virgin olive oil complete with pourer. A selection of delicious rolls
with various fillings including sun-dried tomatoes, olives, and parmesan
cheese -- some of which, lucky-bag style, you do not know the flavour of
until you break it open.
And last, but not least, a small white dish in which to pour the oil.
There has been one slight problem with the usage of Ferrier's
inventive dunking kit. Your average diner uses the oil dish as an
ashtray. The record, so far, for the number of ash-filled oil
receptacles removed by patient staff is six. Held by my dear colleague,
political editor Geoffrey Parkhouse.
No picnic
NEXT month sees the beginning of Wildlife Week 1995 during which
parents and children alike will be invited to participate in such events
as bat barbecues and spider workshops.
The reality is that you don't get to grill those horrible flappy
winged wee creatures nor get to listen to really interesting seminars by
clever arachnids.
The week, organised by an outfit called Wildlife Watch, consists of
various social functions where picnics are allied to wee jaunts where
kids can dip into nature.
All very well, we say, but is it not a sad day when children have to
be programmed to forage into the wildlife which surrounds them?
Whatever happened to fishing for bagaminnies? Whatever happened to
howking about the privet hedge for the pupae and larvae which, after
careful storage, would emerge as beautiful winged creatures?
Whatever happened to hunkering down in the grass and watching a
ladybird take flight without it all being part of a workshop?
Can we please have our countryside and our childhood back? Now.
Near misses
WE still cannot profess ourselves entirely satisfied with our dear
readers' attempts to find a suitably irreverent acronym for British
Airways. We can report two minor prize-winning air misses. Robert Brown
of Pollokshields, Glasgow, offers Bloody Rat-arsed Immediately Takeoff
Is Sounded having Already Imbibed Recklessly Within Airport's Yuppy
Saloon.
Colin H Kerr pessimistically pens Before Riding In The Ideal Sky Hotel
Alert Inlaws Regarding Will And Savings.
* A caller with absolutely no pity recommends we extend the acronym
search to cars and suggests: Fiat -- Faults in All Types; Lada -- Laugh
at Daft Automobile; and Porsche -- Perk of Rich Stockbroker Coining High
Earnings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000054</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000054</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A church to be recommended</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>978321598</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I WAS very interested in the Open Forum article by Gerry McSherry, but
much more so by the comments of the Rev Kenneth Macaulay (May 12).
I was baptised into the Church of Scotland, attended a school
dominated by that institution and in due course was ordained an elder.
In all that time I never felt any sense of belonging to ''The Church''
and never experienced any uplift whatsoever. Sunday attendance was a
chore and I looked at my watch more often than I looked at the minister.
Three years ago, a friend took me to a service in the Scottish
Episcopal Church, and the difference was nothing short of miraculous.
The warmth of the welcome, the feeling of belonging, and the sense of
spiritual well-being and tranquillity were overwhelming. I have now been
confirmed and am a faithful and enthusiastic attender.
I can certainly recommend it, and all non-football fans like myself
will be pleased to know that the support of Partick Thistle is not
obligatory.
William M Sprowl,
Rowan Cottage,
Rothesay.
</TEXT>
