<TEXT>
IN response to my recent article on the subject of the anachronistic
1918 Education Act (May 9), Veronica Fox (May 15) quite rightly pleads
for ''a reasoned and well-informed debate on the Act''.
However, she then proceeds to launch the most unreasoned and
ill-informed onslaught against both myself and the article. She cannot
have it both ways.
In truth, her ''contribution'' to the debate on the Act amounts to
nothing more than a vain attempt to ingratiate herself even further with
the Roman Catholic hierarchy in Scotland (those who have no children).
Further, her letter does indeed strongly reek of the Roman Catholic
parent's ''highly irrational fear'' of those who have no children of
which I spoke in the article. Why else the cheap sycophancy?
As one who has found true Christianity by summarily rejecting the
pseudo-religious psychobabble, practised, perfected, and preached by the
organisation that is Roman Catholicism (and remember, Christianity is
never to be confused with Roman Catholicism) can I, as a true Christian,
extend my heartfelt sympathies to all Roman Catholic parents, including
the unfortunate Veronica Fox?
After all, it is not their fault that they were shanghaied into Roman
Catholicism at a very early age indeed. Like them, I too suffered, but
now that those who have no children no longer possess any physical,
psychological, emotional, or spiritual hold over myself that suffering
is at an end. Christ knows that's true.
Gerry McSherry,
3 Skye Road,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
