<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Council services and CCT</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>978321601</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NICOLA REEVES argues that the principle of Compulsory Competitive
Tendering must be right because local authorities are monopoly providers
of council services (May 11). She is mistaken.
The problem is that the Government's legislation has had nothing do
with with improving services or council efficiency. CCT has meant a
decline in standards in many areas, particularly where contracts have
been awarded to the private sector.
The Government's aim has been to force councils to award contracts on
the basis of lowest cost -- quality of service has never entered the
equation.d
Her comments on the Equal Opportunities Commission report about the
effects of CCT also fail to mention the waste of public money involved.
The EOC concludes that compulsory tendering has produced savings of
around #124m a year. However, the overall cost of CCT amounts to #250m a
year thrugh higher social security spending and reduced income from
taxes and national insurance.
Nicola Reeves is right to condemn the effect CCT has had on women
workers and on equal opportunities. But she should also have condemned
the whole nasty business which has undermined quality of service at the
public's expense. The underlying aim of CCT has been to reduce workers'
pay and conditions of service and, whilst the EOC rightly highlights the
disproportionate effect on women, the policy itself deserves to be
consigned to the scrapheap.
Mark A Irvine,
Head of Local Government (Scotland),
Unison,
60 Belford Road,
Edinburgh.
</TEXT>
