<HEADLINE>Education cuts</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>978321602</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DICK LOUDEN wrote of the iniquity of expecting the universities to
cater for increased student numbers while faced with cuts in funding,
called ''efficiency savings'', year after year (May 9).
At least no university is reported as experiencing a reduction in
actual funding. The situation is very different for further education
colleges where the progress towards application of the funding formula
has led to a situation described by one member of staff at the Scottish
Office Education Department as ''one of winners and losers''.
The reality of that statement has already been reported in the need
for Falkirk College to reduce its staff by the equivalent of 35
lecturers in the coming year and the Scottish Further and Higher
Education Association has information that suggests that several Glasgow
colleges will require to reduce staffing. Compulsory redundancies cannot
be ruled out.
Things will not get better in future years as the Government intends
that the global sum allocated to FE is to be cut each year in the
foreseeable future.
Two years ago the status of colleges was changed; they became
''incorporated''. At the time it was said that this was to free them
from the shackles of local authority control. Now we know the real
reason.
Local authorities would have resisted such funding cuts with the
ultimate weapon of maintaining the service by transferring the cost to
the ratepayers and making sure that the ratepayers, who are also voters,
knew where the blame really lay.
The colleges were transferred to allow cuts in funding to pay for the
''tax cuts'' that the Conservatives use to buy votes.
It must now be clear to everyone that tax cuts always result in a
reduction of standards of the service that we expect and deserve from
the state.
Kenneth W Johnson
Alves,
Westgates Avenue,
Lochwinnoch.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
