<HEADLINE>Interpreting what Mr Rifkind means</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>978321603</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MR Malcolm Rifkind is reported to have said that the vast majority of
Scots would like a Scottish parliament or assembly, but want to remain
part of the United Kingdom.
He had no difficulty with the principle but reconciling these
aspirations is difficult -- presumably because of the West Lothian
factor where Scots can vote on English matters but English MPs could not
vote on Scottish affairs.
Yet this Government will give Northern Ireland an assembly. Irish MPs
will still be able to vote on English matters but the English will not
vote on Ulster affairs.
So Mr Rifkind, who is recognised as a distinguished lawyer, finds the
West Lothian factor insuperable, yet his Government can solve the West
Belfast factor.
That logic is absolutely fabulous.
Frank McDermid,
8 Boghall Street,
Stonehouse.
</TEXT>
