<HEADLINE>Making John Major feel at home</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>978321605</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IF I should find the Prime Minister standing on my doorstep, I would
like to invite him in and give him a cup of tea made with unquangoised,
publicly-owned water.
Should he be unlucky enough to scald himself by spilling his tea, then
I would like to be able to call for a publicly-owned ambulance to take
him to an adequately staffed National Health Service hospital, manned by
properly rested doctors and well paid nurses, supported by cleaners,
porters, and other staff whose wages could not drop below the minimum as
set by the Social Chapter of the Maastricht Treaty.
Should Mr Major be severely injured, then I would hope that he would
avoid destitution by qualifying for the new Incapacity Benefit.
I would then like to escort him to a publicly-owned railway station
and put him on board a publicly-owned train, fuelled by publicly-owned
electricity and running on publicly-owned railway lines, and, as he was
returned, timeously, to Huntingdon, I would wish him well and wave my
Saltire in salutation.
Margaret M H Lyth,
26 Gardenside Street,
Uddingston.
</TEXT>
