<DOCNO>GH950519-000064</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000064</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Myth that Bruce was French</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>978321608</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BY attempting to destroy one myth in Scottish history, Duncan Bryson
yet again perpetuates another, namely that Robert the Bruce was French
(May 5).
The reality of the situation is that, prior to Bruce's birth at
Turnberry in 1274, his family had been established in Scotland for five
generations.
His mother, Marjorie, was the daughter of Niall, Earl of Carrick, and
had a distinctly Celtic background.
There is little or no evidence that families with Norman origins, such
as Bruce's, saw themselves, or were generally regarded, as different
from the other noble families of Scotland during the period in question.
While he may have spoken French, Robert the Bruce was no more French
than the majority of peoples of South America are Spanish (or Portuguese
in the case of Brazil).
B G Bennett,
29 Ormonde Avenue,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000065</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000065</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Myth that Bruce was French</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>978321609</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALEX FLEMING is right that the Normans were originally Scandinavians
(largely Danish) invaders and settlers, but by the eleventh century had
adopted Frankish culture and language (May 13).
The text beneath one of the scenes in the Bayeux Tapestry reads:
''Where the English and the Franks fell in battle.''
I do not agree that Brus was a seventh-generation Scot. Certainly, his
family held lands in Annandale since 1124, but they also held lands in
Yorkshire. His father was a Constable of Carlisle Castle. His
grandfather served Henry III as a judge.His
great-great-great-grandfather appealed to David I before the Battle of
the Standard: ''Since when, my lord, I ask thee, hast thou found such
faith in Scots that thou dost with such confidence divest and deprive
thyself and thine of the council of the English, even the help of the
Normans, as if Scots would suffice alone for thee even against Scots?''
Duncan Bryson,
109 Martin Avenue,
Irvine.
</TEXT>
