<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000066</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000066</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The House and Nolan</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>LEADER</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>978321610</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE United Kingdom has been blessed by a remarkably open and honest
political culture which certainly bears comparison with any other.
Indeed, it would be hard to identify another which is demonstrably
superior, especially over any long period of time. That needs to be
said, and remembered, in case the contemporary preoccupation with sleaze
gets out of hand to the extent that we ignore the reality. The
revelations involved in the exposures of the past few years are worrying
because they are unusual, though those involving sexual relationships
may tell as much about the national fascination with this aspect of life
as the proclivities of politicians. The examples of financial corruption
and constitutional impropriety are another matter, but the Prime
Minister may have allowed himself to be stampeded into setting up the
Nolan Committee before considering whether the House of Commons did not
already possess itself the capacities and the will to tackle the clear
failings of some of its own Members. He wanted to ensure that not only
would the collective reputation of the House be enhanced, but that it
would be seen to be enhanced. He is now landed with the recommendations
of the committee but the House need not accept all of them. It must
maintain its own authority, even though the broad thrust of the Nolan
proposals is probably acceptable to the generality of MPs, as it is also
to the Government and the Opposition in their partisan modes.
Some MPs, for whom Sir Edward Heath, as the Father of the House, has
made himself the spokesman, are resentful of some Nolan recommendations.
In particular they are hostile to the proposal that MPs should be banned
from working for lobbying companies. The House should support them and
reject the proposal firmly, even though Labour, which has fewer Members
contracted to lobbyists (apart from trade union sponsors), will back the
prohibition. The idea that a Member of Parliament should have no contact
and direct financial involvement wih particular interests is hard to
sustain. What would be wrong is that such contacts -- and contracts --
should be concealed. There is nothing wrong with business, and other
interest groups from animal rights supporters to trade unions, seeking
to influence Government through particular parliamentary spokesmen.
There would be everything wrong with their trying to buy that influence.
In that connection the role of business and organised labour in funding
political parties demands addressing (as the Lib-Dems propose to do next
month in the House of Lords), but it has never been shown in the past
that such funding bought specific benefits, apart from honours. And the
only indisputable evidence of the buying of honours involved the
activities of Lloyd George.
Like any other random collection of over 600 people, MPs will contain
a wide spectrum of personalities, intelligences, and capacities. It
would be surprising if they did not contain some individuals unworthy of
the trust and honour their status confers. Perceptions of the collective
quality of the House vary, with some finding a decline in recent years
while others see a favourable comparison with the latter decades of the
past century. The membership tends to represent a cross-section of the
public-spirited membership of the community, with a decided bias to the
professional classes, notably the law and the communications industry
(using that term as shorthand for a wide body ranging from academics and
teachers to journalists). It is not well paid considering its importance
and the way in which the Government -- and any alternative Government --
is composed from its ranks. This relatively poor financial status
explains why many MPs seek to augment their salaries by outside work,
but the case for allowing them to go on doing so has even stronger
foundations. Parliament has always enjoyed the full-time professional
politician (at least since Walpole's day) but it has benefited mightily
also from the services of those whose contribution derived its weight
from their outside knowledge and interests. Such Members should continue
to flower as long as the public is aware of the financial arrangements
which irrigate their roots.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000067</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000067</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scottish takeover doubts</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>LEADER</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>978321611</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WITH a mighty leap -- and large rights issue -- Scottish and Newcastle
has become the largest brewer in Britain. By buying Courage from the
Australian company Fosters, the Scottish company has displaced Bass as
the country's top brewer, strengthening its position in the English
Midlands and marching everywhere south of the Thames. Few takeovers
confer such a neat geographical fit, and as this was widely heralded in
advance it may not evoke an automatic reference to the Monopolies and
Mergers Commission though it leaves Scottish with a quarter of Britain's
beer sales. There may be some job losses but nothing specific is being
said yet, and they could turn out to be fairly modest though more likely
to be in the north at the Tadcaster and Halifax breweries than those at
Bristol and Reading. In fact for a business with such an enormous
turnover, Courage's labour force of fewer than 5000 workers hardly seems
excessive. Redundancies may be focused on the company's headquarters at
Staines where concern is already being expressed.
Doubts about the move will surface all the same. Beer sales are not
growing fast, though this move does enhance Scottish's exposure to some
''fancy'' foreign beers which enjoy considerable popular appeal, like
Foster's lagers themselves (where brewing rights for the UK, Ireland,
and Europe are being acquired) and the American Budweiser. Scottish did
not acquire Foster's large pub chain, but that would have invited the
attention of the Monopolies Commission for the Government has been
trying to loosen the links between producers of beer and the outlets to
consumers. Scottish already has its own clutch of pubs and, like
Whitbread, has moved firmly into the restaurant business as British
attitudes to drink have steadily broadened to include food. It also has
a large stake in wine sales, if much less than Whitbread's which owns
the successful Threshers chain.
The fact is that all the large brewers have diversified from the
traditional product as national habits have changed. We are moving away
from pubs towards home consumption of drinks. Even the undoubted
attractions of draught beer which formerly needed the pub are now in
great measure being met by cans (though connoisseurs are not easily
convinced). Pubs themselves have been greatly improved and in both
Scotland and the north of England Scottish has been a major proponent of
this trend. The drinks industry has become enormous and requires the
critical mass which this deal confers. Its need for size and economies
of scale coexists with a new awareness of the attractions of boutique
producers and sellers. These come and go out of fashion and in response
to financial pressures. The big companies have to have different
strategies for they need continuity and the financial strength necessary
to operate in world markets. That is the context in which this enormous
deal has been made. It could hardly have been envisaged when Foster took
over Courage less than a decade ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000068</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000068</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Crucial question governing role of the lobbyists</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRIAN WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>978321612</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE occasion was the Report Stage of this year's Finance Bill and the
subject was a proposed new tax on non-gaming machines in amusement
arcades. I had, very properly, been approached on the matter by
constituents who run arcades in Largs and Saltcoats. They pointed out to
me why the tax was not a good idea. In return, Lord Nolan, I was not
offered so much as a free ride on the dodgems.
Sir Jerry Wiggin rose to speak. ''I am,'' he declared, ''an adviser to
the British Holiday and Home Parks Association.'' He was followed by a
Tory MP for Hendon, Sir John Gorst -- these guys are all ''Sirs'' -- who
announced coyly: ''I am also an adviser to the industry.''
I was moved to comment that it sounded more like a consultants'
convention than a debate in the House of Commons. It was also a good
illustration of the extent to which ''consultancy'' has become endemic
to both the procedures of Parliament and the earnings of many MPs.
There is not the slightest doubt that the professionally sponsored
representations of these MP/consultants would have had more impact on
the outcome of this particular little issue than my humble pleadings as
a mere MP, representing constituency interests.
Therein lies a crucial, and unremarked upon, weakness of the system.
Tory Ministers -- perhaps with an eye to their own futures -- pander to
it. They give access to these MP/consultants, in the full knowledge that
they are acting as paid lobbyists for interests which may well have
nothing to do with their constituencies.
Millions of pounds hung on the outcome of that one tiny taxation
issue. Small wonder that the director-general of the British Holiday and
Home Parks Association should have been the only one yesterday with a
good word to say about Wiggins: ''We've found his work highly
satisfactory.'' Of that, I have no doubt.
The more complex the legislation, the greater the value of the
lobbyist's role. If they can get a highly technical amendment into the
hands of an MP, then they are off and running. They have opened up a
dialogue which will engage Ministers and civil servants. A skilfully run
lobbying campaign will often then result in changes to the proposed
legislation. Something like the Gas Bill is an absolute paradise for the
lobbyists. The financial implications are vast. The complexities are
immense. The language of the legislation is impenetrable. If, out of
this jungle, a successful amendment can emerge, couched in equally
obscure terms, then the likelihood is that nobody would notice except
the beneficiary!
The incredible act of stupidity on the part of Sir Jerry Wiggin was to
table such an amendment in the name of another MP, without consent. I
would have thought at, even then, it would have been prudent to choose
someone slightly less well-known than Sebastian Coe.
In his political existence, Mr Coe performs a fair impersonation of a
frightened rabbit. It is no surprise that he went into Olympic sprint
mode, to distance himself from the first whiff of scandal. If, instead,
Sir Jerry had squared it with a more battle-hardened veteran, the world
would be none the wiser.
It is utterly pointless to say that lobbyists shouldn't exist, or
suggest that MPs should not liaise with them where there are issues of
mutual interest. The crucial question is whether, in that process, the
MP has maintained his or her independence, or whether he has effectively
been hired by the lobbying interest.
That is the issue on which not even Lord Nolan has gone far enough. I
have never been able to see why the rule of the council chamber should
not also apply in the House of Commons. If an MP has a financial
interest to declare, he should also withdraw from the Chamber and
refrain from voting. If he fails to act in that way, he is guilty of a
criminal act. That would soon put an end to it.
It will be very interesting to see how the Tories respond to the key
recommendations (in this area at least) from the Nolan Committee --
''full disclosure of consultancy agreements and payments''; and a
''review (of) the merits of allowing MPs to hold consultancies.''
Nolan said that the issue of trade union sponsorship should also be
subject to the same examination, and he is absolutely right. Personally,
I am not sponsored and have no wish to be. But the reality which
separates union sponsorship from consultancy work is that no Labour MP
gains a personal penny from that relationship. That is the distinction
which an inquiry will bring out.
Over at Perth and Kinross, I fear that Mr Godfrey will have to wait
awhile for his consultancies. The only Tory posters which I have seen
tend to be very large ones, leering out from bales of hay or yellow
fields full of rape-seed subsidy. All this proves is that big, rich
farmers vote Tory which is not a terrific incentive to the rest of the
population.
I said at the outside the result of this by-election could become
interesting if the 54% of intending SNP voters who (according to System
Three) do not share the SNP's aim of an independent Scotland could feel
''liberated'' to vote Labour, without any risk of the Tories winning. It
is now clear that the precondition of the Tories not winning has been
fulfilled, and there is a lot of movement among the voters as a result.
I was never daft enough to say that Labour would win, but there are
certainly some interesting stirrings outside the Tory voting fields and
hay-stacks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000069</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000069</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Disgraceful attack on Labour</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>978321613</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS a Labour Party member of many years' standing, I write in reply to
the quite disgraceful article by that ex-communist politician Jimmy Reid
who once again reveals his real agenda, donning the clothes of the hard
left to attack the Labour Party in your paper in the article headed The
lost vision (May 13).
It's a bit hard to take coming from people such as Jimmy Reid who
never had a vision in the first place to cast aspersions on the Labour
Party which now has the overwhelming support of the people of this
country.
The old Glasgow saying that ''everyone is out of step bar my boy''
applies to Jimmy Reid in this case. Working people, young and old,
unemployed people, professional people, are voting in their thousands
for the Labour Party, but everybody is out of step bar Jimmy Reid! What
a load of unadulterated rubbish this is.
His reference to worshipping false gods is a bit hard to take coming
from a person whose political life intellectually embraced the worst
excesses of Stalinism and swallowed completely the garbage that emanated
from the Communist Party which claimed to be emancipating the people of
Eastern Europe, but what history has revealed is that it enslaved them
politically and culturally. So let's have less of the rubbish of a
person of that ilk attacking the Lablur Party.
Jimmy Reid is what he always was, a hard-left politician who knows
better than the mass of the people, who is opposed to democratic
socialism and who has revealed himself at this particular time as the
enemy of working men and women when he uses the press to attack the
Labour Party at the present moment when it is in ascendancy. It says a
lot for Jimmy's concern now that he is a journalist, remote from the
reality of working life, that he chooses this occasion and this
particular time to attack the Labour Party.
Well, I have news for him. His political views are those of a
political dinosaur, consigned to the dustbin of history.
The Labour Party will go on, the Labour Party will win the next
election, and the Labour Party will, as it always has, despite the
difficulties , make significant advances for the ordinary men and women
of this country.
Councillor James McCarron,
City Chambers,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000070</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000070</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Strong protest</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>978321614</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
READING The Herald (May 9), we found to our disbelief Hans Teske's
statement about his feelings because his family was removed from the
town of Stolp in 1945 and his father was murdered.
We combatants strongly protest about such a statement. It makes people
think that Poles murdered his father and are murderers. Does he remember
the year 1939 when Germans living in Poland on Hitler's and Goebbels's
order spied?
What about Auschwitz, Treblinka, Belsen, and other concentration camps
where six million Poles, millions of Jews, Hungarians, Czechs and other
nationalities were tortured, murdered by his own people, the SS and the
Gestapo?
We Polish combatants and Polish people are not anti-Germans. It is
time to forgive but not forget, and we hope that peace among the nations
will last for ever.
Major S T Klimowicz,
General Secretary of the Polish Ex-Combatants in Scotland,
26 Glenfarg Street,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000071</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000071</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The Thief of Bagdad, Royal Concert Hall, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MICHAEL TUMELTY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>MAYFEST</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>978321615</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WELL. A night and a half at the movies -- not least in its duration --
in the swashbuckling company of Douglas Fairbanks Sen with Carl Davis
conducting the Royal SNO.
Last of a series of three classic silents, in some ways, The Thief of
Bagdad (1924) was the most stunning of the lot. High melodrama (with
corny titles), buccaneering adventure, and mind-boggling sets and
special effects combined to make a hugely entertaining experience. And
all backed by a very clever score, compiled, composed and conducted by
Carl Davis.
Decades -- nay, more like half a century before their time -- the
special effects of art director William Cameron Menzies stole the show,
lock, stock and barrel. Towering buildings: sleek, elegant and oriental,
suggested no expense spared in the sets.
In a welter of effects -- from flying carpet to winged horse, from
invisibility illusions to Fairbanks Sen sprinkling oofle dust and
creating an instant army -- the undersea scene, brilliantly composed
with Fairbanks in slow motion and his baggy pants billowing exactly as
they would underwater, capped the lot.
Fairbanks own performance -- nimble and lightfooted -- was balletic in
its choreography. No wonder he was dubbed the Nijinsky of the movies:
classical grace married to romantic panache.
Panache galore too from the Royal SNO playing Carl Davis's score,
largely a masterly deconstruction of Rimsky-Korsakov's Scheherazade,
with every motif, every rhythm, and every colour of the Russian
masterpiece, subjected to either literal application or infinite
extension. Equally, the best cuts of the same composer's Golden Cockerel
were called into magical service. First-rate series. More please.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000072</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000072</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ardal O'Hanlon, Dermot Carmody, Tron, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID BELCHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>MAYFEST</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>978321616</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ENTERING on Wednesday night with an electric guitar hanging round his
scrawny neck, the floppily-coiffed Dermot Carmody plainly resembled
Johnny Marr, former axe-hero with the Smiths. But then Johnny Marr never
quite looked as dissipated as Dermot managed to, and if you think about
it, Johnny Marr doesn't have Marty Feldman's attenuated eyeballs lolling
in his face like Dermot does, and here's another strange thing:
rubber-faced Hollywood movie-star Jim Carrey has surely never been as
hyper-active and cartoon-like in the visage department as Dermot,
either.
Similarly, Dermot's humour has many disparate strands. He does funny
musical pastiches, from a whining Bob Dylan via a crazed Patsy Cline to
a sex-hound Prince who is even more bizarre than the original. And he
does a neat job in up-ending Irish cultural stereotypes.
So what does Dermot's compatriot, Ardal, do? Hard to say. The star of
Channel 4's quietly-compulsive Father Ted just shuffles out with a
sleepy, slightly-stunned, hangdog look on his face, and he stands and
witters in an unravelling, punchline-free fashion.
Ardal tells you minutely-detailed things about the house he's just
bought, only he can't remember the details of where the house actually
is, so hasn't that been a waste of money? He speaks about the fickleness
of love; being employed as a Great Plains cow-scratcher; not having an
atrium; giving up God for Lent, and the strain imposed by keeping yawns
in.
No jokes and not a word of sense, but at the night's end, you've sore
cheeks from the continual smiley-chuckles Ardal O'Hanlon has had you
doing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000073</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000073</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hip-hop duo take the rap</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID BELCHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>PROFILE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>978321617</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A new musical genre has emerged on the UK scene. David Belcher
discovers that Earthling music combines well-constructed songs with soul
and funk elements
WHAT'S in a name? Fashionable generic names like trip-hop and
trip-rap. Much-lauded names like Massive Attack and Tricky. Massive
Attack's long-awaited visit to Glasgow transpired to be a massive
disappointment, didn't it? Massive Atrophy.
And what did you make of that sullen, confrontational Tricky laddie
when he supported PJ Harvey? Muttering instead of rapping; mumbling
vague insults at us from the Barrowland stage, shuffling about like a
dooley . . . should we rename him Tripey or Dicky?
But here's a new name -- Earthling -- and a wholly-splendid new
musical genre: Earthling music. Earthling music has hypnotic hip-hop
elements, and eerie looped'n'sampled soul and funk elements, courtesy of
Earthling's musical director, Tim Saul. Earthling music has the wise,
witty and singular words of rapper Mau, who may turn out to be rap's
one-man answer to Bob Dylan, Salvador Dali, and Raymond Carver.
Additionally, Earthling music seduces your ears by deftly deploying the
skewed, honeyed, woozy soul-diva vocals of chanteuse Moni.
And above all, Earthling music features well-contructed songs, despite
the fact that songs have sadly gone out of fashion in recent years. And
Earthling's songs can be playful, frothy things which revel in their own
free-associating poetic nature. Or they can be songs which tell simple
everyday stories. Or they can be incisive narrative creations which
address stark social and political issues: child abuse, rape, drug
addiction, prostitution, and racial disharmony.
All these songs can be found on Earthling's debut album, Radar, which
will be released under on the Cooltempo label on Monday. Listen to it,
as for your own sake you must, and you will gain a new musical
perspective. Because Earthling reside in splendid isolation on the
planet Excellent, and their orbit round our humdrum globe is a
revelatory one.
Actually, Earthling's main duo of Tim Saul and Mau are from Bristol
and the London suburb of Ilford, respectively. Tim has hometown links
with Portishead's Geoff Barrow, but spurns all attempts by journos to
pigeonhole Earthling as part of some happening Bristol trip-hop scene
(man).
''If there has to be a term, British hip-hop is the one we like most.
It's the one we'd encourage journalists to use. Trip-hop . . . no-one
who makes that so-called music would agree that that is what they're
making. It's a term used by some London DJs trying to be friendly and
hip at the same time, in the same way that acid jazz came to be.''
Earthling has yet to be championed by any proprietorial DJs who see
themselves as style gurus at the head of their own nebulous,
trend-driven movement. Partly because Radar is an album for the heart,
mind and soul and not simply the feet. Partly because it blends so many
different musical styles, imagistic viewpoints, personal experiences,
and layers of meaning.
What does the album's title, Radar, mean, for instance? And the LP's
many catchy yet somewhat gnomic refrains -- elliptical slogans like Soup
or no soup -- what do they mean? And have I correctly divined a few
respectful name-checks for the immortal Captain Beefheart? Mau tells
all.
''We called the album Radar because it's a bland word for what we see
as a grand statement of our intentions . . . our music originates from
us two in London, but it spreads out much further. And lyrically and
musically we take from anywhere and everywhere, so we see ourselves as
having an openness . . . the album is about having your antennae
extended to everything. And radar is a whatsit . . . a word that reads
the same backwards as forwards -- a palindrome, which seemed apt, too.
''Soup or no soup is a saying I pinched off my great-grandmother, who
still lives in Ilford. If someone gives you an ultimatum, and you carry
on and do what you were going to do anyway . . . well, you're shrugging
your shoulders and saying: 'Soup or no soup, I'm sticking to my guns . .
. I have self-belief.' ''
Who are Earthling? Two exceptional blokes who met by chance three
years ago through the Musicians Wanted columns of a London free-sheet.
''We arranged to meet at my flat, which is at the top of a converted
church, the one that Reggie Kray got married in,'' says Tim.
Mau's initial awe of the locale turned into a mutual awe of each
other's talents. ''We put together I Could Just Die that afternoon,
using tracks I'd already built up and a rap Mau brought with him. We've
worked together every day since.''
Happy accident informs the creation of Earthling's instrumental
grooves, too. ''When I'm looking for samples, I'm looking for fresh
sounds which have certain characteristics and that no-one else has
sampled,'' says Tim.
''I've actually assembled a collection of totally crap records that
have brilliant sleeve photos. I've got a Millie album which isn't very
good musically, but the cover's great because Millie's sitting on a
giant banana which looks as though it's about to zoom off into outer
space.
''And I've used lots of sounds from an album I've never seen anywhere
else -- Spaced Out: Enoch Lite and His Orchestra Play Bacharach and Bach
-- which has a Barbarella-type figure flying through the stratosphere on
the cover.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000074</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000074</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The Michael Nyman Band, Kings Theatre, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ELIZABETH CLARK</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>MAYFEST</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>978321618</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE music of Michael Nyman tends to split the critical fraternity down
the middle. There are those for whom Nyman serves as the master
minimalist, capable of intoxicating them with his familiar blend of grit
and grace; and there are those for whom he serves as the ultimate in
uninspired boredom, penning tedious repetitions with not an end point in
sight.
Perhaps unusually, this critic prefers to sit on the fence, adjusting
her appreciation depending on the context.
While I can think of fewer recordings I would rather not listen to in
the comfort of my own home, at a concert venue, live and loud, this
music gets me really excited.
In a selection of excerpts from his award-winning film scores, Chasing
Sheep was copybook Nyman, raunch and rhythm over the simplest of
harmonic progressions. In the middle of Eye, as the momentum grew, it
struck me that an interesting comparison can be drawn between this and
rave music. The beat gets into your system and yes, it even makes you
want to dance. Carrington is the forthcoming Christopher Hampton film,
starring Emma Thompson and produced by Scottish-based Freeway Films.
In an unexpected departure from Peter Greenway territory, Nyman's
music remains disappointingly unchanged. Most memorable was an
interactive string episode (in which the Nyman Band was augmented by
eight Scottish players), evocative and wonderfully rhapsodic.
The Piano Suite has become a modern classic revered by a cult
following. They were not to be let down in last night's performance.
Meditative, hypnotic, and utterly passionate, few could have emerged
unmoved by the emotional impact of this, Nyman's richest film score.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000075</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000075</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Walking on Water, The Tramway, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANGUS MALCOLM</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>MAYFEST</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>978321619</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SOMETIMES it is interesting to judge a performance by which personal
state you feel is best suited to its impact. Arc, the dance-installation
show, presented by the Scottish/Canadian company Icehouse, would
gravitate towards a hazy vision.
The set by Robbie Colman neatly fills the small theatre area in The
Tramway, a dark liquid pool, as black as oil, giving perfect reflections
of the three dancers, whose simple movements generate quiet ripples
across the surface. Above them an arc of material, like a jutting
iceberg, reaches towards the audience, carrying swathes of red or blue
lighting framing the action beneath. The piece is intentionally slow
asking the viewer to sit back and allow it to work its magic.
Unfortunately the magic is not delivered by the set of walks, abstract
gestures, and masked expressions which characterise its 50-minute
development.
As with much contemporary dance, it is a hit-or-miss exercise for an
untrained audience, as to whether they will be transported by the
dancers' language or left floundering. In Arc the quality of expression
does not transcend its self-imposed limitations. The ''journey through a
million possible futures which await us'' promised in the advertising
was released only occasionally in a beautifully held image, or the play
of light on well-defined musculature.
In attempting to avoid any definition of meaning within the landscape,
the audience were left pondering the movement of ripples and gentle
sound . . . definitely one for the glazed-eye brigade.
The company looks strong individually on paper, perhaps next time a
more powerful theme will emerge to release their respective talents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000076</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000076</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Geek, CCA, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARY BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>MAYFEST</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>978321620</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JUST to get us in the mood, there's free popcorn -- and glimpses of
other sideshow attractions -- on the way in. We're not actually in the
tent -- we're outside, looking in. And that's where Robert Pacitti and
his fellow performers want us.
While they act the geeks, we will be the voyeurs. They will,
collectively and individually, dangle before us choice morsels of
apparent waywardness. Patriotism, for instance, takes on a rudely
intimate tack as the flag flies from quarters where the sun sure don't
shine . . . Gender will bend with lively flexibility. Sex will rear --
but when it turns nasty, it's because Nanny has the upper hand . . . And
baby was asking for it, just by being there, wasn't he?
Like the geeks of Coney Island, this foursome are the purveyors of
off-line experiences. They are looking to goose our preconceptions of
received values: what it means to be British, white, straight -- in
other words, privileged. The liberties taken with the flag are part of
an onslaught on what is labelled Lie Of The Land. Like the sexual games,
where a nubile Nanny pours out of her uniform even as she pours abuse on
her vulnerable charge, the focus of each section is really to alter the
filter of our viewpoint. You can either laugh, or be offended, but you
can't stay indifferent.
The show still has some rough patches. Inevitable when you are trying
to create a flux of risk-taking and astute pillory. What makes even the
opaque moments worth watching is the sheer class, and courage, of the
performers. Physical nakedness is not the hardest thing to offer an
audience. Exposing your rawest concerns, your own sexual identity, your
own vulnerability -- these are the real tests of integrity: the cast
pass with flying colours.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000077</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000077</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Gaelic elegy</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MICHAEL TUMELTY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>978321621</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MICHAEL TUMELTY reports on a double-first for James MacMillan
THE latest work by leading Scottish composer James MacMillan tonight
receives a double world premiere in London that will be broadcast live
on Radio Three.
Hard on the heels of his choral masterpiece The Seven Last Words,
which last week received an award from the Royal Philharmonic Society,
MacMillan has produced another choral work, Mairi, written for the BBC
Singers.
The BBC's elite choral group -- Britain's only full time professional
chamber choir -- is celebrating its seventieth season with a stream of
commissions: every concert they perform in their birthday series
features a world premiere.
MacMillan's Mairi adapts the text of an eighteenth-century Gaelic
elegy by Evan McColl. Characteristically for MacMillan, the choir will
be divided into multiple parts and will draw on identifiable Scottish
sources -- on this occasion, ancient Celtic music. MacMillan will
introduce the music from the stage of St John's Smith Square in London.
As in each of the BBC Singers' seventieth birthday concerts, the new
work will receive two performances -- one in each half of the concert.
Bo Holten will conduct.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000078</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000078</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ace of clubs</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>SARA VILLIERS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>MAYFEST</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>978321622</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THEY might not have had the nous to throw a press conference but they
sure knew how to throw a party. Whatever the cavils aimed at Mayfest's
artistic programme, one of its biggest successes has undeniably been the
Mayfest Club. Mayfest artistic director Paul Bassett's decision to stage
the club in the city-centre location of the Fruit Market has been a
triumphant one which has packed in crowds night after night.
It certainly couldn't have been worse than last year's atmosphere-free
sojourn at the Becks Tent in Glasgow Green and, arguably, a late-night
club which provides outstandingly good value with three live bands for a
#2 cover charge and with hedonistic drinking hours unhindered by the
blight of the 12.30pm curfew which blankets the rest of the city's clubs
would be a big hit at any time of the year, but that is not to detract
from this year's Mayfest Club's winning formula.
Perhaps its greatest achievement has been in creating an atmospheric
forum for theatre-makers and theatre-goers and putting a sting back into
that much-lauded, much-lamented ''Mayfest buzz''. And while revellers
might get an illicit thrill out of stepping into a drinking den
post-curfew it should be noted that the suspension of the curfew is
singularly Mayfest-related -- the council's concession to the theatre
staff and technical crews who often have to work beyond midnight.
The club started with a bang, with a big bash on Thursday, April 28,
with the colourfully -- and expensively -- decorated Fruit Market
hosting an invited throng of the arts and media mafias. However, when
the same crowd had to stump up the readies for admission the following
evening the club died a dramatic death, with small groups looking rather
lost amid the Fruit Market's cavernous space and bands playing their
hearts out to a desolate dance floor.
Bassett and his staff should be congratulated for their immediate
response to this. They tweaked the formula, abandoned the no-pay area at
the bar, where drinkers were clustering rather than paying to see the
bands, advertised the opening weekend as a freebie loss-leader and
subsequently ironed out the #5 ticket price and #2 concession to a flat
rate of #2 for everyone, enforcing a strict no-more-freebies policy.
A frantic leafleting of local bars ensured the return of the crowds,
with Glasgow's beautiful people dancing the night away to the esoteric
musical line-ups.
Caroline Pierzchalo, the projects manager for the club, can take a pat
on the back for programming the eclectic musical mix combining
contrasting musical genre and up-and-coming talent with more established
names.
The audiences have been just as loyal as the bands and anyone who
hasn't sampled the delights of the Mayfest Club yet would do well to buy
a ticket in advance for the final appearance tonight and tomorrow --
with a crowd capacity of just 650 the events are sure to sell out. See
ya in the queue.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000079</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000079</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Master of faultless flow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHEN MCGINTY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>978321623</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
As a writer you get a physical sense of language, you know what it
feels like, you know what it tastes like.
Author A L Kennedy has reaped much success with her popular novels,
but as Stephen McGinty reports, they are also attracting a slightly mad
audience
WHEN A L Kennedy gives a public reading there is one thing you notice
and it is not the dark Armani suit, though it is a nice bundle of
threads. Nor is it the girls on the floor who watch with awe-tinged
admiration. It is impossible not to notice the slightly mad members of
the audience, like the little old lady in Edinburgh who crept around
asking for the author's personal details from the assistants at
Waterstone's.
But that is not it, though the author has noticed it too. ''I get a
few mad people at readings who stare at you very very intensely, and
other, sometimes intimidating, people who go to readings for the wrong
reasons. It's an attempt to take you back to their flat, I don't know,
maybe to be dinner rather than for dinner.''
At a recent reading in John Smith's bookshop in Glasgow's Byres Road a
lady in a red hat, combat jacket, and jeans sat at the front and fired
questions with the grace of exploding cannonballs.
''What's alchemy?
''Is it a religion like Buddhism?''
''Is Cyrano De Bergerac dead?''
''How can I get to him?''
Through a frozen grin and gritted teeth Kennedy hissed, read the book,
then talked on. It could have been worse. The previous night at the
Princes Street Waterstone's, one man wasn't even let in.
Yet while the novels and short stories of Alison Louise Kennedy can
often contain sex and violence, and a particularly vile combination of
razor blade and snoozing girl which combines both, it is the quiet
moments that catch the reader's breath.
And so with her readings. Despite the subject of the story and the
antics of the audience, eventually you notice that she has not stuttered
or stumbled or mispronounced or misplaced a single word. You'll find no
errs, umms, or ahs on the soundtrack. She reads just like she writes,
with a flow that often cannot be faulted.
Studying drama at Warwick University helped. ''It was all very
self-indulgent but it gave you a feel for words. Drama at university is
very good training if you want to be a writer, it's no good if you want
to act.
''As a writer you get a physical sense of language, you know what it
feels like, you know what it tastes like. I had signed up to do English
but I knew I didn't want to do that when I arrived.
''I know sod all about the language of criticism, alliteration,
metaphors, blah, blah, blah, which is great because that's not how my
mind works. I write so that it feels comfortable to read whether it's
being read out or not. If the music of it is OK then it works.''
When Jennifer M Wilson, the character in Kennedy's latest novel So I
Am Glad, reads out loud it too feels comfortable, for her voice is all
she has. Others write the words; as a radio announcer all she has to do
is speak them clearly, without stuttering, stumbling, mispronouncing or
misplacing a single word.
''Every 30 minutes, I was required to tell a fat black goosenecked
microphone about traffic irregularities, mutilated children, the
wreckage of peace in Europe and the weather. I felt the syllables warm
and open against my teeth, I licked and pushed and breathed them, kissed
them goodbye. It was almost moving, even with a crippled throat.''
When not sealed behind the sound-tight doors of the radio studio she
is impenetrable behind an emotional iron curtain. Her previous
relationship takes a lot of beating, being sado-masochistic, and it
takes time for her heart to warm when her flatmate announces that he is
Savinien Cyrano de Bergerac, French swordsman, poet, and playwright.
To research the real man behind the popular play by Edmond Rauissual
about the French captain with the big nose -- ''he didn't actually have
a giant nose, it was more the Roman nose to end all Roman noses'' -- who
writes love letters to the women he adores but for another man, Kennedy
travelled eight times to Paris and learned seventeenth-century French.
She wept when visiting Sannois where he died and became protective of
the bones of his father after finding out that they had been dumped in
the Paris catacombs. ''I paid it a visit and found these American
tourists posing to have pictures taken beside a heap of bones . . . I
wanted to say my buddy's dad's bones are in there -- show a little
respect for f**k's sake!''
Though Cyrano killed more men than Charles Manson he was an artist
with more than his sword. He wrote the first science-fiction novel with
his adventure Voyage dans la Lune and proved to be a powerful political
thinker whose modern opinions on the subject of the church and crown
could have resulted in his death. As it was, he died of natural causes.
''I think because I've done a lot of work in the community and with
people in confinement I can appreciate Cyrano. He was a wonderful writer
but a lot of it was about being able to fly, to escape. He doesn't feel
happy. At the time of his death he said he had a lot of regrets, he
wanted to be remembered as a playwright. But that was sabotaged . . . he
was accused of being an atheist at a time when you could be hanged for
it. In the end he is only remembered as a play.''
In So I Am Glad it takes a dead man to break Jennifer's barrier. While
her French visitor has retired from a lifetime of violence, Jennifer
continues to indulge pleasure with pain. In one harrowing scene she
badly beats her consenting lover. After a description of the distressing
scene she opens a new chapter with a cunning line. ''Well, I only told
you I was calm. I never suggested that I was nice.''
''All I knew with Jennifer was that she was only a voice. She didn't
have any feelings and in one chapter all her rage comes out. I wanted to
show that people who are very quiet and sealed up can also be very
dangerous because they can't understand what others feel.''
Jennifer does learn to feel and becomes more than a voice but it takes
loss and a duel. A L Kennedy learned to fence while writing the book.
''It's very much like writing. It's all psychology and you're trying to
touch somebody.''
* A L Kennedy's latest book So I Am Glad is reviewed in Weekender
tomorrow.
</TEXT>
