<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>From small beer to the big league</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>978321624</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Andrew Wilson reports on a merger that makes sense
NOT even an advertising agency could have dreamt up a title such as
Scottish Courage and then charged a fee. The merging of the brewing
activities of Scottish &amp; Newcastle and Courage represents the
culmination of rumours which began as long ago as 1968 when there were
exploratory talks between the then two family-dominated companies where
the logic for a combination was as valid then as it is today.
The geographical fit is excellent and both are oriented more to the
free trade than any of their competitors apart from Guinness. But in the
following quarter century or so the two have managerially been
transformed out of all recognition.
There is a certain irony which is relished with quiet enjoyment at the
Abbey Brewery headquarters that S&amp;N has turned the tables on its
one-time enemy when Fosters was a subsidiary of Elders IXL, the
international vehicle for the highly ambitious John Elliott who finally
overreached himself.
The Australian planned to create a truly global brewing empire and
''Fosterise the Universe'' using S&amp;N as its British colony to expand
into Europe and seemed set for success.
However a white knight turned up in the form of the Monopolies and
Mergers Commission which blocked the #1600m bid, partly because of the
domination the Foster's lager brand would have had in the UK with its
becoming the house brand for both S&amp;N and Grand Metropolitan which in
those days still had a direct participation in brewing through its
control of Courage.
There was evident satisfaction when Elders finally sold its 23%
holding at a loss of #90m although Elliott then went on to do the highly
complicated swap of breweries for pubs with Grand Metropolitan.
S&amp;N traces its origins back to 1749 when the William Younger brewery
was established in Leith. Over a century later, in 1856 the William
McEwan brewery was founded in a period of great prosperity for the
brewing industry whose visible proof lies with the magnificent McEwan
Hall given to Edinburgh in perpetuity.
In the early 1930s, the two companies were merged to form the basic
rather unimaginatively named Scottish Brewers.
However there was the other strand developing with Gateshead seeing
the John Barras building his brewery just 21 years after Younger's in
1770 which in 1890 became part of Newcastle Breweries as the industry
began to move towards larger units as the advantages of improved
transport enabled economies of scale.
The two strands came together in 1960, partly for defensive reasons as
a highly aggressive Canadian beer baron named Taylor was causing fear
and trepidation in the industry through his takeover forays and forcing
the native brewers to come together. The most conspicuous example was
the formation of the Whitbread ''umbrella'' when Colonel Whitbread
persuaded many smaller brewers that it was in their interests for
Whitbread to buy large stakes in their shares.
In the 1960s, S&amp;N company did nothing much of note. However it moved
decisively into the free trade in the 1970s realising that Scotland and
the North-east of England was too small a trading area to provide
long-term growth.
It was one of the leaders in supplying the supermarkets which enabled
it to gain a market share in due course of over 10% -- now about 12%-13%
depending upon how one counts the French exports through Calais.
Expansion was helped through the building of a brewery in Manchester
and the acquisition of the Home Brewery in Nottingham -- that seems
exposed if there is to be a rationalisation of the brewery portfolio
once the Courage acquisition is completed.
A year later in 1987, it finally gained control of Blackburn-based
Matthew Brown after two attempts in a very hostile takeover battle.
Under chairman Sir Alick Rankin and his extremely able lieutenant
Brian Stewart, S&amp;N has developed a reputation as being a very effective
corporate operator.
The two deals which are still praised in the City were the sale of
Thistle Hotels for #645m in 1989 with the proceeds almost immediately
invested in Center Parcs, the 14 allweather leisure centres which have
taken northern Europe by storm and have held up consistently in profit
terms even through the bleakest days of the recession.
More recently there has been the purchase of the Chef &amp; Brewer chain
of pubs from Grand Metropolitan for #700m. These have performed ahead of
expectations and have given S&amp;N a substantial pub estate in the south of
England where it has historically been substantially under-represented.
In 1980, the company was valued by the stock market at #180m. Today it
is worth #2900m and has moved into being the largest brewer, overtaking
the longtime leader Bass by a margin of perhaps 6% with 25% of the
market compared with the Bass share of 19%.
But it is far from certain S&amp;N will hold this lead for more than
perhaps a year as some suspect that the unhappy Carlsberg-Tetley may be
sold by present owners Allied Domecq to Whitbread, the past master of
branding to establish the new industry giant.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000081</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000081</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scottish &amp; Newcastle's  planned merger with Courage is intended to create a stronger force in a fickle market. Brewers will feel the draught</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>978321625</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
The day of the floating drinker has arrived, reports Ken Smith, as the
battle between traditional and designer beers intensifies
IT'S a figure that would have the caricature Scots drunk of old
weeping into his beer -- by the end of the decade Scots pubs will sell
over 100 million less pints a year than they do today.
It's not quite a total victory for the Temperance Movement, as the
average Scot will by then be drinking more at home. But it is a
significant change. For more and more people, the pub is no longer the
centre of the universe.
Within these bald figures other changes are taking place. The loyalty
of drinking the same type of pint until you die is evaporating. People
are aware that younger drinkers are often turning to the premium brands,
the so-called designer drinks which come in expensive bottles.
Only they are changing yet again. Many are wakening up to the fact
that paying nearly #2 for a bottle containing less than half a pint is
not the bargain of the century, but they don't want to go back to fizzy
heavy. So now the smart money is on what the trade call mixed gas
dispensed ales such as Caffreys or Kilkenny. The pint is making a
comeback, albeit in a shrinking market.
It seems the day of the floating drinker has arrived. He may have a
pint of Tennent's lager after he finishes work. He may drink Caffrey's
when going out with the lads. He may drink a bottle of Beck's when at
the disco. Pints when playing pool, bottles when on the pull, as it
were.
Confusing? No wonder Scottish and Newcastle wants to protect itself in
a shrinking market by tying up with Courage. With the beer market
declining, and a 20% overcapacity in breweries in Britain, S&amp;N are
obviously taking the fact that you need courage to be a brewer these
days, literally.
Trade information suggests that about two million barrels a year in
Scotland are sold to the on-trade -- pubs, restaurants, and hotels.
Although it may actually be pumped in by tanker, it is still measured in
barrels, which is 288 pints. By the year 2000, it is estimated that this
will drop to 1.6 million barrels.
The growth area of off-sales will see an estimated increase from
930,000 barrels to 1,080,000 barrels. It's an increase of 150,000 which
the brewers will welcome, but will not offset the 400,000 decrease in
on-sales.
So why the change? Mark Hunter, marketing director at Tennent
Caledonian, says: ''There are enormous social changes. Visits to the pub
may be more fleeting, an hour say, as opposed to the whole evening.
Big-volume session drinking is on the wane.
''Other things may initially seem unrelated. But over 85% of Scots buy
lottery tickets which is far higher than the national average. If 25 to
35-year-old males, your core beer drinkers, are buying #2 to #5 worth of
lottery tickets a week, that's the price of a couple of pints.
''People are also doing different things. Multiplex cinemas have grown
to compete at entertainment. People are even going to shopping centres
more and drinking more at home.
''With six cans and a video you can have a reasonable good time at
home.''
Not that Tennent's are throwing in the towel themselves. Their lager
is still a monster. The biggest consumer brand of anything in Scotland.
A quarter of all beer sold in Scotland is Tennent's lager, and they work
very hard at keeping its stature within the market.
Within the standard lager market in pubs, Tennent's has 60% share to
McEwan's 19%, and the others down in small single figures.
The premium lager market, such as Budweiser, Beck's, and Miller
Genuine Draught, is now levelling out after years of steady growth. It
now has 8% of the beer market to standard lager's 44%. Bud, the American
beer now brewed in England, has been making inroads at the expense of
Beck's the quality German beer.
Standard ales, such as Tennent's and McEwan's Special, have 27% of the
market, but the sector has dropped by a quarter recently. Premium ales
are now flavour of the month, which includes beers like Caffreys and
Guinness. The market is growing, but nowhere near as fast to offset
entirely the drop in standard ales.
This will really make an old-fashioned beer drinker splutter. Bud is
actually growing in sales because it tastes so bland. Many younger
drinkers, it seems, want what is called a non-challenging taste. They
use drink as a social lubricant, but don't necessarily want to notice
what it tastes like.
The resurgence in cask beers is caused by those recognising foreign
bottled beers are not particularly good value, and want to go back to a
pint, but still want it to be a bit different from the standard fizzy
beer of old.
Pat Duffy, editor of the Scottish License Trade News, says that pubs
will still survive, but they have to work a lot harder at attracting
customers.
''I know of one pub in Kilmarnock which has 24 beers on draught in
order to satisfy the customers. Not so long ago a pub would have one
lager and one heavy and that was it.
''There has also been a shift to home drinking. People are just
entertaining at home more. Satellite TV is an attraction, and people are
actually spending more time with their kids than they used to do in the
old days.''
He believes that the Courage takeover may lead to the number of brands
being cut, and possibly even brewery closures or sell-offs. He suggests
that S&amp;N is also recognising the substantial growth in England of large
chains of pubs which are not owned by a brewery.
''A number of large regional brewers in England opted out of brewing
completely after the Monopolies and Mergers Commission report aimed at
freeing up the market. Instead they kept their 600 or 1000 pubs and used
their strength to negotiate discounts from the Big Six brewers.
''With the Courage takeover, Scottish Courage, as it may become known
as, will have the spread of brands and economies of scale to deal with
these large chains.''
In Scotland though there are far more free trade outlets and single
owner pubs which may in fact only be selling three or four barrels a
week. They may be paying #250 to #270 a barrel while the big chains are
negotiating discounts of approaching half of that.
The brewers are attempting to cope with the downturn in sales by
selling a quality product, naturally at a quality price. While people
unemployed or strapped for cash are buying strange, unheard of, foreign
brands in the supermarkets, simply because they are cheap, in contrast
the beer cans with widgets in them to give a cask ale style of delivery
are selling at over a #1 a can. The market, it seems, is dividing into
the cheap and cheerful versus the quality brands, which will of course
cost more in the future. And no doubt that will have the caricature Scot
crying into his beer as well.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000082</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000082</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Workers fear for the future</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROY ROGERS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321626</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WORKERS at the 10 S&amp;N and Courage breweries supped their beer last
night uncertain on whether to celebrate the coming together of the two
concerns or to drown their sorrows.
On the one hand the much-heralded merger announcement ended a
prolonged period of uncertainty and should certainly mean both are now
safer from the attention of other predators. Yet history has shown that
takeovers of this scale inevitably lead to rationalisation in an
industry that has shed some 5000 jobs in the past three years alone.
There are also fears that the proposed takeover will spark other
restructuring within the volatile brewing trade which has seen a steady
flow of acquisitions and mergers with the number of breweries plummeting
from some 17,000 at the turn of the century to the latest situation
where, following the S&amp;N-Courage link-up, just four concerns will
control 84% of the industry.
At each step of the way jobs and often plants were phased out with the
result that today there are only about 25,000 employed in the brewing
and distribution sector.
The unions and the beer lovers' pressure group -- the Campaign for
Real Ale -- fear that the merger will further concentrate ownership,
reduce competition and lead to rationalisation throughout the Scottish &amp;
Newcastle and Courage operations. Camra even feels that the future of
several smaller breweries could be threatened.
Transport and General Workers Union national secretary Brian Revell
maintains that the news of the acquisition has at least brought an end
to a period of uncertainty which despite losing several thousand jobs in
recent years still has considerable overcapacity.
He believed his members would give the news a cautious welcome.
Clearly there was a danger of job losses through rationalistion in
administration, distribution and possibly even production through
combining the two groups. But if there had to be a further coming
together of the main players in the industry this was probably the most
acceptable as S&amp;N and Courage's operations complemented each other's in
a way that no other combination could. The two had a good ''North South
fit''.
Mr Revell blamed much of the industry's plight on the controversial
1989 Mergers and Monopolies Commission report on the supply of beer and
on the high level of taxation on it.
Supposed to open up greater competition in the industry which was then
dominated by six companies controlling 78% of the trade, the inquiry was
firmly opposed by the TGWU who pointed out it would be likely to have
the opposite effect.
Despite a certain amount of trading of pubs for breweries to
accommodate the MMC findings, which were endorsed by the then Industry
Secretary Lord Young, the concentration continued.
''Sadly we were proved right,'' comments Revell who bemoans that fact
that neither Lord Young nor any of the MMC inquiry team -- with the
honourable exception of bankworkers' union leader, TUC president and
beer aficionado Leif Mills who produced his own minority report -- knew
much about the brewing industry.
Mr Revell, who will be calling together shop stewards from S&amp;N and
Courage soon to assess the likely implications of the merger, accepts
there will be unpalatable aspects as the inevitable rationalisation gets
under way.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
