<HEADLINE>Wind of change on the Mound</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEWART LAMONT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>978321627</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Stewart Lamont examines the key issues facing the General Assembly of
the Church of Scotland when it opens tomorrow
BEHIND the venerable facade of the Kirk's General Assembly when it
meets in Edinburgh tomorrow will lie some far-reaching changes planned
for the national church. The most obvious is a cosmetic change in the
way the assembly itself is run. Gone are the days of all-male toilets,
and a sauna-style atmosphere in which men in black suits baked under TV
lights, passing resolutions about care for the disabled, none of whom
could reach the rocky heights of the assembly hall's staircases.
There are now female toilets, a coffee lounge, unobtrusive CCTV under
cool lights, a lift for the disabled -- and this year another
modernising change. In the ''playpen'' beneath the Moderator, from which
the procedures are conducted, a series of computer terminals will enable
the officials to communicate directly with the firm which prints the
daily minutes. Gone are the shorthand writers, the savings having bought
a machine which will log the proceedings in sound and vision on around
38 CDs.
This CD-ROM revolution has led to a little game of musical chairs in
the playpen itself. A specially made hexagonal table will group the
players. The principal clerk, James Weatherhead, will sit at the head
with his deputy and successor (Finlay Macdonald of Jordanhill) on his
right and on his left Alastair Dunlop QC, the advocate who successfully
persuaded the Court of Session last month that the Kirk was master in
its own house over hiring and firing ministers.
On his left the business managers (Tom ''Big Ears'' McWilliam and Mrs
Ann McCarter) sit opposite the new Kirk solicitor, Mrs J S Wilson, and
Mrs Alison Murray, Jordanhill Church secretary, who will be slipping her
discs into the computers.
In PR terms it will be a more modern and feminine image for the body
which recently used to address itself as ''Fathers and Brethern''. But
behind the facade other, more far-reaching changes will not be so easily
adopted. Tomorrow evening the Assembly Council will be inviting
endorsement of its plans to trim back on Kirk work in times of
stringency -- and will meet with opposition right away.
The Board of Communication is being told to cut one of its sections
(publishing, design and publicity, or audio-visual) and is fighting its
corner. It agrees that in the commercial world it could not keep these
departments, but wants the Kirk to subsidise them as essential in-house
activities.
This is the problem when you have a structure like the Kirk. There are
so many checks and balances that it is difficult to get agreement to
implement cuts when there are others who consider the work to be
essential. Another example of this will arise when the parish education
committee is challenged by the Kirk group who are running Carberry Tower
to sell it to them (the offer is rumoured to be #300,000 against market
valuations from #1.2m to #1.8m).
The plea is that they should at least be allowed a chance to carry on
valuable work which cannot have a market price put on it. The same kind
of protest will surface from historic churches in Stirling and Alloa who
are being asked to move to short-term contract ministries. But that is
the way the wind is blowing.
The Board of Ministry also wants to introduce contracts for ministers
which will for the first time, spell out duties and a code of conduct
for ministers which will make them more accountable for what they do. A
further extension of this process will come right at the start of the
Assembly when a group will be asked to examine the whole question of
whether ministers should have the right of tenure once they are inducted
to a parish.
This is a key issue. It sharpens and focuses the major issue facing
the Kirk today -- the question of where authority lies. In theory, it is
easy -- it lies with presbyteries (for that is what presbyterianism is).
But for reasons of practical administration it now in reality lies with
Assembly boards (composed of course of representative elders and
ministers from presbyteries).
However, ask the man in the pew and he thinks that authority lies with
his congregation to do as they wish. The mismatch between these areas of
authority creates problems of leadership and dissipates much energy in
solving its problems.
One thing is certain, there is a pressing need to settle the authority
question and press ahead with change. Putting off that decision or
carrying on as before is likely to deepen the malaise. One solution to
the authority question which has been anathema to Kirk worthies in the
past is a system of bishops. Yet that very system is a possible outcome
of one report which invites the Kirk to take up where it left off in
unity talks with the Scottish Episcopal Church.
It is unlikely that if they are unable to agree upon who runs their
show at present, the Church of Scotland will turn to their traditional
bogeyman to save them. The danger, as I see it, is that anachronistic
battles over the B-word will prove a distraction from putting in place a
proper system of authority and accountability.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000084</DOCNO>
