<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Kirk strives for success on a plate</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GEORGE HUME</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>978321628</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
George Hume reports on the cash problems that face the Church and why
members will have to dig deeper
THE shrinking Church of Scotland, strapped for cash, its reserves
squeezed ever thinner, is not in debt -- and that's official. ''We do
not have a crisis,'' says Will Farrell, the Kirk's expert on just how
little comes in on the collection plate each Sunday. But, when the
General Assembly hears next week that congregations will have to chip in
three times as much as they do at present if the Church is to pay its
way and escape its parlous position, many Kirk stalwarts may believe
they are worshipping at St Andrews On the Brink.
Money -- the acute lack of it -- will be the big secular issue at this
year's General Assembly. Almost 75% of the Church's income comes from
members giving four-fifths of that through the weekly expression of
congregations' generosity. But at an average of just over #1 a week from
each member that largesse is, simply, not enough.
As Assembly commissioners and officials of the Church's Board of
Stewardship and Finance struggle to square the circle of inadequate
giving and increasing demand they may pause to marvel at -- the less
pious be envious of -- the level of giving in other churches offering
counsel and comfort in Scotland.
Farrell has an explanation for the gap between the apparent financial
ease of some churches and the ever-tightening belt of the Church of
Scotland. ''These are gathered congregations whereas the Church of
Scotland will take anyone. These other churches have a committed
membership.''
In cash terms committed members, ''gathered congregations'', do well
by their church. The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints -- the
Mormons -- requires members to tithe 10% of their income if they are to
be deemed ''Temple Worthy''. Scottish members -- there is no breakdown
for Scotland of the Church's 170,000 members throughout the United
Kingdom -- are said to be some of the most faithful, ''very
conscientious'' in attending the Temple, an act which can only be
carried out if the member holds a ''recommend'' which, in turn, can only
be obtained if the 10% of income has been paid.
Closer to home the Free Church of Scotland, with around 6000 and a
further 14,500 adherents, last year enjoyed an income from giving of
#2,378,153 . . . an average annual figure for both members and adherents
of #116, virtually double the sum put in the plate by their Church of
Scotland brethren and a figure itself exceeded by Quaker giving the
Society of Friends' 700 members in Scotland, and a like number of
attenders, averaging #150 a year.
The debt-ridden Catholic Church in Scotland, overdrawn by #8m two
years ago, has managed to stimulate giving from an average of 70p per
week for every member -- the Catholic Church counts in its 760,000
strength all who are baptised -- to #1.50, still #1 short of the weekly
target of #2.50 set when the crisis broke, but none the less moving
firmly in the right direction. Almost #3m has already been wiped off the
burden of debt.
Where the Catholic Church in Scotland has managed to double its
members' giving the Church of Scotland requires its members to treble
theirs. Can it reach its target? According to Will Farrell the answer is
''yes'' and the vehicle education. ''The problem when it comes to giving
is racial memory, by which I mean people thinking back to those days
when members did not need to give at all to support the Church,'' says
Farrell.
''They may have given a penny for the poor and another penny for the
foreign mission but the financial burden of maintaining their Church was
met from endowments, glebe rents, feu incomes and the like. That is no
longer the case -- these days are long gone -- but a Church member who
today gives #1 a week, set against that memory, thinks they are doing
rather well by the Church when, in fact, they are not.''
The fact is that those members of the Church of Scotland who do give
make a much greater contribution than the average of #59.24 shown in the
books. The Kirk estimates that of the total membership of 715,571 only
one third is fully committed to the work of the Church and gives a
figure that must work out in excess of #3 a week. Another third of the
membership, says Farrell, ''moves within the Church'', while the
remaining third is ''on the fringe''.
Says Farrell: ''I have a great faith in the Lord but not in all the
members. The straitened position in which the Church finds itself is all
about perception, not financial. We have to make it clear to members
that they are not involved in fund-raising but in Christian giving. It
is not a question of a great push and then settling back at that for a
few years -- giving has to increase sharply and thereafter increase
every year if the Church is to be properly supported in its work.''
The average congregation gives #40,000 a year when what is needed is
#120,000. The gap, says Will Farrell, is ''just too great''. The Church
is striving to encourage members to make a firm commitment to contribute
an additional one per cent of their annual income and to continue to do
so each year until they consider they are giving generously and
proportionate to that income.
In terms of pounds and pence such a target, if taken on and achieved,
would mean an average increase in each member's giving of #120 in the
first year alone -- the Church estimating that the average net income of
its members stands at around #12,000 a year.
Figures to be put before the General Assembly show that congregations
have largely failed to act to rescue their Church from its financial
predicament. Although there was an increase in congregational income
last year of almost #2.5m -- a rise of almost 3.8% and well above the
rate of inflation which last year stood at 2.5% -- in simple cash terms
per capita offerings rose by just over #4 in the full year, a meagre 8p
per person per week.
While declaring it ''a source of satisfaction and gratitude'' that the
per capita givings of members have risen in excess of the increases in
both retail prices and average incomes over the past decade, the Church
stresses that the increases are based on a low starting level of giving
-- Farrell's ''racial memory'' -- with the accounts showing that as
recently as 1989 per capita offerings amounted to no more than #39.14.
In addition, the General Assembly will hear that the benefits of
increased giving are each year offset by the decline in the number of
members. The 1994 drop in membership -- some 17,400 -- would require
more than one million pounds more from those remaining to make good the
loss. Expenditure in the year ahead, it will be made clear, must be
trimmed to fit income.
Says Farrell: ''The Church is not in debt, we do not have a crisis, we
are able to balance our books. But members must think about their
giving. It is right that there should always be a healthy tension
between the Church's ambition and its resources -- we live on the edge
of financial decisions -- and although there will always have to be
these decisions Church members will have to recognise that a much
greater level of giving is needed if the Church is to continue all its
work. What we are doing today is cutting everything from our existing
financial cake when what we really need to do is bake a much bigger
cake.''
* THE Scots Kirk in Paris, headquarters of an escape line for hundreds
of British troops during the last war, is facing closure owing to a lack
of cash. The Rev Dr Donald Caskie -- the so-called Tartan Pimpernel --
masterminded the freedom route to Spain from the church at 17 Rue Bayard
before falling into the hands of the Gestapo. Held in solitary
confinement, often on a diet of bread and water, he was released when
Paris fell to the allies in August 1944.
Now the late Donald Caskie's church is in bad repair. It urgently
needs work costing #50,000 but has an annual income of #10,000 less, a
regular Sunday attendance of just 50, a ''contact list'' of only 150 and
will this year require a subsidy from Church funds intended for the
Third World.
Faced by a recommendation from the Assembly Council that the Church's
overseas budget be cut by 10% in order to make ends meet, the Board of
World Mission is pressing the congregation in Paris to act and stand on
its own feet. A would-be purchaser has offered in the #650,000 for the
church building and Dr Wigglesworth Board is urging the congregation to
sell and make arrangements to worship, with their minister, in one of
the other Reformed churches in Paris.
''The congregation would like us to continue to shell out the 40% of
total costs of the Scots Kirk in Paris, a subsidy which at present
amounts to about #30,000 a year. But that is not possible,'' he said.
</TEXT>
