<DOCNO>GH950519-000087</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000087</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Deal secures bright future for Gaelic soap opera</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN LAING, ENTERTAINMENTS WRITER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321631</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE future of Gaelic soap opera Machair has been guaranteed for at
least the next three years following a funding agreement between
Scottish Television and the Comataidh Telebhisein Gaidhlig, the Gaelic
Television Committee.
The deal also ensures the programme will continue to be made on
location in the Western Isles. In earlier discussions, Scottish
Television had put forward the option of moving part of the filming to
its Glasgow studios because bad weather conditions on location were
interrupting production. The proposal was strongly opposed by the local
community which benefits from commercial spin-offs.
Scottish Television now expects to conclude a deal with Western Isles
Enterprise and Comhairle Nan Eilean to build a basic studio for Machair
in the isles. This will enable filming to continue whatever the weather.
The new agreement, funding for which will come from the CTG's #2.2m
allocation for serial drama, secures continuity for the next 78
half-hour episodes. Previously, Scottish Television had to approach the
CTG for funding on an annual basis.
The crew are currently in the Western isles filming the sixth series.
Mr Alistair Moffat, chief executive of Scottish Television
Enterprises, said: ''This allows planning of a sort not previously
available for Machair. We can build on Gaelic-speaking talents in a
structured way, both in front and behind the camera.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000088</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000088</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Gardener who raped girl, 14, gets eight years</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRUCE MCKAIN, LAW CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321632</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A RAPIST who subjected a 14-year-old girl to a terrifying sex attack
as she took a shortcut through a cemetery, was jailed for eight years
yesterday.
Lord Weir told William Nicholson ''What you did to that innocent girl
of tender years was unforgiveable. The crime which you perpetrated was a
terrible one. It is one of the most serious cases I have come across for
some time.''
The judge was told that Nicholson's victim suffered severe
psychological distress because of her ordeal. The only factor in his
favour was that he had admitted the crime and spared the girl the ordeal
of having to give evidence.
Nicholson, 36, a landscape gardener of Templeland Road, Pollok,
Glasgow, admitted raping the girl at Craigton cemetery, Cardonald, on
Janaury 6 this year.
His victim was taking a shortcut through the graveyard when Nicholson
grabbed her by the arm. She managed to break free, but the accused kept
following her.
He grabbed her, pulled her into undergrowth, pushed her on to her back
and raped her. The girl screamed but was warned: ''Shut up if you know
what is good for you.''
She managed to escape when Nicholson stumbled and fell into dense
undergrowth and ran naked from the waist down to a relative's house.
Nicholson, a first offender, had been working with a squad of men
clearing bushes and undergrowth in the disused graveyard. He had been
drinking before the attack on the girl.
He originally pleaded guilty at the High Court in Glasgow and Lord
Weir deferred sentence to obtain a psychiatric report.
At the High Court in Edinburgh yesterday, Mr Tom Welsh, defence
counsel, told the judge that Nicholson appeared to be a shy introverted
and somewhat lonely man.
He had been segregated from other prisoners in Barlinnie since his
detention in January and was terrified of the circumstances in which he
found himself.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000089</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000089</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cunard chairman weighs anchor</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321633</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE chairman of Cunard, is to leave ''by mutual agreement'' just five
months after the disastrous Christmas voyage of the shipping line's
flagship, the QE2, it was announced yesterday.
Trafalgar House, Cunard's parent company, said Mr John Olsen was
leaving its board and that of Cunard ''to pursue other interests''.
A Trafalgar House spokesman said yesterday: ''Mr Olsen joined on a
two-year contract with an option to review it for an extra year. The
two-year contract was due to be completed on May 31 and by mutual
agreement Mr Olsen will not be staying on after that.''
The chairman of Rolls-Royce Motor Cars, Mr Peter Ward, will replace Mr
Olsen on the Trafalgar and Cunard boards.
Cunard suffered a #6.9m loss for the six months to the end of March
1995.
Trouble for both Mr Olsen and the 66,000-tonne QE2 began when the
vessel went to Germany for a #30m refit last year.
Cunard was confident the 27 days set aside for the refit would be
adequate. But the vessel returned with much still to be done, including
vital plumbing.
A cruise to the Bay of Biscay was cancelled and the Christmas cruise
to New York on December 17 suffered flooding due to plumbing problems.
Mr Olsen joined the ship at New York to discuss passengers'
grievances. But later US coastguards prevented the liner sailing to the
Caribbean because of fire hazards and safety violations.
Cunard had to set aside #7.5m to compensate passengers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000090</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000090</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Everest -- there's no way for climbers</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>978321634</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SCOTS mountaineer has abandoned plans to scale Everest because there
is no room at the top of the world.
Mr Dave Rowe had hoped to undertake an expedition to the Himalayan
peak, but discovered it is fully booked.
Instead, Mr Rowe, 34, of Blairgowrie, and three companions will head
to Greenland later this month to climb uncharted peaks.
The full-time mountaineer explained: ''I had thought of going to the
Himalayas, but Everest is just too busy. The mountain is fully booked
for some time.
''There're so many sightseers in the Himalayas as well that
mountaineers can't get up there and it makes it a bit less of a
wilderness.''
He described the Greenland trip as ''the challenge of a lifetime''.
He explained: ''It's uncharted territory and we'll be putting up new
routes. There are no guide books.
</TEXT>
