<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000091</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000091</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Minister ready to steer away from Howard line. Fraser in bid to reassure police</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES FREEMAN, HOME AFFAIRS REPORTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321635</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Home Affairs Minister Lord Fraser is understood to be ready
to distance himself and the Scottish Office from the thinking of Home
Secretary Michael Howard on the future of Britain's police forces when
he addresses top Scottish policemen in Peebles today.
He is expected to offer reassurance instead of confrontation, and in
particular to emphasise that Scotland need not necessarily swallow whole
the police core functions review, which is based almost entirely on
English and Welsh experience.
His speech may go some way to allaying fears voiced by Strathclyde's
Chief Constable Mr Leslie Sharp in his attack on Government police
policy at the Association of Scottish Police Superintendents'
conference.
Lord Fraser, it is understood, will stress that any plans taken on
board north of the Border would be subject to the widest consultation.
He is also likely to be conciliatory over the fears of senior officers
about fixed-term contracts and appraisal-related pay which, he is
expected to emphasise, will not be based on arrests or league tables.
But there is much scepticism among police on this matter, and it is
likely to remain, despite Government claims that people like Mr Sharp
are projecting worst-case scenarios.
The association's agenda this week has reflected many of the same
preoccupations as those voiced by Mr Sharp, including strong misgivings
that fixed-term appointments and performance related pay will undermine
the traditional independence of chief officers.
There are also grave doubts over the Home Office review of core
functions -- an exercise to save money by seeing which bits of the
police service could be hived off to private security, Mr Sharp
maintained.
It became apparent yesterday that the ''Spare a Copper'' lecture had
provided a focus for police concerns at every rank.
General secretary of the Scottish Police Federation Mr Douglas Keil
said: ''What Mr Sharp said in his lecture reflects exactly what we
consider to be the major dangers facing the police service in the UK.
The Government is proposing root and branch changes which will be to no
one's benefit.''
Mr Tom Rowatt, secretary of the federation branch in Strathclyde
police, added: ''There is no doubt in my mind that the police service
should be professionally managed and accountable to the general public,
with whose consent it polices.
''I believe that these principles are firmly based at the moment, but
that they are being threatened by dogma from a Government driven by
making profits for 'haves', while ignoring the effects that these
policies will produce on the 'have nots'.''
Mr Rowatt said that the only thing which could now prevent the total
destruction of the police service as we know it was a change of heart by
the Government on the privatisation of the public service, or a change
in government itself.
The opposition was not slow to side with the police service against Mr
Howard's perceived excesses. Mr John McFall, Labour's Scottish spokesman
on home affairs, told the association that the Government held the
narrow belief that cutting costs was in itself a form of efficiency.
''The narrowing of police officers' responsibilities is superficially
attractive to the Treasury eye. If you can identify tasks which can be
performed by operatives who cost less and require less training and
investment than it takes to produce a fully-trained constable you can
privatise these roles, instantly reduce the workload of the police, cut
police numbers and save costs,'' he said.
At one level -- traffic wardens and typists -- that might work, but it
was simplistic to take it too far.
Referring to Mr Sharp's misgivings about the increasing role for
private security companies, Mr McFall added: ''Communities which are
desperate to deal with crime are being tempted to take the law into
their own hands as vigilantes, or to pay out hard cash for private
companies to do it for them. Attracted by a market which is almost free
of regulation, new companies -- some operated by people whose record
gives the police cause for concern -- are moving in to offer their
services.
''To go back to the days when private police forces existed on the
basis of the wealth of those who employed them would be to return to the
worst sort of basics -- the law of the jungle,'' Mr McFall said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000092</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000092</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Council votes for Ferguslie inquiry</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ELIZABETH BUIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321636</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RENFREW District Council is to set up its own investigation into the
activities of the Ferguslie-based security company, FCB Enterprise
Security Ltd, which is currently being investigated by the police.
A motion by the leader of the main opposition SNP group, Councillor
Bruce McFee, to set up an inquiry into the company, its contracts with
the council and its employment practices was passed last night by 23
votes to 13, with one abstention. Three rebel Labour councillors voted
for the motion, and 13 members of the controlling Labour group voted
against.
The working party will be made up of three Labour group nominees, two
from the SNP, one Conservative and one Liberal-Democrat or non-aligned
party member.
Councillor McFee told the meeting that FCB was given the security
contract -- a single tender contract -- because it claimed it would
create local employment and it would pay #3.60 an hour to employees.
He claimed that the company had, however, paid people on the dole who
were claiming social security benefits #1.50 an hour ''cash in hand''.
As the contract was based on hours worked by employees on #3.60 an hour,
he asked: ''Where did the balance go?''
He also alleged that ''ghosting'' practices had been carried out by
FCB employees, in which fewer staff were on duty than the contract had
dictated.
Councillor Olga Clayton, a member of the council's Labour group and a
director of the company, said she welcomed any investigation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
