<DOCNO>GH950519-000094</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000094</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Decision day for V &amp; A</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321638</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE director of the National Galleries of Scotland, Mr Timothy
Clifford, will find out today if he has been appointed as the new
director of the Victoria &amp; Albert Museum in London, ending weeks of
speculation.
Last night an unusually publicity-shy Mr Clifford was unavailable for
comment.
A National Galleries of Scotland spokeswoman said: ''The V&amp;A are
keeping things very, very close to their chest. We will have to wait
until an announcement is made.''
The V&amp;A said that four candidates had been interviewed by a selection
committee for the prestigious #63,000-a-year post currently held by Mrs
Elizabeth Esteve-Coll. But they declined to say who the applicants had
been, or even who had been on the selection committee.
The museum's spokeswoman, Tracey Williamson, said that from that list
one name had been selected and given to the museum's 17-strong board of
trustees for approval yesterday afternoon. That name had then to be
approved by the Prime Minister before the candidate was notified.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000095</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000095</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Six arrested at Shell protest</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>978321639</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SIX people were arrested yesterday when demonstrators tried to force
their way into Shell's annual general meeting in London.
About 50 protesters, unhappy with the oil company's activities in
Nigeria, ran towards the Queen Elizabeth conference centre.
When they could get no further than the lobby, they staged a sit-down
protest before being dragged away by police.
There were scenes of mayhem as officers struggled with the
demonstrators as shareholders queued to get into the meeting.
Generally, police were content to repel bids by the protesters to
enter the building. However, two people were charged with breach of the
peace, one with assault on a police officer, and three with criminal
damage.
Two protesters managed to scale a canopy at the front of the building
and stayed there for two hours. They burned a Shell flag before lowering
themselves down to police.
The protest was organised by Shell Out, a coalition of environmental
and human rights campaigners formed to highlight Shell's activities in
Nigeria.
They allege collusion between the oil firm and military forces in
Nigeria, and devastation of land belonging to the Ogoni people in the
Niger Delta. Shell denies the allegations.
A spokesman for the company said yesterday: ''Shell is not in
collusion with the military. It has repeatedly condemned violence by
anyone.
''Shell has not devastated the environment. Where we are responsible
for problems, we are committed to remedial action. We are carrying out a
rolling programme, spending, for instance, well over #60m in 1995 for
environmental improvements.
''Many factors have contributed to environmental problems in the Niger
Delta. To determine the facts, Shell is funding a #1.2m independent
environmental study.''
The spokesman said Shell had withdrawn from the Ogoni area in January
1993 because of violence and threats of violence against staff. He added
that its oil production from the area ceased in the middle of that year.
''We have said we will not return to Ogoni unless we can work in
harmony alongside the communities.''
Shell believes communities have been pressing for a greater share of
oil revenues from government, political self-determination, and mineral
rights. It said communities and other organisations had attacked the
company to raise the profile of their campaign to international level.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000096</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000096</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Plea to force Greenpeace off.Oil company in new Brent Spar eviction bid</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRUCE MCKAIN, LAW CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321640</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A JUDGE will decide today whether to grant an order to eject
physically a dozen Greenpeace protesters who are occupying the disused
Brent Spar oil terminal in the North Sea.
Brent Spar's owner, Shell UK, asked Lord Johnston for an order for
summary ejection of the protesters, who are objecting to plans to sink
the installation in the Atlantic.
Shell is unaware of the identity of 11 of the protesters and the judge
will have to decide whether a court order against unnamed persons is
competent under Scots law.
Mr Gerald Moynihan, counsel for Shell, told the judge at the Court of
Session that Lord Kirkwood had already granted an interdict to ban the
protesters from occupying the platform.
Last Friday night, messengers-at-arms were flown by helicopter to the
platform and served Lord Kirkwood's order on 12 individuals. Only one, a
man called Mr Jonathan Castle, was prepared to give his name.
Mr Moynihan told the court that the protesters were trespassing, had
been ordered to leave by the court but had refused to do so and were on
the Brent Spar in contempt of the court order. Shell had a right at
common law to remove people from the rig, but the protesters had
threatened passive resistance against any such attempts.
In a fax sent from the Brent Spar, Mr Castle had said that the
protesters were prepared to put themselves at risk for the higher
purpose of protecting the ocean and the planet from destruction.
However, by implication, they had said they would not resist removal
attempts by duly authorised court officers.
Mr Moynihan said the issue was whether the court would make an order
of ejection and assist Shell achieve the removal with the minimum risk
of confrontation.
''If your lordship refuses, you will be signalling the impotence of
this court against people who sit on an oil rig in the North Sea and, in
effect, blow raspberries. Can the court, in the face of stubborn
resistance from a class of people intent on resistance, do nothing? That
would be an absurdity.''
Mr Moynihan made it clear that Shell was not asking for the protesters
to be sent to prison until they had obeyed Lord Kirkwood's order. They
were martyrs to a cause and jailing them would be rewarding them by
fuelling the publicity they desired. They would simply be taken off the
platform by helicopter and conveyed to Aberdeen.
Mr Jonathan Mitchell, QC, counsel for Mr Castle, asked Lord Johnston
not to grant an eviction order against his client. He said Mr Castle had
not had the chance to take legal advice on the interim interdict granted
by Lord Kirkwood and it could not be assumed at this stage that he was
in contempt of that order.
As far as the other 11 unnamed protesters were concerned, the order
Shell was asking for was incompetent. He was unaware of any practice by
the Scottish courts of granting orders against people who could not be
named in the order.
It was a cardinal feature of Scots law that court orders should be
restricted to specific individuals.
It was his understanding that, with with the exception of Mr Castle,
most of the others on the Brent Spar when the order was served last
Friday night had left and others had taken their place.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000097</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000097</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scots lecturer asks Europe for sanctions against Italy</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MURRAY RITCHIE, EUROPEAN EDITOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321641</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SCOTTISH lecturer in an Italian university who claims he is the
victim of illegal discrimination has urged the European Commission to
apply economic sanctions against the Italian government.
Professor David Petrie, 43, a lecturer in languages and literature,
has suffered substantial cuts in wages and conditions at the University
of Verona along with 13 other foreigners while their Italian colleagues
have received pay rises and promotion.
His case -- supported several times by the European Court of Justice
in Luxembourg -- has been taken up by Euro-MP Hugh McMahon, whose
Strathclyde West constituency includes Dumbarton, Mr Petrie's home town.
Mr Petrie yesterday led a delegation of the lecturers to the European
Parliament in Strasbourg where Mr McMahon called on the Commission to
cut funding for educational programmes until the Italians respected
European law.
''The Italians are just ignoring European law point blank -- it is a
scandal,'' Mr Petrie complained.
Mr McMahon said: ''It is deplorable that EU citizens are receiving
such treatment at the hands of an EU member state. The EU is supposed to
promote opportunities for citizens to work across the Union. The Italian
authorities are breaking EU law by refusing to grant equal status to
non-Italian nationals.''
After complaints to the university authorities recently the foreigners
were told their salaries were being cut by 15% and they were ordered
into smaller offices, Mr Petrie said. An attempt was also made to
reclassify the lecturers as laboratory assistants so that the wage cuts
could be justified.
Mr McMahon accused the Commission of being lax in supporting Mr
Petrie's clear right to equal treatment. ''Despite the fine words and
rhetoric, the Commission at the moment is not implementing the powers it
currently has,'' he said.
A Commission statement noted that there were problems for foreign
language-lecturers in Italy. The legal situation in Italy was
unsatisfactory, it said, adding that it would continue infringement
proceedings opened in 1992 against Italy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000098</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000098</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Labour condemns American reward offer on Lockerbie</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321642</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR last night condemned a a $4m US Government reward for the
capture of the two alleged Lockerbie bombers -- and demanded to know if
Britain had been consulted.
The offer, and the inclusion of the two men on the FBI's Ten Most
Wanted Fugitives list, had ''the ring of banditry'', said Lord Macaulay.
He demanded to know if the Crown Office , responsible for the Scottish
prosecution of the two men, had been consulted or whether the FBI had
made a unilateral declaration.
Lord Macaulay, Opposition spokesman in the Lords on Scottish legal
matters and Shadow Lord Advocate, voiced his alarm in a letter to the
Lord Advocate, Lord Rodger.
The FBI said in March it had put the two Libyans accused of the
bombing, Abdel Basset Ali Megrahi and Lamen Khalifa Fhimah, on its Ten
Most Wanted list and that the US Government would offer a $4m reward for
information leading to their arrest.
The two were charged in 1991 with planting the bomb that destroyed
PanAm Flight 103 over Lockerbie with the loss of 270 lives in December
1988.
Lord Macaulay said the offer could encourage bounty- hunters.
It also could lead to difficulties if the two Libyans stood trial in
Scotland, only for the trial to collapse if there was a successful
defence claim that a fair trial was impossible on pre-trial publicity
grounds.
In his letter, Lord Macaulay asked if the Americans had consulted
Britain before the FBI move and if not, whether the Crown Office had
registered a protest.
''The offer made has a ring of international banditry about it and
will subject both subjects to the implied threat that even if they leave
Libya to stand trial in Scotland and were acquitted, whether on
preliminary argument regarding publicity being successful or otherwise,
they will be under the threat of capture by the FBI to stand another
trial in the United States.''
The Crown Office said: last night: ''We cannot comment until we have
seen Lord Macaulay's letter.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000099</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000099</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>MPs worried about job satisfaction</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STUART TROTTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>COMMONS SKETCH</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>978321643</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MPs YESTERDAY were thinking about things that could destroy jobs --
like the minimum wage, the Social Chapter and some of the Nolan
Committee recommendations.
Most Tories are vocally averse to the first two, a number think the
third might destroy their jobs in the sense of making them less
attractive than they now are.
Realising that the terms of their contracts to represent United
Umbrellas or Taxidermists Anonymous could be exposed to the public gaze
has made them react in the manner of shop assistants told that opening
hours are being changed from nine to five, to seen to eight.
There is sneaking admiration for Mr Tony Blair who has tackled his
problem with the minimum wage by announcing that he is standing by the
principle but will only start thinking about how to implement it once he
is elected.
One Tory school of thought believes that this wheeze would work for
Nolan. Reaffirm your commitment to high standards in public life, but
defer action on any painful changes until after the next election when
some will no longer be in a position to hold parliamentary
consultancies.
Mr Major resolutely refused to respond to prods from Mr Blair to give
a personal view on all this, but laid into the European job destroyers,
the Wage and the Chapter, with gusto.
And while ''opportunities for profitable consultancies'' may have to
be deleted from the Westminster job specification, we were reminded of
other hidden hazards that face our sturdy legislators.
There is the Whips' book recording the personal peccadilloes of those
Members who are interesting enough to have any. Like almost everything
else connected with this struggling administration it is the Government
Whips' dirt book which has come into the full glare of publicity.
But, gentle reader, do not be shocked if the Sketch reveals that
similar records are kept by the great Opposition Party's Whips. The
binding may be less elaborate, but the information necessary to bring
all but aspirants to sainthood to their knees and into the right lobby
is there.
The secret gambler at tiddlywinks, the real ale person who guzzles
champagne in the privacy of his or her own home. They are all there. If
dramatised, the Whips' books would make compelling television, after the
nine o'clock 'clock watershed of course.
The smaller parties are sufficiently small for all their Members'
oddities not to require elaborate record-keeping.
Mr Tony Banks (Newham North-West -- Lab.), like the rest of us,
believes that to know the Government Whips' book exists is not enough.
It should be published.
He confessed that it was the ''jucier'' Members' interests he was
interested in, not the tedious stuff about finance.
Paying what some might regard as a back-handed compliment, he enquired
if it was true that the Government Whips had now gone into a second
volume and were thinking they might require a loose-leaf format.
The Commons Leader, Mr Tony Newton, is rumoured to have taken to
chain-smoking after being shown his first glimpse of the Book as a
junior Whip. He reverted to his old role and kept mum. He went on to
become Government Chief Whip, a post which leaves one as unsurprised by
the vagaries of human nature as the Head of MI5, the general of the
Jesuits, or a holiday tour guide.
As their party lurches from one public relations disaster to another,
Tory MPs are eyeing the steady convergence of opinion poll data and the
next General Election date with increasing anxiety. Even some of those
who believe they can survive fear they may return to a Commons where the
doctrine of the maximum wage holds stern sway.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
