<DOCNO>GH950519-000103</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000103</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Government attacked over response to Nolan findings</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHEN MCGREGOR, PARLIAMENTARY CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>978321647</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government was strongly criticised last night over its response to
the Nolan Committee report on standards in public life.
In a highly-charged Commons debate on the committee's recommendations,
Public Service Minister David Hunt pledged that some of the Nolan
proposals would be implemented.
However, it was clear that many key recommendations were being put on
hold for further examination and that the Government was anxious to have
further consultation.
Last night's debate followed the recent publication of the Nolan
report into standards in public life, thrown into stark relief by the
''cash for questions'' scandal and the controversy surrounding Tory MP
Sir Jerry Wiggin.
Key recommendations of the report included:
* A ban on MPs working for lobbying companies.
* Full disclosure of MPs' earnings and contracts for providing
parliamentatry services.
* A code of conduct setting out how MPs are expected to behave, and a
clearer code of conduct for Ministers.
Last night, Mr Hunt said the Government was ready to take ''early
action'' on the recommendations, but it was clear that the Government
intended further review.
He said there were many complex issues of detail, and emphasised: ''We
must ensure the recommendations would indeed achieve their aims. We will
have to examine these issues carefully and resolve any difficulties
before implementation.''
For Labour, Shadow Leader of the Commons Ann Taylor, urging Government
action, said; ''Whether it is cash for questions or cash for amendments
we cannot pretend that there is not a very real problem here.''
The debate was marked by a contribution from former Tory Prime
Minister Sir Edward Heath, who felt the House could police itself.
Leading the charge against hasty change, Sir Edward, who is Father of
the House, He said: ''We in this House know far more of what is going on
with our fellow members than any bureaucrat brought in from outside. Of
course we do.''
He continued: ''What can this gentleman do? He can't come into the
smoke room and say, 'By the way, have you heard so--and-so about
so-and-so? Do you think I ought to look at that?' Of course not.''
Sir Edward said: ''What saddens me about Lord Nolan is that he is an
admirable judge but to me he seems to lack a certain worldliness, of
realising what actually goes on in this world of ours.
''We have got to be careful that we don't fall into that trap.''
Outside the Commons, one Tory MP, Alan Duncan, confronted Lord Nolan
-- on his way to the House to hear the debate.
Mr Duncan told him bluntly: ''You are about to obliterate the
professional classes' representation in the House of Commons.''
The MP for Rutland and Melton added: ''It is a very, very dangerous
game.''
Earlier, the Prime Minister told MPs that the Government ''broadly
accepted'' the committee's recommendations, declaring: ''It's important
that not only do we ensure high standards but that the people of this
country see for themselves that this House adopts high standards.''
However, when Mr Hunt promised MPs they would have the ''final say''
on more controversial plans to curb their outside work, he swiftly ran
into a barrage of protests from senior Tories.
Mr Nicholas Budgen (Wolverhampton South-West) warned against a ''panic
response'' and called for any material changes in MPs' terms of office
to be decided through ''slow deliberation'' by statute.
Former Tory Minister Tristan Garel-Jones (Watford) suggested the
detailed changes should be referred to a senior Commons committee for
careful deliberation and another Tory ex-Minister Sir Giles Shaw
(Pudsey) said this could act as a ''conduit through which Nolan can be
rationalised into what's practical''.
In an intervention, Tory Anthony Steen (South Hams) drew Tory cheers
when he protested: ''I deeply resent the inference in Nolan that all of
us are crooks.''
Winding up the debate, which ended without a vote, Commons Leader Tony
Newton said the key point was to go forward ''with proper care'' but
without delay.
''We've got to get it right,'' he insisted.
Mr Newton said: ''One possibility would be for me to come forward with
resolutions but I have grave doubts whether that purpose would be
appropriate or right.
''The appropriate course is to operate according to what the House
would normally do in such circumstances which is to ask a group of
senior and respected members to make recommendations about how we should
proceed in the light of the report and to put forward specific proposals
for resolutions which might be put to the House.''
Mr Nigel Spearing (Newham South -- Lab.) said: ''The real problem is
that too many MPs regard a seat here as a negotiable asset for private
gain rather than a basis for a vocation.''
However, Nolan Committee member and Tory former Cabinet Minister Tom
King defended lobbying as an ''essential part of the democratic
process''.
He insisted: ''It is not only allowable but actually valuable for MPs
to have outside interests and involvements, because it widens the
experience and contribution they can make.''.
Tory ex-Minister Sir Archibald Hamilton (Epsom and Ewell) said he was
disappointed with the Nolan report.
''It must be a good thing to get professional middle class people to
come into this House,'' he said. ''If they are being told they have got
to do this on a salary of #32,000 a year, to be quite honest they are
not going to come.''
Sir Dudley Smith (Warwick and Leamington -- Con.) complained that
''parliamentary sovereignty is really being undermined'' by Nolan, whom
he described as ''an over-zealous headmaster''.
Labour left-winger Tony Benn (Chesterfield) said MPs might as well
give up if they did not take a ''strong line against the commercial
corruption of Parliament''.
For the Liberal Democrats, Mr Robert Maclennan argued that a pay rise
for MPs and a written constitution would help resolve the problem.
British politics, he said, was ''gratifyingly clean'' compared to some
countries.
Members' Interests Select Committee chairman Sir Geoffrey Johnson
Smith (Wealden -- Con.) warned of the Nolan report: ''There is an awful
lot in this and a lot needs to be thought out, and I do think we are in
danger of under-estimating some of the complications -- deciding what
should and should not be registered.
''I am not at all convinced the Government would be wise to rush into
this. There are a lot of hurdles on the way.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000104</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000104</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pressure on Wiggin</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>978321648</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE heated debate in the Commons came amid the continuing row over the
tabling of an amendment in another MP's name by former Tory Minister Sir
Jerry Wiggin.
He could face suspension from the House.
Sir Jerry, who is in South Africa leading a group of six other MPs on
an investigation into fruit and vegetable farming, is due to check out
of his Cape Town hotel today,
Commons Speaker Betty Boothroyd has said she is ''seriously
examining'' calls for a full investigation into claims that Sir Jerry
broke parliamentary rules in an apparent bid to change a Bill in which
he had a financial interest.
The matter is now expected to end up before the powerful privileges
committee -- which could recommend punishments ranging from a severe
reprimand to suspension from the Commons.
</TEXT>
