<HEADLINE>Labour backs Dromey in bitter union battle</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROY ROGERS, INDUSTRIAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>978321651</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR Party ''spin doctors'' have raised the temperature in the
battle for the leadership of the transport union by heavily promoting
the views of challenger Jack Dromey, who has accused the present general
secretary, Mr Bill Morris, of undermining the party's election chances.
The Transport and General Workers' Union is the largest affiliate of
the party, and the lobbying taking place on behalf of Mr Dromey is
widely interpreted as the continuing emergence of New Labour and
something of a pay-back for Mr Morris's opposition to the party
leadership on Clause 4.
Mr Dromey, who is married to Shadow Employment Secretary Harriet
Harman, probably is best known in Scotland for his close involvement in
campaigns to save jobs at Rosyth dockyard and the Ordnance factory at
Bishopton.
Currently the union's national secretary, Mr Dromey played the Labour
Party card in a key speech to TGWU members in Chester entitled ''A union
in crisis theatening the chances of a Labour Government''.
In it, he spoke of TGWU members being deperate for a Labour Government
yet ''year in,year out, the current union leadership threatened the
chances of a Labour Government.''
In recent years, he said, it had been Bill Morris against John Smith
on one member-one vote or Bill Morris against Tony Blair on reform of
Clause 4 and now there was the prospect of Bill Morris versus Tony Blair
on economic policy at year's annual party conference in Brighton.
TGWU members were crying out for change , crying out for a Labour
Government led by Mr Blair. That was what the TGWU election was all
about -- a strong trade union alongside a strong Labour Government not
an irrelevant union constantly undermining Labour and its leaders.
He suggested that Bill Morris was now only seen in public attacking
the Labour Party. That would not be his approach, Mr Dromey said,
adding: ''While Bill Morris battles with Tony Blair to the dismay of our
members, I fight bad employers and take on the Tories.''
Mr Morris, who has called an election a year before his intitial
five-year term of office was due to expire next May, immediately
condemned the attack as ''the desperate speech of a defeated candidate
who has run out of ideas ,support and, apparently, any loyalty to the
organisation he works for.''
Recalling how Mr Dromey had promised not to attack him personally or
the union or make the Labour Party a campaign issue, he said he had now
broken all three promises, dragging the union through the mud and
dragging the Labour Party into the campaign.
''And he has attacked me for repesenting our union's policies as
determined by the membership.This is not a man the members can trust'',
he declared.
He said that under his leadership ''no-one will do more than the TGWU
to fight for the re-election of a Labour government.
Nominations for the increasingly bitter contest close today when it is
expected they will show something in the region of a 3-1 ratio for Mr
Morris who also has the support of six of the eight regional
secretaries. However previous elections have shown that such support
does not necessarily translate into members' votes.
The Dromey camp and the Labour leadership believe their man will be
swept to office on a tide of support for New Labour which would bring
the largest affiliate firmly on board.
However whoever wins will still have to report to the TGWU lay
executive which ,at least until it too comes up for relection at the end
of the year,remains distinctly Old Labour.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000108</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000108</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Quiet high-flyer whose chance has yet to come</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBBIE DINWOODIE, SCOTTISH POLITICAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>PROFILE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>978321652</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THREE curses hang over Labour candidate Douglas Alexander in this
by-election -- boyish good looks, intelligence, and vaulting
achievement.
The first he will certainly overcome in time, as 10 years from now he
will look his present age of 27.
The second he will get away with, since it has become more fashionable
under New Labour for the IQ to be worn on the sleeve, rather than having
something tattooed across the knuckles.
The third, however, will make it harder for him to wake up to defeat
next Friday morning for he is not someone accustomed to coming second.
Mr Alexander is much more personable on a one-to-one basis than in the
bear pit that passes for by-election press conferences, where he can
seem over-earnest and mechanical in the determination with which he
sticks to his party brief. ''Quite clearly,'' he will reply, before
going on to deliver a far from clear Blairite soundbite.
For example, in an effort to get behind this facade, one reporter this
week tried to find out what issues brought passion to the candidate's
political vision. ''What would you go to the stake for,'' he was asked.
Back came the wording of the party's new Clause 4 about ''power, wealth,
and opportunity in the hands of the many, not the few. '' An audible
groan ran round the room.
And yet, speaking yesterday in a calmer atmosphere, he waxed eloquent
and passionate about the anger and frustration at his coming of age
politically in the Thatcher years; of her denial of such a thing as
society; of young people unable to find a job and middle-class people
terrified of losing one; and of a Government obsessed by market forces
and devoid of moral leadership.
Why did these impassioned sentiments not come across better in the
formal encounters with the massed ranks of reporters? ''Candidates
should not just be there to make journalists' lives interesting,'' he
said.
''It becomes more like a pub quiz than a press conference and the
confrontational nature makes it hard to be friendly. Frankly, it's a bit
of a combat zone but I actually enjoy it.''
He has a point. If candidates keep the lid on their emotions and
responses, they are categorised as earnest and dull. If they respond
more openly they are criticised for being inexperienced and gaffe-prone.
The newspapers had Alexander marked down as diffident, lacking
confidence, over-confident, and having blown his top -- all at the same
meeting. ''Put me on the doorstep and it's not like that,'' he said.
The reference to blowing his top at one meeting this week may have
been over-stated, but he did appear distinctly tetchy when pushed on
whether he would regard coming second as a decent performance. He would
not be happy with that, he insisted.
Where does this competitive edge come from? ''If you care sufficiently
about what you're standing for, of course you have to win. In politics
there are no prizes for second place. We need this determination to
deliver for the people who are relying on us,'' he said.
He put his approach down to hard work and a belief in education and
application, instilled in him during an upbringing which most would
consider to have been a hot house environment.
He was born in Glasgow in 1967 and his father is still the local
minister at Bishopton, Renfrewshire. His mother, a haematologist in
north Ayrshire had become politicised through her experience of the
National Health Service and the young Douglas and his two sisters moved
as if by instinct into the Labour Party they regarded as their natural
political home.
His father, who numbers prominent Conservative Annabel Goldie among
his elders, avoids overt political involvement in his parish. But he,
too, carries a party card. Mr Alexander recalls an upbringing where
politics were discussed at the breakfast table, although he also had a
weakness for football. He has been hinting this week about an affection
for St Johnstone, but is keeping quiet about being a Rangers man.
At the local comprehensive school he claims a sense of humour helped
him avoid coming across as too ernest. ''Otherwise I would have known
about it soon enough and in any case you need a sense of humour to play
rugby of you are my size,'' he said.
From Park Mains High School he won a scholarship to one of the United
World Colleges in Vancouver, where he spent two years rubbing shoulders
with other bright youngsters from across the globe and taking part in
local services including operating the lifeboat and mountain rescue.
On his return, in 1986, he studied history and politics at Edinburgh
University. There he met the academic Paul Addison, who provided a link
with Gordon Brown, who was subsequently to take on Alexander as a
researcher after his graduation in 1990.
When Alexander won the nomination for the present by-election there
were some mutterings that ''Wendy's wee brother'' -- his sister was
well-known for as a researcher at Keir Hardie House -- had not fully
earned his chance through the grind of bearing local office, but had
been touched by greatness through his association with Gordon Brown.
He is a man who leaves little to chance. On the first day of the
campaign it was remarked that his thick mane of dark hair gave him a
passing resemblance to Michael Portillo. He went straight to the barber.
Like all candidates he has to insist that he can win but as a 4-1 shot
with the bookmakers, realistically his chance may have to come later.
One of the things he admits to being passionate about is a Scottish
parliament and he agrees that the Westminster lifestyle is far from
ideal.
In spite of his party's protests to the contrary, the barrage of
Shadow Ministers and the endorsement of Tony Blair will probably not be
enough to propel him to Westminster this time round. Already there is
dark talk of the next General Election or if only the campaign had been
given another week to gain momentum.
The truth is Labour will do well to come second, however painful that
experience may be for the high-flying Douglas Alexander, who will get
his chance to come first another time.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000109</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000109</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Major warns of split on Europe</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GEOFFREY PARKHOUSE, POLITICAL EDITOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321653</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Prime Minister yesterday signalled a fresh row with the European
Commission, if power is further centralised in Brussels.
Such a move would ''split Europe asunder'', he told the Commons 24
hours after his meeting with EU President Jacques Santer.
''It is for national governments, not the European Commission, to take
decisions on Europe's future at the Inter-Governmental Conference. We
will certainly maintain the national veto and we will certainly not
accept any attempt to end the opt-outs that I negotiated in the
Maastricht Treaty.''
Mr Santer has alarmed Tory Euro-sceptics during a visit to Britain. He
has been arguing that an ''a la carte'' Europe, allowing member states
to pick and choose their commitments would not work.
Mr Major, questioned by his back benchers, yesterday insisted: ''The
proposition of a substantial amount of further centralisation, I
believe, would do great damage to Europe, would split it asunder and
ought to be resisted.''
He declared that British opt-outs on a single currency and the social
chapter are part of the Maastricht Treaty and are not for
re-negotiation.
He said: ''We are examing now in the detail the British-position in
Cabinet sub-committees as to how we will approach the IGC.
''When we have completed that detailed consideration, of course it
will be a matter to be discussed within the House. That was the case
before the Maastricht Treaty. It will be the case before the next IGC.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000110</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000110</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Devolution pledge on powers of councils</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>FRANCES HORSBURGH, LOCAL GOVERNMENT CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>978321654</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH local government has nothing to fear from the setting up of a
Scottish parliament Shadow Scottish Secretary George Robertson pledged
yesterday.
He delighted council leaders by giving a clear promise that the Labour
legislation to set up the parliament would guarantee the powers and
responsibilities of local authorities.
This would keep them safe from any predatory instincts of central
government in the future, he said.
Speaking at the Making Change Happen conference on council
reorganisation in Dunblane, which is sponsored by Coopers and Lybrand,
Mr Robertson insisted that it was time to lay to rest the claims by Tory
Ministers that Labour's planned new legislative body would take powers
from local authorities.
He emphasised: ''There is no intention to devolve power from
Westminster simply to centralise it in the hands of people who happen to
be sitting in Edinburgh.''
Elected councillors had the right to know that the Scottish parliament
was not in the business of taking over the functions of local
government, he said.
He promised that the principle of entrenching the powers of local
government would be a significant part of the legislation to set up the
parliament.
Addressing the conference later, Mr George Kynoch, the Scottish Local
Government Minister, said that the speedy decisions of appointment of
chief executives showed that the new unitary councils were fully aware
of the importance of the timescale within which they were operating.
He praised the work done so far by inter-authority committees and said
he hoped that the co-operation would continue, right up until the new
councils took over next April.
However, the Minister added that he hoped the new authorities would
resist the temptation to try to deliver all the services themselves.
Mr Kynoch also warned that councillors in the new all-purpose
authorities would not be able to afford the luxury of involving
themselves in the day to day details of service delivery.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000111</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000111</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Blair back as party goes for broke. Tories now accused of telling defectors to vote Labour</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBBIE DINWOODIE, SCOTTISH POLITICAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321655</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR leader Tony Blair returns to Perthshire today for the
by-election campaign, in a highly personalised intervention that shows
his party is going for broke to prove it can win the contest.
Mr Blair seems determined to confound critics who say his second visit
of the campaign in support of candidate Douglas Alexander is a high-risk
strategy which will damage him if the voters of Perth and Kinross do not
respond. His walk-about in Crieff this morning will be followed by no
fewer than six shadow cabinet ministers in the next four days.
SNP chief executive Michael Russell said last night: ''As a day
visitor I am sure Mr Blair will find Crieff interesting, but he will
have to work very hard to find any Labour vote there.''
Yesterday saw a welter of campaign claim and counter-claim. Tories
were accused of making personal attacks on the doorsteps against SNP
front-runner Roseanna Cunningham.
The Nationalists also claimed that following Conservative candidate
John Godfrey's controversial tactic of urging Tory defectors to give
their protest vote to anyone but the SNP, party workers were now
specifically saying these people should vote Labour. Such a bizarre
endorsement, presumably designed to create the maximum split in the
vote, would carry the risk of pushing the Tories into third place.
It was even suggested by Liberal Democrat MP Charles Kennedy,
supporting candidate Veronica Linklater, that the Tories could come
fourth. He also accused Labour of falling into the classic trap of
believing its own propaganda.
The day began with Home Office Minister Michael Forsyth attacking the
media for the spate of stories suggesting that he wanted the job of
Scottish Secretary Ian Lang. Mr Forsyth has been seen by most observers
as being at the centre of these stories since a return to a Scottish
portfolio would assist his attempts to hang on to his highly marginal
Stirling seat. But he accused the media of engaging in tittle-tattle
which deflected from the Tories' efforts in the by-election campaign.
Even then he was unable to avoid a hint of controversy when he said:
''At the moment Ian Lang is Secretary of State. He has done an
outstanding job and done well.'' The phrase ''at the moment'' was
immediately invested with great significance.
Mr Forsyth, in a high-spirited attack on the SNP candidate, whom he
described as an extreme republican and socialist, gave the kind of
bravura performance which his supporters feel he would bring to the post
at St Andrew's House.
By contrast last night, a speech in Perth by Mr Lang was a very
straighforward statement of the case for the Union which said little
that had not already been put across in recent days.
The SNP theme yesterday was NHS cuts which are reducing the number of
beds for the elderly infirm, and penalising people by taking their homes
and savings if they have to be taken into care. Ms Cunningham described
this as something which was causing profound anxiety and an offence to
the notion of a decent society.
Shadow Chancellor Gordon Brown attacked the SNP in terms very similar
to the criticisms from Conservatives. He referred to ''extreme
anti-monarchist separatism'' which he contrasted with Labour policies
characterised by moderation and common sense. He said that on Rosyth and
the nuclear industry the SNP had to explain what it would do about the
impact of the policies on jobs.
</TEXT>
