<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Company director appalled by assault on researcher during Glasgow visit. Knife men in stab attack on scientist</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM TINNING</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321656</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A RESEARCH scientist on a one-day business trip to Glasgow was
repeatedly stabbed on the head and body while he and a friend were
making their way to a restaurant.
As Dr Luigi ''Gino'' Martini, 26, recovered in hospital yesterday, one
of the directors of his company, a pharmaceutical company with worldwide
interests, said he was appalled.
Dr Marry Seager, of the Swindon-based Scherer DDS claimed he was not
aware of any of their 3000 employees worldwide being subjected to such
an attack while carrying out company business.
Dr Martini from Swindon, Wiltshire, and fellow research scientist, Dr
Jonathan Embleton, 29, of Newbury, Berkshire, were attacked on Wednesday
night about 10.20pm by two young men carrying knives, as they made their
way through a car park in the city's Rouken Glen Park towards a Chinese
restaurant.
Detectives say the attack had been ''completely unprovoked''.
Both scientists tried to run away after being confronted, but Mr
Martini, a bachelor, was caught and knocked to the ground where he was
repeatedly stabbed on the head and body. Mr Embleton, also a bachelor,
was not injured but was said to be distressed by the ordeal.
Dr Martini was rushed to the city's Victoria Infirmary where his
condition was initially described as serious although last night he was
''satisfactory''. His parents were on their way to visit him.
The attack on Dr Martini, a pharmacist, and Dr Embleton, a chemist,
occurred less than 800 yards from the Macdonald Thistle Hotel in
Giffnock, where they were staying. They had checked in a few hours
earlier and were on a one-day visit to the city to ''further their
research.''
Dr Seager, director of Scherer DDS, which is part of the US-based RB
Scherer Corporation, said the two men had travelled widely on company
business and ''knew how to keep out of harm's way.''
Speaking from the company's Swindon office he added: : ''Everyone here
is shocked and horrified. We are very distressed and greatly concerned.
It amazes me to think people can do this to others.
''Our business regularly involves many of our employees travelling
throughout Britain and the world to meet academics and companies to
further our research and development.
''As far as I know none of RB Scherer's employees has ever been
attacked in this way before and they regularly visit cities which have
much more violent reputations than Glasgow.''
Dr Seager said the attack had not changed his opinion of Glasgow. ''We
are very fond of it,'' he said. ''We have a company in Clydebank and
regard our Scottish employees very highly. They are dear friends to us.
We all think Glasgow is a great place. It is very sad when when this
sort of thing happens.''
Dr Stephen Jones, a director at the Clydebank headquarters of Scherer
DDS, who visited Dr Martini in hospital yesterday, said: ''He was fine
considering the circumstances and is making a good recovery.''
The director said he had also spoken to Dr Embleton who was ''upset
and distressed'' by the attack.
The man leading the hunt for the two assailants, Detective Sergeant
Campbell Farquharson of Giffnock CID, said the attack had been
''completely unprovoked.''
The attackers had stolen Dr Martini's anorak-style jacket containing
his wallet. The wallet was recovered at the scene although the jacket
was still missing.
Mr Farquharson added: ''This appears to have been an isolated
incident. However, attacks like this do nothing to promote the image of
the city.''
He said the two assailants were both in their early 20s. One was
wearing a dark coloured leather jacket and denims; the other a bright
red jacket.
Anyone with information should telephone 0141 883 0491.
</TEXT>
