<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000113</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000113</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Judges reject plea for Leeson's release</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>978321657</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A CALL for the immediate release of former Barings trader Nick Leeson
was turned down by a German court yesterday.
Judges rejected claims by Mr Leeson's lawyers that his continued
detention pending extradition proceedings was ''wrong in law''.
Mr Stephen Pollard, Mr Leeson's English lawyer, insisted that a
forgery charge on which his client is being held was invalid.
The plea for the trader's release on bail was lodged on Monday, citing
inconsistencies in extradition papers submitted by the Singapore
authorities.
Mr Leeson faces four charges of forgery and eight of ''cheating'' in
connection with multi-million pound futures trading in Barings'
Singapore office.
But he is being held on the basis of a specimen charge alleging he
forged the signature of a New York broker in a bid to top up funds to
keep his trading alive as the markets crashed.
Mr Pollard insisted there was no evidence of forgery -- just a
question of a signature being photocopied, with no confirmation that Mr
Leeson was responsible.
Mr Pollard said the charge was not punishable under German law, and
therefore invalid as a basis for extradition, but the judges rejected
the bail application.
Now Mr Leeson, 28, remains in custody in the Frankfurt jail where he
has languished since flying to the city in March following the collapse
of Barings with the loss of hundreds of millions of pounds on futures
trading.
Mr Pollard is still hoping that a British extradition appeal will be
lodged in Germany, giving Mr Leeson the option of returning home to face
a judicial system which, his lawyer claims, is less draconian than the
regime in Singapore.
The Serious Fraud Office has been given copies of the extradition
warrant, with Mr Pollard pointing out parts of the evidence which he
says could amount to a charge of ''false accounting'' in UK law.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000114</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000114</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>#200m ships decision on hold</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN BRUCE, DEFENCE CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321658</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
YARROW Shipbuilders will have to wait until next week to learn if it
has won a #200m order to build four patrol corvettes for the South
African Navy.
The South African Cabinet is currently reviewing the bids from the
main contenders, Yarrow and the Spanish, state-owned Bazan.
There has been behind-the-scenes pressure from German, Danish and
French shipyards for a new round of tendering.
But a Yarrow spokesman said yesterday it was unlikely that the contest
would be widened. He said: ''There is simply a delay in the
decision-making process in Pretoria. As far as we are aware, only
ourselves and Bazan are in the running.''
Both the Clyde yard and Bazan, based near Cadiz, have offered 100%
deals backed by export credit loans aimed at stimulating the local South
African economy. This ''offset'' investment from either the UK or Spain
would equal the cost of the warship programme.
Among GEC-owned Yarrow's proposals is a scheme to transfer technology
and allow South Africa to build further warships under licence in
future, and a promise to set up a new local company to build
prefabricated houses -- a major issue for President Nelson Mandela in
his struggle to rid South Africa of squatter camps.
Bazan is also offering technology transfer, and a straight loan to
allow construction of fishing vessels in South Africa. Both are offering
home-based naval training packages to SAN personnel.
South Africa's defence budget allows #118m for maritime defence this
year and a further #120m in 1996.
Given its key strategic location guarding the Cape, South Africa is
keen to gain a ''blue water'' navy and replace its existing handful of
ageing diesel-electric submarines and a few Israeli-designed inshore
patrol boats.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
