<HEADLINE>Trader in wild falcons jailed for 18 months</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321660</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MAN was jailed for 18 months yesterday after being found guilty of
illegally selling or holding 22 wild peregrine falcons.
Derek Canning, 33, of Riding Mill, Northumberland, denied six charges
of selling peregrines and another of holding the birds of prey for sale
during 1992-93 at Newcastle Crown Court.
He claimed the birds he sold and others found in a raid on his home in
July 1993 were all produced from licensed captive, adult birds.
DNA tests proved that Canning must have used wild birds to produce the
number of fledglings which passed through his hands.
After the verdicts it was disclosed he had a previous conviction for
similar offences.
The jury had heard how Canning had maps pinpointing at least 10
peregrine eyries in southern Scotland, Northumberland and Cumbria.
The UK peregrine population has, through conservation, increased to
more than 1000 pairs, 25% of the European total.
Mr Guy Shorrocks for the RSPB welcomed the judgment and said that five
of the 16 peregrines taken from Canning during the inquiry would be
returned to the wild.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000117</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000117</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lifeboat coxswain gets top honour</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321661</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE coxswain of Lerwick lifeboat has been awarded one of the RNLI's
highest bravery honours following the rescue of 67 Russian seamen in
appalling weather last year.
Mr Hewitt Clark, 49, was presented with the RNLI's silver medal --
only eight have been awarded in the past 10 years -- by the Duchess of
Kent in London yesterday.
Mr Clark and his crew made 70 trips to the factory ship Pionersk in
the teeth of a gale on October 31 last year.
An official RNLI report said: ''The fact that no lives were lost or
injuries sustained makes it seem easy. But the seamanship, consummate
skill and boat-handling ability of Coxswain Clark was second to none.
''To go in and take a lifeboat where there was absolutely no margin
for error is a skill in itself. To do it in the conditions that
prevailed that night and in total darkness is beyond belief. To do so
over 70 times without loss of life or injury is surely nothing short of
a miracle.''
At the RNLI's annual annual general meeting which preceded the awards'
ceremony, institution chairman Sir Michael Vernon warned of a funding
crisis.
Legacy income, which makes up the largest part of the RNLI's funding,
fell 4% last year and the trend continued into 1995. The lifeboat
service relies entirely on voluntary donations, he added.
The institution also recorded its busiest year, saving the lives of
1624 people and bringing nearly 1000 more ashore.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000118</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000118</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Council to appeal on sauna ruling</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LYNNE ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>978321662</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EDINBURGH District Council is to appeal to the Court of Session over a
sheriff's decision to revoke a licence for a Leith sauna, which a
mother-of-two claimed would be used as a brothel.
Council leader Lesley Hinds said last night the authority had been
''disappointed'' at the ruling over the Gemini Sauna in Iona Street.
''That's one of the reasons why we are appealing, although we are
appealing on a matter of law,'' she said.
But Councillor Hinds stressed the judgment made it clear that
allegations over a ''purported policy'' that they knowingly licensed
saunas which could be used for prostitution had been unfounded and
formed no part of the sheriff's findings.
The council has 28 days to lodge its appeal, although a hearing is not
expected before the end of the year.
Councillor Hinds stressed the judgment applied only to this particular
case and would not affect any other sauna applications which would be
dealt with in the usual way. The case had been dealt with on its
individual merits, she said.
The sauna -- which had been granted a temporary five-month licence,
due to expire next month -- is now expected to go ''into limbo''.
Councillor Hinds admitted there was nothing to stop a further
application in a different name for an entertainments licence.
In ruling the council made a mistake, Sheriff Nigel Thomson said the
authority's licensing sub-committee had ample evidence to show the
Gemini Sauna in Iona Street, Leith, would have been used for
prostitution.
In a written judgment at Edinburgh Sheriff Court, the sheriff said:
''There was, in my view, a mass of material before the committee from
which they could form a view of the applicant's intention.
''The committee was, no doubt, well aware that it would be illegal to
have a brothel in Iona Street,'' wrote the sheriff.
The Edinburgh-based Scottish HIV Action (SHIVA) group warned the
ruling would put the capital's 200 sauna workers at risk.
SHIVA outreach worker Ms Joette Thomas said: ''If the criminal element
comes back into saunas, there will certainly be an increase in women on
the street, which would put more women in danger. They wouldn't have the
security element and the protection of an operation that was above
board.''
Mrs Debra Scanlan, who took the authority to court to appeal their
decision to license the Gemini Sauna -- only yards from her Leith home
-- was yesterday staying tight-lipped about her victory. She was among a
number of objectors who opposed the original sauna application.
Her lawyer, Mr Robert Hayhow, is reported to have said they would
fight any appeal by the council.
A spokesman for the owner of the Gemini Sauna, Mr Ian Haig, said he
was also considering an appeal.
In his written judgment, Sheriff Nigel Thomson ruled the council's
licensing sub-committee had been both wrong in law and unreasonable in
the way it exercised its discretion in granting the licence.
Sheriff Thomson said the original objections to the sauna ''were
rooted in the likelihood of what was described as a 'health studio'
turning out to be a brothel''.
Sheriff Thomson also referred to letters in support of Mr Haig's
application which had been considered by the council. These had
mentioned such matters as reducing kerb-crawling, preventing incidents
of women being accosted in the streets and promoting safe sex.
Although he had the power to send the application back to the
committee, Sheriff Thomson said he had decided to go further and simply
reverse the decision to grant the licence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000119</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000119</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tests support adultery theory</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN MACDERMID, MEDICAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321663</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Greek Army has come to the rescue of the Episcopalian Bishop of
Edinburgh, under fire for his comments about the ''promiscuous gene''
which critics have interpreted as condoning adultery.
Army recruits who volunteered for blood tests on their first day in
the forces in Athens have helped to establish that male sexuality is a
matter of chemistry.
The governing factor is a hormone, rather than a gene, but the
discovery reinforces the Most Rev Richard Holloway's plea for
understanding for people who have ''followed their instincts''.
Dr Christos Mantzoros, an endocrinologist at Harvard Medical School in
Boston, conducted the tests, accompanied by a questionnaire, on 92 males
aged 18-22, and reports the results today British Medical Journal.
Sexual activity was based on the average weekly number of orgasms over
the previous month (the circumstances were not gone into) and the blood
samples were subjected to a battery of biochemical tests.
The mean weekly number of orgasms was 3.5, on a range of 0 to 11, and
the hormone with most influence on this was dihydrotestosterone, a
metabolite of the male hormone testosterone.
Dr Mantzoros concludes: ''The frequency of orgasms depends not only on
psycho-social factors but on variation of dihydrotestosterone
concentrations within the normal range.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000120</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000120</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Stirling defers 'cathedral' plan</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321664</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
COUNCILLORS called last night for urgent talks with an English-based
drugs company which wants to build what has been described as a mock
cathedral with a 70ft tower in the shadow of Stirling Castle.
The call came after Stirling district councillors voted unanimously to
defer the scheme after a last-minute intervention by the Secretary of
State.
Surrey-based Scotia Pharmaceuticals had earlier threatened to drop a
1000 job scheme if the proposal was vetoed.
In a letter faxed to the council's head of planning, Mrs Sheila Terry,
less than 45 minutes before councillors were due to vote, the Scottish
Office environment department said that the Secretary of State wanted to
time to consider ''calling in'' the proposal if it were approved.
Scottish Office planner, Mr John Gillespie told Mrs Terry that Mr Lang
had taken the decision ''in view of the possible effect on the setting
of Stirling Castle''.
A mass of objections to the plan included one from the Scottish
Office's ancient monuments arm, Historic Scotland.
The direction does not commit the Secretary of State to calling in the
application, but reserves his right to intervene. He will have to give
his decision within 28 days.
Moving deferral, council leader Mr Keith Harding said the matter was
too important to be rushed.
He told fellow councillors: ''This council has a good record of caring
about the history and heritage of Stirling, but we are also aware of the
economic potential and we do wish to attract Scotia to Stirling with the
jobs that would come with it.
''We don't want the wrong message to go out from Stirling -- that
we're against development -- but we have to address the concerns of all
the outside bodies and individuals who have written to us.''
Work is almost complete on a new two-storey office building for Scotia
on the prestigious but controversial Castle Business Park.
But Scotia has applied for permission to build a two and three-storey
extension, more than trebling its office space, with a 70ft hexagonal
tower forming a fourth-storey centrepiece.
The most scathing criticism has come from the Royal Fine Art
Commission for Scotland, which alleged the ''tired and inappropriate
concept of repeated mock cathedrals with cruciform plans'' as aspects of
the plan which ''very seriously threatened one of the most important
settings in Scotland''.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000121</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000121</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>President's men find reward in Cabinet</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NICHOLAS POWELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321665</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
In Paris
ALAIN JUPPE, newly-appointed Prime Minister to President Jacques
Chirac, announced his new Government yesterday.
With 39 Ministers and Secretaries of State, it is larger by 10 members
than the outgoing government of Prime Minister Edouard Balladur and a
scrupulous mix of members of the UDF and Gaullist RPR, which form the
conservative majority in the National Assembly.
The new government rewards the most faithful colleagues and followers
of the newly-elected President, retaining only Francois Bayrou, 43, as
Minister of Education from the previous Cabinet.
Several eminent personalities of the former regime, such as Interior
Minister Charles Pasqua, a political enemy of Mr Juppe, and Budget
Minister Nicholas Sarkozy, both of whom supported Mr Balladur against Mr
Chirac during the election, are unemployed.
With the creation of several new Ministries, including one called
Integration and the Fight Against Exclusion and another termed
Solidarity between the Generations, President Chirac and Mr Juppe are
evidently trying to fulfil election promises to make the struggle
against unemployment and poverty a top priority.
Jacques Toubon, 54, Minister of Culture in the outgoing Government,
was at the Cannes Film Festival yesterday when he learned he had been
appointed Minister of Justice, the second most important job in the
government after Prime Minister. His replacement as Culture Minister is
42-year-old Philippe Douste-Blazy, the mayor of Lourdes and current
Minister for Health.
Alain Madelin, 49, the first senior member of the UDF to come out in
support of President Chirac and noted for his liberal economic views,
was made Minister of Economy and Finance. Herve de Charette, another
Chirac supporter from the UDF, takes over from Mr Juppe as Foreign
Affairs Minister while Jean-Louis Debre, 50, son of General de Gaulle's
Prime Minister Michel Debre, goes to the Ministry of Interior.
Charles Millon, 49, who stood briefly in the presidential election as
candidate for the UDF before rallying President Chirac's camp, is
Defence Minister.
The Ministry of Health goes to 38-year-old Dr Elisabeth Hubert, one of
the few women to hold a senior position in the new government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000122</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000122</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Health workers spread net for killer virus victims as toll rises</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN MACDERMID, MEDICAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321666</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Kinshasa, Thursday
HEALTH workers searched the quarantined Zairian city of Kikwit today
for victims of the deadly Ebola virus after the killer bug appeared to
have escaped from medical centres where it was initially isolated.
The World Health Organisation in Geneva announced that experts on the
ground in south-west Zaire had identified 114 cases, of whom 79 had died
-- most of them in Kikwit.
The tropical city with a population of 600,000 remains the epicentre
of the outbreak, which began at a local hospital at the end of March or
early April. However, the search for victims has now widened to
surrounding villages.
Today's WHO figures represented an increase of 13 since the United
Nations body reported yesterday, warning of a further surge over the
coming days.
The Red Cross said three of its Zairean volunteer workers were among
the dead while a fourth was in the last stages of the disease and beyond
medical aid.
A WHO spokesman said despite fears in the Zairean capital Kinshasa, no
cases had been identified there. The increase in reported cases over the
past few days has followed checks by health workers in villages around
Kikwit.
There is no known antidote or cure for the virus, which kills by
causing severe internal bleeding. Infection is passed on by close
contact or by infected blood, which emerges through the skin of victims.
In the US today, the Centre for Disease Control and Prevention ordered
all airlines to notify the agency if any passengers headed to the US
were ill with fever or vomiting blood, two Ebola symptoms.
A Zairian man who arrived in Toronto aboard an airliner from Belfast,
was put in 21-day quarantine overnight after telling Canadian officials
his mother died in the area stricken by Ebola.
Meanwhile, a Swiss zoologist who survived the Ebola virus has provided
scientists with the first proven link between human infection and
monkeys, writes Medical Correspondent ALAN MacDERMID.
The 34-year-old woman caught the virus from a dead chimpanzee on which
she had performed a post-mortem examination in the Tai National Park in
Cote d'Ivoire, West Africa, the Lancet reports.
Her illness last November was not connected with the outbreak in
Zaire, and scientists from the Pasteur Institute in Paris say it is a
new strain, bringing the total of Ebola strains to four.
Despite a general assumption that Ebola has jumped species from monkey
to human, this the first time that a human infection has been connected
to naturally-infected monkeys in Africa.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
