<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000125</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000125</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Canadians hear evidence against Bernardo over schoolgirl murders</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321669</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Toronto, Thursday
A MAN accused of kidnapping and killing two schoolgirls went on trial
today in one of the most closely watched cases in Canadian legal
history.
Spectators jammed Toronto's largest courtroom and strained to see
30-year-old Paul Bernardo as he was led in. He wore a dark suit and
appeared relaxed.
Bernardo is charged with killing Leslie Mahaffy, 14, and Kristen
French, 15, both of Ontario. If convicted, he could face up to life in
prison.
Prosecutor Ray Houlahan argued in his opening statement that the
killings were premeditated and took place in connection with confinement
and sexual assault.
He presented a litany of graphic detail, charging that the suspect and
his former wife took the girls in separate incidents to their home,
where they were sexually abused and murdered.
Justice Patrick LeSage gave detailed instructions to the eight men and
four women on the jury. He said they would be presented with a variety
of evidence, including videotapes.
Authorities say the trial will involve dozens of witnesses and stretch
over several months.
Bernardo's former wife, Karla Homolka, 25, will probably be among
those witnesses. She was convicted two years ago of manslaughter in
connection with the deaths and sentenced to 12 years in prison.
Mahaffy vanished in 1991. Her body parts were found encased in
concrete two weeks later. French's abduction a year later raised fears a
serial killer was operating in southern Ontario.
Following Homolka's trial, a judge slapped a ban on publicising key
details of the case in an effort to ensure the jury would be impartial
in Bernardo's trial.
Justice Patrick LeSage must still rule on a key question -- whether
journalists and other courtroom spectators can see videotapes that
LeSage said would be graphic and ''disturbing'' to many people.
The victims' families want them screened so that only the judge, jury,
and lawyers can see and hear them. News organisations fought the
request.--AP.
</TEXT>
