<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000126</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000126</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hollywood madam turns down plea deal</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321670</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Los Angeles, Thursday
CONVICTED Hollywood madam Heidi Fleiss said in an interview published
today that she has rejected a deal offered by prosecutors which would
have put her in prison for less than four years.
Fleiss said she had chosen to fight the case in court instead of
accepting the plea bargain, which would have required her to plead
guilty to federal money laundering and tax evasion.
''I already told them no deal,'' she told the Los Angeles Daily News.
''I don't think it's any deal at all. I'm offended by the offer. It
might as well be a life sentence.''
Fleiss, who is accused of running a high-priced call-girl ring
catering to the Hollywood elite, was scheduled to be sentenced tomorrow
for her conviction last December on three counts of pandering.
She faces from three to nine years in prison for providing undercover
police officers with prostitutes in the state case.
However the separate federal case against her carries an even heavier
penalty.
Fleiss, 29, is charged with laundering the proceeds of her
prostitution business, tax evasion, and conspiracy. If convicted, she
could be sentenced to up to 158 years in prison.
Fleiss contended that she was being unfairly targeted. ''It's like sex
is the worst crime on earth,'' she said.
Last week her father, paediatrician Dr Paul Fleiss, who was also
charged in the federal case, agreed to plead guilty to income tax fraud
in exchange for a lighter sentence.--Reuter.
</TEXT>
