<DOCID>GH950519-000129</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Recognition move raises Bosnia heat</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321673</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Sarajevo, Thursday
SNIPER barriers went up along Sarajevo's frontlines today after a
three-day onslaught on the Bosnian capital left 15 people dead and
dozens more wounded.
The level of fighting eased today after earlier artillery barrages and
small-arms exchanges described as the worst in 18 months. However, the
killing of civilians continued.
Local media put today's toll at three dead and 12 wounded while United
Nations officials confirmed two dead and nine wounded.
Most devastating was a Serb mortar shell which slammed into a market
place, killing a man and wounding six other people. Two Russian
peacekeepers also stepped on anti-personnel mines in the Serb-held
suburb of Grbavica.
UN spokesman Lieutenant Colonel Gary Coward justified holding off
punitive Nato airstrikes by saying that most fighting had been
''military on military''.
Neither side has made significant gains around the city, the UN said.
However they could be jostling for position amid hints that Serbian
President Slobodan Milosevic is preparing to recognise
Bosnia-Herzegovina.
Milosevic, instigator of the Serb rebellion that started the Bosnian
war in April 1992, has had talks all week in Belgrade with a top US
envoy about a deal that would suspend punitive trade sanctions on Serbia
if he recognises Bosnia.
That would not halt fighting immediately, but it could be the first
step in a protracted endgame to the wars in former Yugoslavia.
''Shortly, we will see Milosevic convinced to issue a declaration in
which he recognises the territorial integrity and the internationally
recognised borders of Bosnia-Herzegovina,'' said Greek Foreign Minister
Carolos Papoulias after talks with his Austrian counterpart in Vienna.
''One cannot always just demand something from Milosevic, without
wanting to give him something,'' added Papoulias, one of the few Western
officials with good ties to the Serbian leader.
Meanwhile, thousands of Serbs were on the run in north-west Bosnia
today after the army of the Muslim-led government took a town and three
villages just south of the beleaguered government-held town of Bihac.
There were indications the Serbs had evacuated the settlements in
anticipation. UN officials said up to 6000 had fled.
About 155,000 residents in the government-held Bihac enclave were
reported by relief officials to be facing starvation unless its
besiegers lifted their blockade on relief convoys.--AP/Reuter.
</TEXT>
