<DOCNO>GH950519-000138</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000138</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Patients given new pills to treat cancer</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321682</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PILLS designed to curb any kind of fast growing cancer tumour are
being tested on patients in Britain.
The drug called BB-2516 has been developed by British Biotech of
Oxford. If the first human trials prove successful, the company plans to
try the pills out on many more people.
Patients with cancers of the colon, prostate, ovary, or pancreas have
been taking two pills the size of aspirins twice a day. The company is
hoping the drug will stabilise growths and allow patients to live
reasonably normal lives, according to a report in New Scientist
magazine.
BB-2516 neutralises enzymes that are overproduced by tumours. It is
these that help the cancer to spread and allow invading growths to
establish the blood supply that is vital for further growth.
Blocking the action of the enzymes should prevent the tumours from
starting secondary growths in other organs.
Chief executive of British Biotech, Mr Keith McCullagh, said: ''If you
can take a pill every day for the rest of your life that keeps the
cancer under control, it will transform people's expectations of
cancer.''
However, he warned against raising expectations too high at this
stage, despite claims of encouraging results from experiments on
animals.
''Until we complete these preliminary human trials, we can't say
anything positive,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000139</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000139</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Chirac affirms Kohl as partner</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALISTER DOYLE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321683</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Strasbourg, Thursday
FRENCH President Jacques Chirac, in his first foreign policy act, met
German Chancellor Helmut Kohl today and reaffirmed Franco-German
partnership as the heart of European Union.
Chirac said after meeting Kohl for an hour that both ''have an equally
strong will for European construction''.
Both men said there would be no change in Franco-German relations
after Chirac's takeover from Socialist President Francois Mitterrand and
that the partnership would be constantly reinforced.
In a largely symbolic meeting in Strasbourg, home of the European
Parliament near the German border, the two leaders skirted around
possible economic policy differences over unemployment.
Chirac dismissed as ''absurd and unfounded'' reports that he might
suggest a shake-up of the European currency grid.
Kohl said there were some differences of approach but that egoism and
national interest on the part of either Germany or France would be
impossible as long-term solutions.
Using body language to demonstrate harmony, the two conservative
politicians smiled broadly and shook hands several times on the steps of
the ornate 1870 building at the start of the meeting in Strasbourg, home
of the European Parliament.
At a meeting earlier with fellow Christian Democrats at the European
Parliament, Kohl said the new French president was an old friend and he
believed they saw eye-to-eye on the importance of continuing European
integration.
''The most important task is to pursue the process of European
integration. That's the aim of our meeting with Jacques Chirac and I
think I am in agreement with him on this point,'' Kohl said.
He said the priorities of an EU summit which Chirac is to chair in the
French Riviera resort of Cannes at the end of June were ''continuing the
policy of monetary stability'' and studying new possibilities for
co-operation with central and eastern Europe.
Yesterday, Chirac's office had to crush suggestions that he might
propose a shake-up of the European Union's currency grid, perhaps
accepting a weaker franc to help combat unemployment. The rumours drove
the franc down against the Deutschmark.
French and German officials insisted the Franco-German axis would
remain the motor of Europe even though some Chirac backers are cool to
EU integration and a single European currency.
German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel said Chirac and his newly
appointed Prime Minister Alain Juppe, until now Kinkel's counterpart,
stood for ''continuity in foreign policy''.
''Changes of government on this or that side of the Rhine have never
resulted in a need to reinvent German-French friendship,'' Kinkel wrote
in the French daily Le Monde, adding that it was more often a chance to
reinvigorate the ties.
Jean-Jacques de Peretti, a close aide to Chirac, dismissed suggestions
that Chirac might depart from a decade-old ''strong franc'' policy, even
though this has often meant high interest rates in France.
''Jacques Chirac has been falsely judged during the whole campaign on
that issue,'' he told RTL radio. ''He is without doubt the man most
focused on the strong franc and on the overall balance (in the
economy).''
Markets fear that Chirac will have problems reconciling his campaign
goals of boosting wages, cutting taxes, and creating jobs with keeping
the franc pegged to the mark and slashing the budget deficit.
He has also signalled a less enthusiastic stance on Europe than his
predecessor, Francois Mitterrand, by suggesting a referendum on EU
reforms.
In another development, Kinkel today announced that he would step down
next month as leader of the small liberal Free Democratic Party, which
has been battered by mounting losses at the polls.
He pledged to stay on as German Foreign Minister and Vice-Chancellor
in Kohl's centre-right coalition.--Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000140</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000140</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scots targeted by rogue charities. Firms in Border raids to evade new laws</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROB ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321684</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Scottish public has no adequate legal protection from unscrupulous
English companies who move north of the Border and rip them off by
falsely claiming to be collecting for charity.
At least eight English firms have switched their activities to
Scotland, particularly Glasgow and Edinburgh, because of the lack of a
legal framework in Scotland to control their activities.
Charity bosses believe the companies have moved north because they
would be prosecuted under new English law if they continued their
activities south of the Border.
The companies involved claim they raise money for charity, but pass on
little or none of the money collected.
The worst offenders are companies who run lottery schemes in shopping
malls for what they claim to be charity, publishing firms who claim part
of the money from their magazines go to good causes, and charity card
sellers.
The concern over their activities has come from the Scottish Council
For Voluntary Organisations, the representative body for Scottish
charities, and the Institute of Charity Fund-raising Managers which acts
as the professional body for charity fund-raisers.
Hilary Mounfield, chairwoman of the ICFM, said it was ''appalling''
that Scottish people who donated to charity were not as well protected
by law as those in England.
She said Scottish law should be brought into line with English
legislation on fund-raising, and said that, in the interim, the
institute had been forced to draw up a voluntary self-regulation code
for Scottish charities.
In England and Wales, the 1992 Charities Act imposes strict curbs on
how charities operate. Legislation dealing with fund-raising activities
set out in the Act only came into affect in March of this year. Similar
rules on fund-raising are included in a Government White Paper for
Northern Ireland.
Despite a campaign by the SCVO, similar legislation on fund-raising
was not extended to Scotland, leading to charity bosses introducing
their own code for charities because of growing concern over rogue
fund-raisers and the lack of legal proceedure to deal with them. The
code will only have power over around 1000 of the 20000 charities in
Scotland, but the institute hopes to highlight complaints from the
general public about non-members.
As well as fund-raising problems, the Scottish organisations are
concerned over how big a financial cut professional fund-raising
consultants take when called in by charities to run joint promotions.
Difficulties with fraudulent fund-raisers who collect for general
charitable purposes rather than named charities have also been
expressed.
Scottish Office chiefs believe there are enough safeguards already in
place to keep rogue collectors at bay. They point to the Scottish
Charities Office which investigates charities, local authority rules on
street collection and parts of the Law Reform (Miscellaneous Provisions)
(Scotland) Act 1990.
Lucy Pratt, policy analyst of the SCVO, said she did not accept the
Government's argument and said her organisation had made its concerns
over rogue fund-raisers clear.
Mr Stephen Lee, UK director of the ICFM, said he knew that at least
eight English firms had moved north because of the tight new legislation
south of the Border.
Labour's National Heritage spokesman Maria Fyfe said it was a worry
when charity experts were raising concerns over the lack of fund-raising
legislation and legal protection for charity donors.
Mrs Fyfe said: ''It is highly significant that these very respected
charity bodies feel the law is inadequate. I would urge the Government
to take a fresh look at the whole issue.''
Ms Mounfield added: ''Ultimately we hope that legislation will be
introduced in Scotland to supersede the voluntary code of practice. In
the meantime, the new code will go a long way to reassure the public
that when they are asked for money for charity, that it is a legitimate
request.''
Trevor Jones, vice-chairman of the ICFM in Scotland, said that people
giving to charities should not be scared to ask specific questions about
where their money was going.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000141</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000141</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>San Diego tank thief flattens suburb in chase to death</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>PATRICK BROGAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>978321685</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Washington, Thursday
A SUBURB of San Diego, California, was devastated yesterday when an
unemployed plumber stole a tank and drove down the streets, flattening
and knocking over telephone poles and power lines.
Shawn Nelson, 35, was a trained army tank crew member who had talked
about suicide and had apparently praised last month's Oklahoma City
bombing.
He was fatally shot by police when the tank stuck on a concrete
divider in the centre of highway 163 after a 30-minute joyride.
The tank was a 63-ton M-60, the basic battle tank of the American
army, and Nelson stole it from the National Guard armoury. Guard
officials were too embarrassed to offer any explanation of how he
managed to drive away with such a weapon.
The tank's guns were not loaded: all the damage was done by its sheer
bulk and weight.
After Nelson got into the tank and started it, he escaped from the
Guard compound in the simplest way possible -- by running over the gate.
In scenes reminiscent of a Hollywood action film, police pursued him
down the road, but police cars are not much good at stopping a tank
driving at 45mph. Nelson deliberately ran over at least 25 cars, fire
hydrants, and power and telephone poles.
Witnesses said Nelson, whose head was sticking up through the hatch,
was smiling and laughing as the tank rumbled along.
''He came right for us. He looked out of his tank and he just looked
right at us . . . he was trying to kill us,'' said one tearful woman.
Another resident added: ''The expression on his face was: 'Hey, I'm
having fun'.''
Finally the tank ran over the central divide, and stuck. The driver
rocked it back and forth, attempting to get it free.
Four policemen seized the occasion to jump on top of it. They opened
the hatch with bolt cutters. When the thief refused to come out, they
shot him, and he was reported dead at hospital.
Police said Nelson had served with the US army and trained as a tank
crew member at Fort Knox, Kentucky. He also served with a tank battalion
in Germany.
Nelson had been down on his luck and had been acting strangely, police
added. He was out of work, had financial problems, and recently broke up
with his girlfriend.
Nelson had talked to neighbours and friends about suicide and a week
before the incident told a neighbour he wanted to get hold of a tank,
said police spokesman Captain Tom Hall.
Referring to last month's Oklahoma City bombing that killed 166
people, Hall told a news conference that Nelson had said to a neighbour:
''Oklahoma was good stuff.''
However Hall added that Nelson had made no threats. There was no
indication that he had any links to armed militias or held
anti-government views.
Hall defended Nelson's shooting, saying their job was to protect the
public and they had no other option. ''Municipal police officers are not
equipped to stop a 60-ton tank,'' he added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
