<TEXT>
RUNAWAY banker Ian Lumb, who fled the country with #94,000 from the
branch where he worked, began a two-year jail sentence last night.
Lumb, 38, had told his wife Susan, 33, nothing of the massive debts of
#130,000 that caused his mental breakdown and led to him spending seven
months on the run in France with the stolen money, Bolton Crown Court
heard.
He was on the point of suicide when a call he made from a French hotel
was answered by his elder daughter Jenni, 13, and Mrs Lumb, who told him
they loved him and begged him to come home.
Lumb, of Chestnut Drive, Rawtenstall, Lancashire, who took the money
from a NatWest branch in Bolton, was told by Judge Michael Lever, QC,
that the sentence was the least he could pass on someone who had
breached the trust of their employers and stolen a large sum.
After the case, Lumb's solicitor Mr John Potter said Mrs Lumb was
behind her husband ''one hundred per cent''.
''She is a very, very impressive person,'' he said. ''If anyone can
emerge with credit from a situation like this, it is her. He has her
total support.''
Defence counsel Mr Phillip Curran told the court that the family --
the couple have a second daughter, Nicole, 11 -- were ''closer than
ever'' since Lumb returned home last Christmas.
His debts, after borrowing on up to a dozen different credit cards,
had triggered his breakdown and led to him fleeing the country.
The banker had pleaded guilty to stealing the #94,050 at an earlier
hearing.
Sentencing him after reading psychiatric and medical reports, the
judge told Lumb he took into account the ''extraordinary circumstances''
which led him to flee not only his responsibilities but his entire
lifestyle for a ''nomadic existence'' in France.
The court heard he toured France, visiting places where he and his
family had holidayed. He posted sums of cash and letters back home --
and had now repaid all but #120 of the stolen money. Around #55,000 was
sent back from abroad and he had been given another #25,000 by his
mother-in-law to reimburse the bank.
The judge told Lumb, who had worked for NatWest for 20 years before
they sacked him after his return, that he took account of his guilty
plea, his remorse and the fact that his career was over. He had brought
disgrace on himself and suffering on his family.
He said Lumb's mind must have been in ''turmoil'' during his time in
France and his actions had been illogical.
''However, despite these highly individual features, the fact of the
matter at the end of the day is that the central facts are simple and
stark,'' he said.
''You were an assistant bank manager and you stole nearly #100,000
from your employers. It is a serious case and my duty is to reflect
that.''
</TEXT>
