<HEADLINE>Loch anglers worried by algae 'thick as green paint'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ELIZABETH BUIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321694</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TOXIC algae as thick as green paint in sections has spread from
Soulseat Loch, near Stranraer, to the Piltanton Burn in the first major
algal pollution incident of this kind in flowing water.
Members of the Dunragit Angling Club plan to demand compensation if
fishing on the Piltanton Burn is affected by the algae, which they claim
has now moved seven miles from the source at Soulseat Loch.
Committee member Angus McLean said: ''There was serious pollution in
the Piltanton four or five years ago and it has just recovered. We have
restocked the burn since that time. Fish migrate to this burn and we are
expecting a run of fish at the end of June. If the burn is polluted the
fish will not come in.''
The club faced a considerable financial loss if existing fish were
poisoned and others did not spawn because of the algae, said Mr McLean.
Notices are posted around the Soulseat Loch, which is owned by Stair
Estates, warning anglers and farmers of the potential danger.
Mr Bill Affleck, depute director of environmental health at Wigtown
District Council, said: ''If you drank the water, it could make you very
ill. It could be fatal. It could cause skin or eye irritations and
rashes. Some days it is toxic, some days it is not.''
The algae in this case has been named as oscillatoria, but the loch
has a long history of algal problems, although the recent pollution is
thought to have been exacerbated by the use of phosphates in
agricultural fertilisers and recent mild winters. Monks in Soulseat
Abbey, which dates from the twelfth century, referred to the loch as the
''green stank''. The recent incursion into the Piltanton Burn is being
attributed to strong northerly winds which have blown the algal blooms
across the loch.
Dr Alastair Stephen, fisheries biologist with the West Galloway
Fisheries Trust, said: ''It looks like green paint -- it is incredibly
thick. In a loch like this you would expect to have a lot of plant
growth in it. But there is not because the light is precluded from
getting to the bottom because of the algae.''
One possibility being considered by the Solway River Purification
Board is the use of barley straw which gives off toxins which damage
algal growth, but this would take a number of years to be effective.
''The Stranraer and District Angling Club added a lot of copper
sulphate a few years ago. It kills the algae but causes another severe
problem in that the copper builds up in the sediment and that is toxic
to the plantlife,'' said Dr Stephen.
Soulseat Loch is stocked with rainbow trout and so far there have been
no reports of dead fish, although two cattle are believed to have died
recently and six calves last year after drinking water from the loch.
Mr Stuart Coy, area inspector for the Solway River Purification Board,
who has called a meeting of interested parties today, said: ''We are
talking about a very serious algal problem, probably of largely natural
origin, although there is an anthropogenic element. It is the same as
the Loch Leven problem a few years ago, although a different algae, I
believe.''
He went on:''There is no easy answer. This loch has had an algal
problem going back to medieval times. It is a naturally fertile water
with a very high level of natural phosphates.''
</TEXT>
