<HEADLINE>MPs angry as #10m pledged to set up new water boards</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RON MACKENNA</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>978321695</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government's decision to allocate almost #10m to the setting up of
three new water boards in Scotland provoked fury from opposition MPs
last night.
SNP leader Alex Salmond described the figure as a ''scandal'' when
compared to the #36m which has been set aside to fund Scotland's 29 new
councils.
The leader of Strathclyde Regional Council, Mr Bob Gould, warned that
the cash could be used to fatten up boards for privatisation at some
point in the future.
The figure of #9.7m was revealed by Scottish Office Local Government
Minister George Kynoch in response to a parliamentary question from Mr
Salmond.
Mr Salmond said later: ''The Tories are throwing money at their pet
project and at the same time starving the new councils of desperately
needed cash.
''While the new boards must think Christmas has come early, Scotland's
new councils have been given a shoestring budget to get themselves off
the ground.
''An average of #1.2m has been given to each of the new councils while
nearly #10m has been given to provide just one service. Yet again the
Tories have got their priorities wrong.
''They are willing to splash out millions removing Scotland's most
precious asset from public control while implementing cuts in local
government funding which have jeopardised vital services the length and
breadth of Scotland.''
Councillor Gould, who will next year become the leader of the new
Glasgow City Council, said Labour had been warning for years that the
Government would pull out all the stops to fund water boards.
''If we asked for that sort of money for a similar thing we would be
told to get lost,'' he said. ''It is clear the Government are trying to
buy their way into the system.
''I believe that privatisation is one of the goals and this may be
their way of making water boards more attractive. If they win the next
election then I have no doubt the boards will be privatised.
''One of the reasons for this unusually large amount of money is to
try and convince people that they would get better value if they went
down a certain road.''
A spokesman for the Scottish Office said last night that the
allocation was not excessive, adding: ''Comparing the new councils with
water boards is not a valid comparison.
''This money will be used to set up three boards to cover the whole of
the country. There are 29 new councils in Scotland.
''The funding is to allow the setting up of the new authorities that
will include money to get premises, recruit staff and buy equipment.''
</TEXT>
