<HEADLINE>Appeal lodged over second jury award to sportsman</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRUCE MCKAIN, LAW CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321697</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE case of a former clay-pigeon shooting champion who has twice won
large damages awards may have to go back to a jury for a third time.
Last week, a jury at the Court of Session awarded #165,500 to Mr David
Girvan, a five-times Scottish champion, European champion and a
Commonwealth Games bronze-medallist whose sporting career was ended by
an elbow injury.
Mr Girvan, 45, from Glenmoriston in Inverness-shire, raised a #250,000
damages action following an accident near his home in which a van ran
into his Land Rover. He suffered a serious fracture and dislocation of
his right elbow which ended his competitive career as a clay pigeon
shooter.
Out of the total damages, the jury awarded #95,000 for solatium, or
pain and suffering.
Last week's decision followed an earlier jury award of #193,000
(#120,000 for solatium) which went to a second jury after three Appeal
Court judges described the amount as ''wholly extravagant''.
Appeal from the verdict of a civil jury takes the form of a new trial
and Inverness Farmers' Dairy of Lochalsh Road, Inverness, the company
being sued by Mr Girvan, has now lodged another appeal.
The company will argue that although last week's damages award is
lower than the first, it is still too high.
The case has illustrated the wide gap between the attitude of judges
and juries in Scotland over appropriate levels of damages.
The jury's latest award for pain and suffering to Mr Girvan, is only
#20,000 less than the record payout by a judge for a woman paralysed
from the neck down after road accident.
In December last year Lord Penrose made a solatium award of #115,000
to quadriplegic Mrs Elizabeth Martin, who suffered catastrophic injuries
after a lorry ploughed into the back of her parked car. The highest
award by a Scottish judge for pain and suffering for a paraplegic is
believed to be #70,000.
In allowing the first retrial in Mr Girvan's case, Lord Ross, the Lord
Justice Clerk, said it was quite clear that the solatium award of
#120,000 was quite out of line with anything which had been awarded in
the past.
The appeal judges were told that the largest previous Scottish award
for an injury of the type suffered by Mr Girvan was #15,000.
Counsel for Mr Girvan argued that a judge in England might have
awarded about #40,000 for pain and suffering in a case like this and in
Mr Girvan's case it should be higher because of his inability to compete
any longer at the highest level of clay-pigeon shooting.
Reference was also made to huge libel awards in England and the large
pay-outs to pregnant ex-servicewomen.
Unless the two sides can reach agreement on the level of damages,
there is, in theory, no limit to the number of times the case could go
back to a jury.
</TEXT>
