<HEADLINE>Nurses urge change in law to protect prostitutes</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321700</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NURSES have called on the Government to decriminalise prostitution to
protect the health and safety of women and children.
Members of the Royal College of Nursing's annual congress yesterday
voted by an overwhelming majority to instruct their leaders to press for
a change in the law.
The move was prompted by worries that prostitutes and their children
are suffering discrimination.
The vote -- following this week's decision to tear up the college's
no-strike rule -- further shatters the RCN's traditionally moderate
image.
Voting was 381 for, with 55 against, and 44 abstentions -- a 79%
majority.
Under the law as it stands, it is not illegal to be a prostitute, but
it is to solicit, keep a brothel, or live off the earnings of others
selling sex.
RCN delegates were told of evidence that prostitutes are being denied
proper health care, including fertility treatment.
Ms Robbi Robson, assistant director of RCN policy, said all too often
there was a belief that if you were a prostitute you were a bad woman
and bad mother, but this was not true.
However, because of this belief, children of prostitutes were being
taken into care.
Ms Robson said the RCN wanted male and female prostitutes to have
access to non-discriminatory health services.
At the moment, many feared that by going to hospital their names might
be passed on to police. This fear was so great that even women who had
been severely beaten were reluctant to attend hospital.
Mrs Julia Fearon, of the RCN's Society of Paediatric Nursing, said
that decriminalisation would enable regulation of prostition and
licensing of brothels. By licensing brothels, anti-drug policies and
minimum age limits could be introduced.
She said: ''Decriminalisation will not solve the problems of poverty,
but we believe that it would help reduce some of the discrimination
women, men, girls and boys who prostitute, currently face.''
Delegates heard that between 1989 and 1994 there was a 35% increase in
the number of girls under 16 cautioned for soliciting.
Mrs Gayle Trotter, a worker in a Scottish outreach clinic for
prostitutes, said: ''The law is colluding with prostitutes because women
are cautioned, fined, and have to go back on the street to pay the fine.
I see this cycle of entrapment reported every night.''
Mrs Liz Rees, one of the few who spoke against the resolution, warned
that it could lead to more people becoming prosititutes. She claimed
decriminalisation should ''remain the English Collective of Prostitute's
cause, not the RCN's''.
</TEXT>
