<HEADLINE>MP steps into custody battle</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>978321701</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A LABOUR MP has written to the Secretary of State for Scotland, Ian
Lang, urging him to prevent a 14-month-old child at the centre of an
international custody dispute being taken back to Spain.
Ms Catherine Johnston, 25, of Craigendmuir Park, Stepps, is fighting
to keep her daughter Lucia Cortes in Scotland.
Mr Tom Clarke, the MP for Monklands West, said there should be no
attempt to take Lucia to Spain until the matter is raised at Scottish
Questions in the House of Commons on Wednesday.
But the girl's father Mr Jose Cortes is demanding access to Lucia
after Ms Johnston took her from Spain. Mr Cortes has been backed up by a
Court of Session ruling last month that Lucia's removal was unlawful.
Mr Clarke raised the matter at Business Questions in the Commons
yesterday. He asked the Leader of the House, Mr Tony Newton, to allow a
debate on the matter.
Mr Clarke said the well-being of the child -- as laid down in the 1989
Children Act and the Children (Scotland) Bill currently being debated --
would not be ensured if she was taken away from her mother, kept in
custody and put on a plane without any members of her family.
In the letter he said: ''The Leader of the House referred me to
Scottish Questions on Wednesday, May 24, and agreed to bring the matter
to your attention.
''Can I therefore have your assurance that you will ensure no action
is taken by sheriff officers in my constituent's case before then?''
Lord Cullen, sitting at the Court of Session on Wednesday, ruled that
court officers could remove Lucia from the country.
But Mr Clarke said: ''Mr Newton is a fellow Cabinet member of Mr Lang
so it is important that he has made this statement. Mr Lang should deal
with this at Scottish Questions as Mr Newton suggested.''
He said that would give Ms Johnston a respite from the threat of court
officers removing Lucia.
Mr Cortes, 36, speaking from Benidorm, said last night: ''I hope to be
reunited with my little girl in the next few days, possibly as soon as
this weekend -- but I'm not certain.''
He added: ''I want to give my side of this problem. But I've been
'handcuffed' by my lawyers. They have told me not to say anything until
this matter has been resolved.''
But Mr Cortes did make one promise. He said: ''I will obey whatever
decision the courts make. I just want to be close to my daughter
sometimes.''
</TEXT>
