<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000158</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000158</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Healthy outlook for jobs boost in the Highlands</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321702</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Highlands are poised to win much-needed new jobs with the prospect
of an international bio-medical company building a research and
manufacturing base in Inverness.
The multi-million pound development would be the biggest hi-tech
manufacturing deal ever brought to the North of Scotland.
It would create around 375 jobs over five years as well as substantial
spin-off employment.
However, the firm is working to a tight schedule and any delays caused
by red tape could mean the opportunity being lost.
The deal, now about 95% certain, has been won by development agency
Highlands and Islands Enterprise, working with Locate in Scotland and
Inverness and Nairn Enterprise.
HIE has asked Highland Regional Council to arrange an emergency
planning committee meeting next month in a bid to rush through the
application.
The identity of the company has not been revealed, but it is based
abroad and already has an operation in England. It is understood to be
keen to begin manufacturing in Inverness by the turn of the year.
If successful, the deal will be a major coup for the Highlands which
will have beaten off fierce competition from home and overseas.
A significant factor has been the availability of land next to
Raigmore Hospital in Inverness, the biggest general hospital in the
Highlands.
An HIE spokesman said yesterday the deal remained a ''firm prospect''
and said he was confident the firm's deadlines could be met if the
planning hurdle can be cleared.
''If key procedures including planning permission are cleared quickly,
the requisite construction and other steps to meet deadlines for
commencing production can be met.''
It is believed several dozen office, manufacturing and laboratory jobs
would be created immediately with the figure rising to around 375 within
five years.
The HIE spokesman added the proposal is in line with the local
enterprise company's strategy to develop complementary businesses beside
the specialist facilities at Raigmore.
Only last month a conference in Inverness heard the medical sector was
a potential growth area for the Highlands.
Raigmore Hospital serves an area the size of Belgium and is well
positioned to benefit from spin-off industries.
A Highland Regional Council spokesman confirmed a special meeting of
the planning committee will be held on June 14 to consider the
development.
''The request for an early meeting was granted by senior officials who
recognised the importance of the application and the need to consider it
speedily.''
</TEXT>
