<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000161</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000161</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Doctors link skin cancer risks and sunbeds</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN MACDERMID, MEDICAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321705</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FITNESS centres that offer the use of sunbeds may be putting health
enthusiasts at risk of skin cancer, doctors warned yesterday.
Consultant dermatologist Dr Margaret Price revealed she now sees
around 50 cases of skin cancer each year and the numbers are rising.
''Many gyms and fitness centres where you can go for step aerobics
also advertise sunbeds. It is giving people a double message that they
are healthy,'' she said.
''We are now seeing about one case a week of the most dangerous type
of skin cancer, malignant melanoma,'' said Dr Price, who practises in
Brighton.
Health Education Authority research showed young people, mainly women
in the 16-24 age group, were the biggest sunbed fans. Almost one in four
spends longer than the recommended two courses of 10 sessions per year
on UVA sunbeds.
The alert about overuse of sunbeds is disclosed in the British Medical
Journal. The problem revealed by the HEA survey on attitudes is that
most adults and children interviewed felt sunshine in Britain posed
little risk.
Sunbeds are designed to produce a tan by giving off UVA radiation,
which was thought until recently to be a safe form of radiation, with
the tan produced by a sunbed a safe tan.
But now it is known this is not the case. UVA ages the skin
prematurely and contributes to potentially fatal cancers.
Ms Katie Aston, manager of the Health Education Authority's skin
cancer campaign said: ''In light of this new research, the public needs
more information about the risks of using sunbeds.
''We would hope very much that the manufacturers will take this
opportunity to consult with medical and other health professionals to
ensure that sunbed users have the most accurate information available
when deciding whether or not to have a sunbed session.''
The HEA recommends that some people should never use sunbeds. These
include the under 16s, people who burn easily or tan poorly, people
using drugs or cosmetics known to be photo-sensitising or people who
have had skin cancer.
The results show:
* Serious attempts to tan seem to start from the teenage years
onwards.
* Younger children aged eight to 12 liked their appearance when
tanned, but found it boring and uncomfortable to lie in the sun for a
long time.
* Most people, particularly teenagers, believed they look sexier and
feel better with a tan.
* Large expanses of white skin are associated with ill-health and a
general lack of vitality.
</TEXT>
