<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000162</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000162</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Chinook crash report 'not ready'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321706</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE official report into the RAF Chinook helicopter crash which killed
top counter-terrorism experts will not be published before a memorial
service for the victims.
While RAF chiefs agree that it would have been ''insensitive'' to make
public the report -- expected to blame pilot error for the horrific
accident -- before the service, a spokesman said yesterday it had not
yet been completed.
The elite of Britain's intelligence community and relatives of the
dead will gather in private for a service at the Army barracks chapel at
Lisburn in Northern Ireland on June 1.
Relatives will then be flown to the Mull of Kintyre for a solemn
pilgrimage to the small cairn of stones marking the spot where the
helicopter crashed on June 2 last year.
Twenty-five of the principal strategists in Britain's fight against
terrorism were killed, along with the four crew on the flight from
Northern Ireland to Scotland.
The long-awaited RAF Board of Inquiry report has been complicated by
two primary factors -- there was no ''black box'' flight recorder and
no-one survived to provide an eyewitness account.
The sensitive reportis understood to focus on why the pilot was flying
so low when approaching a mountainous area.
Conditions were difficult and experts were immediately baffled as to
why the pilot had not approached the coast at a safe altitude.
It is believed the report will explain that the helicopter crew had
lost their bearings and were not flying where they thought they were.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000163</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000163</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>New Solicitor-General</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>978321707</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MR DONALD Mackay, QC, was installed as Solicitor-General for Scotland
yesterday, in succession to Lord Dawson who has been elevated to the
Bench.
Mr Mackay, 49, was educated at George Watson's College in Edinburgh
and graduated in law from Edinburgh University. He also has a degree
from the University of Virginia.
He qualified as a solicitor in 1971 and became a partner in the
Edinburgh law firm of Allan McDougall and Co.
Mr Mackay was called to the Bar in 1976 and was an advocate-depute
from 1982 to 1985. He became a QC in 1987 and was a member of the
Criminal Injuries Compensation Board from 1989.
He is married with a son and two daughters.
</TEXT>
