<DOCNO>GH950519-000164</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000164</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>#750 for hanged teenager's son</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321708</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE girlfriend of a teenager who hanged himself in a police cell
yesterday won #750 damages for their baby son.
Miss Mary Stewart had claimed #15,000 from the Chief Constable of Fife
over the death of Mr Colin Davidson for the child she was pregnant with
when he died. The boy is now five-years-old.
Miss Stewart, of Green Street, Dunfermline, in Fife, had also sought
#20,000 damages for herself, but a civil jury at the Court of Session
made her no award.
The 12-strong jury decided that the proportion of blame for the death
of Mr Davidson, 19, in police custody at Dunfermline Police Station in
April 1989 lay 95% with the youth himself.
The mother of the dead teenager, Mrs Helen Davidson, 57, of Wedderburn
Crescent, in Dunfermline was awarded #500 damages. She had claimed
#10,000.
The family had claimed that Mr Davidson should have been treated as a
suicide risk when he was taken into police custody on charges involving
the assault of a 73-year-old woman.
Fife police disputed the action, before Lord Hamilton, and alleged the
youth died because of his own voluntary conduct.
</TEXT>
