<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000165</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000165</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Warming news from Iceland on jobs front</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CALUM MACDONALD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321709</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FROZEN foods chain Iceland, yesterday announced major expansion plans
which could mean the creation of up to 500 jobs in Scotland over the
next five years.
Company chairman Mr Malcolm Walker told shareholders that he expected
to open more than 50 stores in the UK every year for the foreseeable
future, doubling its number of shops and adding 5000 staff.
However, the bullish forecast from Iceland was undermined by
yesterday's announcement that one of Britain's long-established life
assurance companies, London Life, is cutting 460 jobs and is no longer
seeking new business.
Most observers will regard the mixed news as symptomatic of the UK
economy: many of the Iceland jobs will be part-time and relatively
unskilled, while the downgrading of London Life, founded almost two
centuries ago, is another example of severe pruning in the financial
sector.
The Bristol-based company's Scottish regional headquarters in Glasgow
is to close, with the loss of nine jobs. Staff have been offered a
number of options, including voluntary redundancy and transfer to sister
firms.
London Life policy-holders have been assured that their investments
are ''absolutely safe''. All existing contractual rights would continue
to be met in full, said a spokeswoman.
Meanwhile, at Iceland's annual meeting in Wales, Mr Walker said the
chain had opened 20 new shops already this year, and expected to reach a
total of 55 by the end of 1995, including about eight more in Scotland.
''Our planned growth will create an additional 1000 jobs this year,
and more than 5000 by the end of the century. This will include the
creation of around 60 store management positions each year.''
Iceland trades from 723 stores, including about 60 in Scotland, but
has identified a further 800 potential sites where it hopes to tap
consumer demand.
It already employs 17,000 staff, and boasts three million regular
customers. Last year, with a turnover of #1300m, it had an operating
profit of #74m.
Yesterday's announcement was the latest chapter in the success story
of Malcolm Walker, who launched his first store in 1970 in Oswestry,
Shropshire. The company took over the rival Bejam chain in 1989, and has
been expanding ever since.
The annual meeting was told that Iceland proposed a 25% increase in
dividends for 1995.
</TEXT>
