<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>'Citizen Smith' petrol-bomb attack</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRUCE MCKAIN, LAW CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>978321712</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THREE men, likened to Citizen Smith radicals after trying to put their
housing scheme on the map with a petrol-bomb attack on a kebab shop,
were remanded in custody yesterday.
The High Court in Edinburgh was told that an outbreak of civil unrest
had led to improved facilities in another part of town and the men
believed that by damaging property they could achieve similar benefits
for their own area.
David Graham, 23, of Muirhouse Drive, Edinburgh, admitted that between
August 12 and 14 last year he assembled incendiary devices with intent
to cause an explosion.
John Gilmour, 20, and Kevin Williamson, 18, also of Muirhouse Drive,
admitted that on August 13 they petrol-bombed a shop in Pennywell Court,
Edinburgh, endangering the lives of two workers there and damaging the
premises.
Mr Paul McBride, Advocate-depute, told the court that on the afternoon
of August 13 Graham had 10 petrol bombs at his home and discussed with a
number of others the possibility of a riot to ''put Muirhouse on the
map'' and ''give Muirhouse a name''.
Later that night, Gilmour and Williamson left the house, each with a
petrol bomb, and made their way to the kebab shop.
Gilmour walked in and threw his bottle at the wall. The bottle
exploded and the counter caught fire. Williamson was outside at the back
of the shop throwing his bottle at the wall.
The two workers, Shamim Saeed and Mohammed Gouse, fled. They were not
injured, but the shop suffered #24,000 damage.
Mr McBride emphasised that there was no suggestion of any racial
motive for the attack on the shop.
Mr Gary Allan, defending Graham, said the discussion at his client's
house had been about the Muirhouse area lacking many of the facilities
which had recently been provided in Pilton after some civil unrest. It
appeared to the group that the civil unrest had prompted action by the
authorities.
''Graham had the misguided belief that that by causing some signficant
damage to property, the authorities would in some way be compelled to
spend money refurbishing Muirhouse,'' he said.
Lord Johnston asked whether it was some kind of revolutionary
activity, but Mr Allan said that was a somewhat dramatic description.
''One is put in mind more of the television programme Citizen Smith
about a misguided radical whose attempts at achieving anything were
somewhat pathetic. The tragedy of this matter is that Graham took some
overt steps to do something about it.''
He added that the intention was to damage property, not endanger life.
Lord Johnston remanded all three in custody until June 2 for
background reports.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000169</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000169</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pledge on Scottish HQ as purchase makes Britain's biggest brewer. S&amp;N to take Courage in #425m deal</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>978321713</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH &amp; Newcastle is set to become Britain's biggest brewer, with
the purchase of Courage for #425m to form Scottish Courage as its beer
division.
Once the smallest of the Big Six brewers, S&amp;N will now have annual
beer sales of more than #2200m and have a market share appreciably
higher than that of the long time industry leader, Bass, which owns the
Tennent's and Carling brands.
Shareholders are being asked to put up #354m.
S&amp;N is buying Courage, Britain's second biggest brewer, from Foster's
Brewing Group of Australia to realise a dream that began as long ago as
1968, when S&amp;N and Courage had exploratory talks about the possibilities
of a merger.
The main assets being acquired include six breweries, the Foster's
brands for Britain and Europe and also the Courage names.
Chief executive Mr Brian Stewart said yesterday that there were a lot
of synergy benefits in putting the two companies together and that they
were complementary.
The deal has to be approved by regulatory authorities, including the
Office of Fair Trading, with completion expected in July.
Mr Stewart said that there would be rationalisation, but he could not
give the numbers involved at present.
He added that, although attention naturally focuses on the brewing
side, about 75% of employees are involved in the packaging, warehousing
and distribution activities.
Altogether, the two companies employ 9500 in brewing, with S&amp;N having
4500 and Courage 5000 workers.
It is possible that just over 1000 jobs could be lost.
The risk to employment in Scotland appears to be minimal, with the
cost-cutting and reorganisation expected to generate #40m of savings
annually from 1997.
S&amp;N has five breweries -- at Edinburgh, Newcastle, Marsham -- which
makes Theakston's -- Manchester and Nottingham.
The Courage breweries are situated in Bristol, Cork (Beamish stout),
Reading, Tadcaster and Halifax as well as a half-interest in the
Mortlake brewery on the Thames where Budweiser is brewed under licence
from Anheuser Busch.
Any brewery closures would seem likely to involve Courage at Halifax,
which has been at risk for some time, and S&amp;N's Home Brewery in
Nottingham.
The geographic areas of overlap are mostly in Yorkshire and to some
extent the north-east of England, where there will be reductions on the
distribution side.
Mr Stewart emphasised that, while Scottish Courage would maintain a
''significant presence'' in the south of England, it would be ''firmly
headquartered in Edinburgh -- unlike Guinness''.
He added: ''I don't want to see Scottishness eroded, nor see the
Courage identity lost.''
Courage has had a complicated career since it ceased to be a
family-controlled company. It was taken over by Imperial Tobacco in
1971, which in turn was acquired by Hanson.
Lord Hanson sold it to Foster's, which then split the company up in a
deal with Grand Metropolitan, whereby Foster's took the breweries and
the pubs were put into a jointly-owned company named Inntrepreneurial
Estates Limited.
In 1988 and 1989 Foster's tried to take over S&amp;N, but was thwarted by
the Monopolies Commission.
The reasoning behind the Courage deal is that both companies are
particularly strong in brands, with S&amp;B contributing McEwans,
Theakston's, Beck's and Coors while Courage brings in Miller,
Kronenbourg, Holsten and the omnipresent Foster's as well as Webster's
Yorkshire Bitter.
Brand strength is important, with both brewers seeing increases in
volume at present in contrast to the industry's overall decline --
Courage claims 3% gain.
Measured by consumption, Scottish Courage will have a 25% ''share of
throat'' -- the new term for beer market share which compares with
around 19% for Bass.
However, the Office of Fair Trading may be more interested in the more
traditional measurement of beer production where S&amp;N's 13% has to be
added to the 18% of Courage to make 31% and with the OFT unhappy about
any merger which results in more than 25% market control.
When Fosters was bidding for S&amp;N, the defence was that any takeover
would limit consumer choice as well as lose 3000 jobs.
Yesterday, Mr Stewart said that times had changed and that the beer
market had opened up as a result of the Beer Orders which limited the
number of pubs the big brewers could own.
In addition, competition from imports through Calais now amounted to
5% of the UK market.
TheCampaign for Real Ale (Camra) has demanded an immediate reference
to the Monopolies Commission. Campaigns manager Mr Steve Cox said:
''This merger is grossly anti-competitive. It will give one brewer up to
one-third of the UK market.''
S&amp;N's Mr Stewart claimed that the acquisition of the Courage business
offers a unique opportunity to achieve many strategic initiatives at a
single step and will provide a strong base for growth in the UK and
continental Europe.
The brand owners, including Anheuser Busch, have all agreed to stay
with the enlarged company. There had been speculation that some would be
unhappy about the conflict of interest between certain lager brands.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000170</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000170</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Jail for footballer who kicked ref</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN HUNTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321714</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A FOOTBALLER was ordered to serve a 90-day jail sentence yesterday for
an attack on a referee. He has also been banned from playing the game
for 50 years.
Richard Anderson, 26, of Clunie Road, Dunfermline, Fife, admitted
assaulting a referee during a Sunday match. His lawyers challenged the
sentence at the Justiciary Appeal Court in Edinburgh yesterday claiming
that the sentence imposed on the player was excessive.
They had claimed that the sentencing sheriff ''failed to take account
of the fact that this incident happened during the course of a football
game and as a result the accused was banned from playing football for 50
years''.
Anderson admitted assaulting referee Mr Andrew Watson at a pitch at
Launcherhead Road, Lochgelly, in Fife, by kicking him on the legs on
September 25 last year, when he earlier appeared at Dunfermline Sheriff
Court.
He was sentenced to 90 days' imprisonment, but was released on bail
pending his appeal against the sentence yesterday.
Three appeal judges heard that the referee in the Sunday league
fixture noticed that several players, who were under the influence of
alcohol, were involved in dangerous tackles.
He decided to abandon the fixture after only 16 minutes, but Anderson
''took umbrage'' at this, Sheriff John Forbes said in a report.
The referee was about to show Anderson a red card, but as the match
official turned his back Anderson kicked him on the back of his legs.
Anderson's counsel, Miss Margaret Scott, told the court that it was
clear during the game that her client's team had been in the pub before
kick-off.
She stressed that the referee did not need medical attention. Lord
Allanbridge, who chaired the appeal court bench, pointed out that
Anderson had eight previous convictions for assault, which included a
six-month jail sentence in 1992.
The judges said they were satisfied in the circumstances of the case
that the jail sentence imposed was appropriate.
The team Anderson was playing for was disbanded shortly after the
incident, writes Alan Hunter.
The incident took place durings a Sunday Welfare League match when he
was playing for Dunfermline's Glen Gates FC against Lochgelly Minto,
another local pub team, at Lochgelly's Launcherhead Park.
The decision on the referee's report, submitted to the executive
committee of Dunfermline Welfare League, was later sent to the Scottish
Sunday Welfare Football Association, which ratified the ban.
Lochgelly Minto's secretary, Mr Walter Moodie, added yesterday: ''It
was the first time we had played them, and you could say it was quite a
match.
''I learned later that the other club folded because they could not
get players, although some are playing with other clubs in the league.
''It is hardly likely that the player would want to play football
again in his seventies.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000171</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000171</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sinn Fein leader's cousin is jailed</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321715</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A COUSIN of Sinn Fein president Gerry Adams was jailed for 25 years
yesterday for conspiracy to murder.
Belfast Crown Court had heard David John Adams, 36, of Bunbeg Park,
Belfast, was arrested with two other men in Belfast in February 1994
when police stopped a hijacked van.
Two rifles, a pistol, and a coffee-jar bomb were found at the scene.
Robert Crawford, 37, and Paul Stitt, 24, both of Belfast, were also
convicted of conspiracy to murder.
</TEXT>
