<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000172</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000172</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Five-star magic on the menu for a quiet wedding</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ELIZABETH BUIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>978321716</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GLASGOW'S renowned restaurateur and hotelier, Ken McCulloch, could
have held his reception in one of his own establishments -- One
Devonshire Gardens, for instance, or Malmaison.
Instead, he and his bride, Amanda Rosa, an interior designer, chose to
slip away to Crinan.
''We chose Crinan because we want somewhere very special to us. It was
quiet and you could not have found a more magical place in the world,''
he said.
The bride, of Italian parentage, comes from Dumfries and studied
design at Dundee.
The couple married at the church at the nearby estate owned by the
Marquis of Poltallach, and held a reception for 18 close family members
at Crinan Hotel.
What had the groom chosen for the wedding breakfast? ''Fresh seafood
from Crinan, landed today. You couldn't get any better than that.''
</TEXT>
