<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950519-000173</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950519-000173</DOCID>
<DATE>950519</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Adams and Mayhew to meet in US</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GEOFFREY PARKHOUSE, POLITICAL EDITOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>978321717</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Prime Minister has authorised a meeting between his Northern
Ireland Secretary Sir Patrick Mayhew and Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams in
Washington next Wednesday.
It will be the first publicly acknowledged meeting for 70 years
between a Cabinet Minister and Sinn Fein.
Ulster Unionist leader Jim Molyneaux and Mr John Hume of the SDLP were
informed of this decision when they left a joint meeting with the Prime
Minister in his office at the Commons yesterday -- a meeting which in
itself was historic. It is the first time in 25 years that the Ulster
Unionists and the SDLP have co-operated in this way.
Sir Patrick, announcing that he intends to ask Mr Adams to meet him in
Washington on Wednesday when the two of them are attending an investment
conference for Northern Ireland, said he is asking Mr Adams to meet him
''informally'' as early as possible at the conference.
Twenty-four hours earlier No. 10 was saying only that they might bump
into each other at the conference. The meeting has now been upgraded in
a significant way to give a boost to the peace process.
Sir Patrick explained the purpose of his request for a meeting with Mr
Adams at the conference which President Bill Clinton will also attend:
''Economic progress for Northern Ireland, including especially inward
investment, depends crucially on the permanence of peace and on people's
confidence that peace is truly permanent.
''My purpose will be to explain this and to say that public confidence
in the permanence of peace requires, among other important matters,
substantial progress on the decommissioning of arms held by paramilitary
organisations who have declared that violence is at an end.
''I shall make clear again that substantive political talks with Sinn
Fein will only be possible when there is a satisfactory outcome to
exploratory dialogue, including the progress on decommissioning which we
have already publicly stated to be necessary. I shall look to Mr Adams
to respond positively to this.''
This puts the peace process ball back in the hands of Mr Adams who has
been demanding a meeting with the Northern Ireland Secretary in parallel
with talks being held by Mr Michael Ancram, the negotiating Minister,
and Sinn Fein's Martin McGuinness.
The joint meeting of Mr Molyneaux and Mr Hume with Mr Major in the
Commons last night dealt with social and economic matters in Northern
Ireland and the presentation to be put in Washington next week to
encourage American inward investment.
Both sides emerged pleased with the meeting which confirmed that
electricity prices in Northern Ireland will receive sympathetic
treatment and that water privatisation will not take place there ''in
the lifetime of this parliament''.
The Ulster Unionists and the SDLP were surprised to be told on their
way out from the Prime Minister's office in the Commons about the
intention to conduct a meeting with Mr Adams next week.
The Unionists have been privately reconciled to a meeting between Mr
Adams and the Secretary of State for some time, despite their worries
that Sinn Fein will be allowed into political negotiations without
having handed over any weapons.
But the meeting was condemned by Ulster Unionist MP for South Belfast,
the Rev Martin Smyth.
He said that by giving the impression he would not talk to Sinn Fein
until the IRA had begun giving up its weapons, Sir Patrick was left
looking weak and untrustworthy now he had agreed to meet Mr Adams.
Mr Molyneaux was last night reported to be considering pulling out of
the US conference because of Sir Patrick's decision to meet Mr Adams.
Mr Molyneaux said: ''It looks as if this was Washington-driven, the
whole story broke in Washington first.
Pressure was put on Sir Patrick and ''he had very little option --
that is not to say I agree with the decision'', he added.
Mr Peter Robinson, deputy leader of the Democratic Unionist Party,
said: ''This despicable Government has no principles, no bottom line and
no conception of the outrage and anger within the Unionist community
arising from their serial betrayals.''
''The IRA maintains their firepower, they keep their bloody murder
gangs in place and this excuse for a Government Minister prostrates
himself before their front man.''
Mr Andrew Hunter, chairman of the Tory back bench Northern Ireland
committee, welcomed the meeting.
He insisted it would not detract from the process of exploratory
dialogue with Sinn Fein followed by substantive talks.
</TEXT>
