<HEADLINE>More cuts for Highland lines.</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAIN WILSON, CHIEF REPORTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321718</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE West Highland Line is to suffer cuts over and above the threatened
loss of the Fort William-London sleeper service, it was revealed last
night.
ScotRail confirmed that it is axing Glasgow-Oban and Glasgow-Fort
William special summer trains that have run for the past three years.
Their withdrawal in July and August was immediately interpreted by
critics as yet another threat to the line's long-term survival.
Additional summer services between Inverness, Thurso and Wick and
Inverness and Wick are also being withdrawn.
Highland Regional Council convener Duncan McPherson warned any
reduction in rail services in the area would be opposed.
The special West Highland Line trains left Glasgow Queen Street at
9.50am, ran to Oban on Mondays, Fridays, and Saturdays, and to Fort
William and Mallaig on Tuesdays, Wednesdays, and Thursdays.
Now summer visitors will have no choice but to use the ''normal
service'' -- the 8.12am to Fort William/Mallaig or the 8.42am to Oban.
The summer service withdrawal was confirmed with the publication of
ScotRail's summer timetable, which runs from May 28 to September 23. A
spokesman blamed the axe on ''disappointing loadings''.
A spokesman for the Scottish Tourist Board described the loss as
disappointing, and added that talks would be sought with ScotRail
management for a stay of execution.
He went on: ''Since the threat to sleepers, a number of people and
organisations have been looking at how West Highland services could be
better marketed and promoted.
''Our view is that people must use it or lose it. But to win
customers, ScotRail must market the line better. We need a breathing
space to see how it can be promoted.''
ScotRail also confirmed it is to stop using locomotive-hauled trains
because of ''financial constraints''. That means the old-fashioned
engines will be replaced with Sprinters on the West Highland Line and
between Inverness and Kyle of Lochalsh, and that Edinburgh-Inverness
summer locos will also be lost.
It would appear the battle to meet Government demands for 5% cuts in
the budget up to privatisation is on in earnest. Withdrawing special
trains will achieve savings, but not incur the wrath of the Office of
Passenger Rail Franchising, which set minimum levels of service for the
ScotRail network earlier this week.
Opraf insists its passenger service requirement -- which must be
adopted by the train operator -- will ''safeguard all current routes,
stations, and services'' over a seven-year period.
However, the new timetable included several other surprises, which
left ScotRail in a muddle in one case.
The document includes two midnight ''ghost trains'' to run over a
short stretch of track in Glasgow, allegedly being introduced to avoid
proper public consultation over the withdrawal of Fort William-London
sleepers.
Last night, Strathclyde Regional Council signalled there will be a
pre-emptive strike to ensure the 23.59 Maryhill-Bishopbriggs and 23.49
Cumbernauld-Glasgow trains never run.
The warning of legal action coincided with an embarrassing blunder in
the timetable over the controversial demise of all seated accommodation
on Anglo-Scottish sleepers from May 28.
ScotRail's response is that travellers can no longer look up the
timetable and regard the contents as sacrosanct.
The ''ghost trains'' are scheduled in the Great Britain Passenger
Railway Timetable, despite critical findings by Lord Kirkwood in the
Court of Session earlier this month.
He ruled they would be of no benefit to the travelling public; are
unlikely to carry any passengers, and are meant to circumvent public
consultation procedures.
A ScotRail spokesman was adamant the late-night trains will be
introduced from Monday, May 29. He stressed: ''We are obliged to run
what is in the timetable.''
However, the timetable also states overnight London-Edinburgh and
London-Inverness trains will be ''sleeping accommodation only''. No such
proviso is attached to London-Glasgow or London-Aberdeen overnight
services.
Silence greeted the question: ''Does that mean there will be seated
carriages on the Glasgow and Aberdeen trains -- after all, you are on
record saying that ScotRail is obliged 'to run what is in the
timetable?'''
A spokesman later described the failure to declare all overnight
trains as sleepers-only as ''an omission, a simple error,'' and added:
''There will definitely not be seated accommodation on any of the
sleepers from May 28.''
The timetable excludes the Fort William sleeper, although reprieved
after Lord Kirkwood granted an interdict to Highland Regional Council
preventing its withdrawal on May 28. BR has lodged an appeal, to be
heard on June 1.
The document also confirms the axing of all Motorail services and the
Glasgow-Plymouth and Carlisle-London sleepers because subsidies were
withdrawn by Opraf.
</TEXT>
