<HEADLINE>Nolan 'being sidelined'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHEN MCGREGOR, PARLIAMENTARY CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>978321719</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government appeared to sideline the recommendations of the Nolan
Committee into standards in public life yesterday.
The move followed angry reaction by senior Conservatives after Public
Services Minister David Hunt promised ''early action'' on Nolan
Committee recommendations governing the behaviour of MPs.
After a heated debate, leader of the Commons Tony Newton appeared to
soothe some Tory back benchers' fears by proposing a committee of senior
MPs to decide how best to implement proposed reforms over politicians'
conduct.
Winding up last night's debate, Mr Newton suggested that the
appropriate course was to ask ''senior and respected'' MPs to make
recommendations about how to proceed in the light of the Nolan report.
They would put forward specific proposals which might then be put to
MPs, he said, insisting this would be consistent with the House's normal
practice.
His comments came after senior Tories, led by former Prime Minister
Sir Edward Heath, lined up to warn the Government against taking ''panic
responses''.
But his comments, welcomed by Tories critical of Nolan recommendations
affecting their outside earnings, were seized on by the Opposition as
evidence of a cave-in.
Labour accused the Government of putting greed before the interests of
Parliament.
Earlier Mr David Hunt had told the Commons that some of the Nolan
recommendations would be implemented, but others would have to wait for
review.
His comments were reflected in angry Question Time exchanges between
the Prime Minister and Labour leader Tony Blair.
Mr Newton said the House needed a ''proper mechanism'' in place before
decisions could be taken, and that he had been encouraged by various
aspects of the debate which had signalled possible ways forward.
He said ''the devil was in the detail'' and then questioned whether an
existing committee or one established for the purpose of closer
examination would be the right course.
Mr Newton concluded: ''The latter would probably be preferable, not
least for the reason that the existing committees - the Privileges
Committee and the Members Interests Committee -- already have other work
on their plate the House would not like to see pushed aside.''
Mr Blair said the Prime Minister already had accepted the broad thrust
of the Nolan report. He questioned, however, whether the Prime Minister
accepted the recommendation that MPs with consultancies should disclose
the terms of their agreements and earnings
The Prime Minister made clear that the Government wanted to hear the
views of MPs and take them into account before reaching a conclusion. Mr
Blair responded that it sounded as if the Government might reject parts
of Nolan.
In the Commons debate on the report, Mr Hunt reflected the cautious
line. He said, for example, that the Government intended to implement
Lord Nolan's recommendation that proposals by former Ministers to take
up appointments after they leave public office should be brought within
the scope of an advisory committee on business appointments.
Mr Hunt told the House: ''Integrity must remain our watchword. We all
share the responsibility, in this House and elsewhere, for reinforcing
the public's confidence in public service.
''The Government will do everything necessary to ensure that the
quality of the British public service remains, and is clearly seen to
be, the best in the world.''
For Labour, front bench spokesman Mrs Ann Taylor said: ''No-one could,
should and I hope would condone a blanket condemnation of all MPs. It is
simply not the case that all MPs behave as badly as the few who have
brought this House into disrepute. But to imply there is no real problem
does our reputation no good whatsoever.''
</TEXT>
